/** Etymology data for lemma IDs in chunk 7 */
export const etymologyChunk7: Record<number, string> = {
  "3354": "مَسْكُوبٌ and related words stem from the root س-ك-ب, with the root verb سَكَبَ meaning \"he poured out\" or \"he caused to flow.\" مَسْكُوبٌ is a passive form meaning \"poured forth\" or \"flowing.\" The connection lies in the act of liquid being poured or flowing freely, directly relating to the root's emphasis on pouring. This term may describe abundant streams or blessings that flow continuously, symbolizing generosity, abundance, and the continuous grace of Allah (ﷻ) upon creation.",
  "3355": "مَسْكُونَةٌ and related words stem from the root س-ك-ن, with the root verb سَكَنَ meaning \"he dwelt,\" \"he resided,\" or \"he became still.\" مَسْكُونَةٌ is a passive form meaning \"inhabited\" or \"dwelt in.\" The term denotes a place that is inhabited or settled by people, directly connecting to the root's concept of dwelling and habitation. It highlights the idea of a community or area that provides stability and rest for its inhabitants, emphasizing the collective aspect of dwelling and the creation of a settled environment.",
  "3356": "مَسْنُونٌ and related words stem from the root س-ن-ن, with the root verb سَنَّ meaning \"he fashioned\" or \"he sharpened.\" مَسْنُونٌ means \"fashioned\" or \"molded.\" The connection is in the act of shaping or forming something with precision. In the Qur'anic context, it refers to humans being fashioned from clay, emphasizing deliberate creation and the artistry involved in forming life.",
  "3357": "مَشَىٰ and related words stem from the root م-ش-ي, with the root verb مَشَىٰ meaning \"he walked\" or \"he moved on foot.\" This term captures the fundamental human activity of walking, symbolizing movement, progression, and the journey through life. In classical Arabic, walking is often associated with deliberate action and purposeful travel, reflecting one's intentions and direction in life. The act of walking can also denote humility and modesty, as it involves traversing the earth with one's own effort. Additionally, the term can imply the spreading of news or actions among people, as in the phrase مَشَىٰ بِالنَّمِيمَةِ (\"he walked with gossip\"), highlighting the social implications of movement.",
  "3358": "مَشِيدٌ and related words stem from the root ش-ي-د, with the root verb شَادَ meaning \"he erected\" or \"he built.\" مَشِيدٌ means \"lofty,\" \"elevated,\" or \"well-built.\" The connection lies in the root's concept of constructing something grand or solid. مَشِيدٌ describes structures that are impressively built, highlighting human efforts to achieve greatness through architecture. It reflects on the temporal nature of such achievements compared to the permanence of spiritual accomplishments.",
  "3359": "مَشَّاءٌ and related words stem from the root م-ش-ي, with the root verb مَشَىٰ meaning \"he walked\" or \"he moved on foot.\" مَشَّاءٌ means \"one who walks much\" or \"a frequent walker.\" This term emphasizes habitual walking, which can be interpreted positively as diligence and perseverance, or negatively when associated with undesirable actions, such as in مَشَّاءٍ بِنَمِيمٍ (\"a persistent gossipmonger\"). The intensive form highlights the significance of repeated actions and their impact on individual character and societal interactions.",
  "3360": "مَشْأَمَةٌ and related words stem from the root ش-أ-م, with the root verb شَأَمَ meaning \"he became ill-omened\" or \"he was of ill-fortune.\" مَشْأَمَةٌ refers to \"the left hand\" or \"ill-fortune,\" symbolizing misfortune and adversity. The connection lies in the association of the left side with unfavorable outcomes, directly relating to the root's meaning of ill-omen. In the Qur'an, it describes those who receive their record in their left hand, highlighting their unfortunate state in the hereafter.",
  "3361": "مَشْحُونٌ and related words stem from the root ش-ح-ن, with the root verb شَحَنَ meaning \"he loaded\" or \"he filled.\" مَشْحُونٌ is a passive form meaning \"laden\" or \"filled,\" describing something fully loaded or charged. The connection lies in the root's emphasis on filling up, reflecting the state of being packed or loaded to capacity, often used for ships or containers fully stocked.",
  "3362": "مَشْرَبٌ and related words stem from the root ش-ر-ب, with the root verb شَرِبَ meaning \"he drank.\" مَشْرَبٌ refers to \"a drinking place\" or \"a vessel used for drinking,\" denoting the location or means associated with drinking. The connection lies in the root's emphasis on the action of drinking, extending to facilities or tools that facilitate this essential act, highlighting provision and accessibility.",
  "3363": "مَشْرِقٌ and related words stem from the root ش-ر-ق, with the root verb شَرَقَ meaning \"it rose\" or \"it shone.\" مَشْرِقٌ refers to \"the place of sunrise\" or \"the east,\" denoting where the sun rises. The connection lies in the root's emphasis on the rising sun, symbolizing beginnings, light, and hope emerging from the east.",
  "3364": "مَشْعَرٌ and related words stem from the root ش-ع-ر, with the root verb شَعَرَ meaning \"he perceived\" or \"he became aware.\" مَشْعَرٌ refers to \"a place of ritual\" or \"sacred site,\" particularly in the context of the Hajj pilgrimage. The connection lies in the heightened spiritual awareness and consciousness associated with these sacred locations. It embodies the root's concept of perception, where believers become more attuned to Allah (ﷻ) and their surroundings, fostering a deeper connection and mindfulness during the sacred rituals.",
  "3365": "مَشْكُورٌ and related words stem from the root ش-ك-ر, with the root verb شَكَرَ meaning \"he thanked\" or \"he was grateful.\" مَشْكُورٌ is a passive form meaning \"praised,\" \"thanked,\" or \"appreciated.\" The connection lies in the root's concept of gratitude, focusing here on the recipient of thanks. مَشْكُورٌ describes someone or something that has been acknowledged or appreciated by others, highlighting the recognition of their contributions or favors.",
  "3366": "مَشْهَدٌ and related words stem from the root ش-ه-د, with the root verb شَهِدَ meaning \"he witnessed.\" مَشْهَدٌ means \"scene,\" \"place of witnessing,\" or \"spectacle.\" The connection lies in the root's concept of witnessing, with مَشْهَدٌ referring to the location or occasion where events are witnessed. It embodies the idea of a significant event or gathering that people observe, often carrying importance in legal, historical, or spiritual contexts.",
  "3367": "مَشْهُودٌ and related words stem from the root ش-ه-د, with the root verb شَهِدَ meaning \"he witnessed.\" مَشْهُودٌ is a passive form meaning \"witnessed\" or \"attested.\" The connection lies in the root's concept of witnessing, with مَشْهُودٌ describing something that has been observed or testified to by witnesses. It highlights the significance of an event or fact confirmed through observation, emphasizing its authenticity and importance.",
  "3368": "مَشْيٌ and related words stem from the root م-ش-ي, with the root verb مَشَىٰ meaning \"he walked\" or \"he moved on foot.\" مَشْيٌ refers to \"walking\" or \"gait,\" focusing on the manner or style of one's movement. In Arabic literature, the description of one's gait can convey insights into their personality, mood, or social status. A deliberate and steady gait may suggest confidence and purpose, while a hurried or erratic walk could imply anxiety or instability. The term also reflects the broader concept of life's journey, with each individual's \"walk\" representing their unique path and experiences.",
  "3369": "مَصَانِعُ and related words stem from the root ص-ن-ع, with the root verb صَنَعَ meaning \"he made\" or \"he crafted.\" مَصَانِعُ (plural of مَصْنَعٌ) means \"factories,\" \"workshops,\" or \"structures.\" The connection lies in places or things that are made, built, or constructed, reflecting the root's emphasis on craftsmanship, creation, and the act of making. This term highlights the process of manufacturing or assembling something, symbolizing human skill in shaping the material world through deliberate effort.",
  "3370": "مَصِيرٌ and related words stem from the root ص-ي-ر, with the root verb صَارَ meaning \"he became\" or \"he turned into.\" مَصِيرٌ refers to \"destination,\" \"end,\" or \"ultimate return.\" The connection lies in the final state or place to which one turns or becomes, emphasizing the concept of an ultimate outcome or fate. This term highlights the idea of returning to Allah (ﷻ) as the final destination, reflecting the root's focus on becoming and the culmination of one's journey.",
  "3371": "مَصْرُوفٌ and related words stem from the root ص-ر-ف, with the root verb صَرَفَ meaning \"he turned away.\" مَصْرُوفٌ is a passive form meaning \"diverted\" or \"turned away.\" The connection lies in being the object of diversion or redirection. In the Qur'an, it describes punishment that cannot be averted from wrongdoers, emphasizing the certainty of divine justice and the inescapability of consequences.",
  "3372": "مَصْرِفٌ and related words stem from the root ص-ر-ف, with the root verb صَرَفَ meaning \"he turned away\" or \"he expended.\" مَصْرِفٌ means \"place of expenditure\" or \"destination.\" The connection lies in the endpoint where something is directed or spent. In the Qur'an, it can relate to the ultimate destination of actions or resources, emphasizing accountability and the importance of directing efforts toward righteous ends.",
  "3373": "مَصْفُوفَةٌ and related words stem from the root ص-ف-ف, with the root verb صَفَّ meaning \"he arranged in rows.\" مَصْفُوفَةٌ is a passive form meaning \"arranged,\" \"arrayed,\" or \"set in order.\" The connection lies in being meticulously organized or beautifully lined up, embodying the root's emphasis on order and harmony. In the Qur'an, it describes thrones in Paradise that are exquisitely arranged, highlighting the aesthetic and spiritual pleasure derived from orderliness and the blessings bestowed upon the righteous.",
  "3374": "مَضَاجِعُ and related words stem from the root ض-ج-ع, with the root verb ضَجَعَ meaning \"he lay down\" or \"he reclined.\" مَضَاجِعُ means \"beds,\" \"places of rest,\" or \"lying places.\" The connection lies in the act of reclining or resting in a specific place. This term emphasizes the human need for rest and the inevitability of death, as it is sometimes used metaphorically for graves, reflecting the root's focus on lying down and repose.",
  "3375": "مَطَرٌ and related words stem from the root م-ط-ر, with the root verb مَطَرَ meaning \"it rained.\" مَطَرٌ specifically refers to \"rain,\" highlighting its role as a life-giving force that revitalizes the earth and supports growth and sustenance. The root extends to embody themes of abundance, mercy, and provision, as rain is often seen as a blessing and a sign of divine care. The connection is direct, as rain is essential for nurturing life and maintaining the balance of ecosystems. In classical Arabic, مَطَرٌ can also carry broader connotations of renewal, purity, and the unending cycle of provision, highlighting its symbolic association with Allah’s (ﷻ) mercy and continuous sustenance of creation.",
  "3376": "مَطْلَعٌ and related words stem from the root ط-ل-ع, with the root verb طَلَعَ meaning \"he rose\" or \"he emerged.\" مَطْلَعٌ means \"place of rising\" or \"time of rising,\" often referring to the east where the sun rises. The connection lies in the point of emergence, directly reflecting the root's concept of rising. This term highlights orientations in time and space, emphasizing beginnings, particularly the dawning of a new cycle or event. The term captures both the physical rise, like the sun's appearance, and metaphorical origins, pointing to the start or initiation of something, marking a significant moment of transition or commencement.",
  "3377": "مَطْلُوبٌ and related words stem from the root ط-ل-ب, with the root verb طَلَبَ meaning \"he sought\" or \"he requested.\" مَطْلُوبٌ is a passive form meaning \"sought\" or \"desired,\" referring to that which is pursued or requested. The connection lies in being the object of pursuit, directly reflecting the root's concept of seeking. This term emphasizes the value or significance of something that is actively sought after.",
  "3378": "مَطْلِعٌ and related words stem from the root ط-ل-ع, with the root verb طَلَعَ meaning \"he rose\" or \"he emerged.\" مَطْلِعٌ means \"ascension\" or \"elevation,\" referring to the act or place of rising. The connection lies in the emphasis on ascent or emergence, directly reflecting the root's concept of rising. This term highlights the significance of origins and the inception of events, pointing to the moment or place where something begins its rise or elevation. It captures both literal and metaphorical meanings of ascent, not only in the physical sense of rising but also in the figurative sense of progress, development, or the start of an important change.",
  "3379": "مَطْوِيَّاتٌ and related words stem from the root ط-و-ي, with the root verb طَوَىٰ meaning \"he folded,\" \"he rolled up,\" or \"he wrapped.\" مَطْوِيَّاتٌ is a passive form meaning \"folded,\" \"rolled up,\" or \"wrapped,\" describing something that has been folded, compressed, or concealed. The root conveys themes of contraction, concealment, and gathering into a compact form, emphasizing the act of enclosing or wrapping something. مَطْوِيَّةٌ reflects the state of being enveloped or hidden, directly aligning with the root’s focus on folding or compressing. This term can also symbolically represent things gathered or stored, highlighting the versatility of the root in physical and metaphorical contexts.",
  "3380": "مَظْلُومٌ and related words stem from the root ظ-ل-م, with the root verb ظَلَمَ meaning \"he wronged\" or \"he acted unjustly.\" مَظْلُومٌ is a passive form meaning \"wronged person\" or \"oppressed one.\" The connection highlights the recipient of injustice, reflecting the root's concept from the victim's perspective. This term emphasizes the plight of those who suffer oppression, underlining the importance of recognizing and addressing injustice, and reinforcing the moral imperative to protect the oppressed.",
  "3381": "مَعَادٌ and related words stem from the root ع-و-د, with the root verb عَادَ meaning \"he returned\" or \"he reverted.\" مَعَادٌ means \"return,\" \"place of return,\" or \"hereafter.\" The connection lies in the ultimate return to Allah (ﷻ) after death, reflecting the root's emphasis on returning. It highlights the belief in the hereafter and accountability, encouraging individuals to live righteously in preparation for their return to their Creator.",
  "3382": "مَعاذِيرُ and related words stem from the root ع-ذ-ر, with the root verb عَذَرَ meaning \"he excused\" or \"he pardoned.\" مَعاذِيرُ is the plural of مَعْذِرَةٌ, meaning \"excuses\" or \"apologies.\" The term encompasses multiple instances of seeking forgiveness or providing justifications, directly linked to the root's emphasis on pardoning and offering reasons to alleviate blame. This highlights the human tendency to present various excuses, reflecting on the moral significance of sincerity in seeking forgiveness and the importance of accepting genuine apologies.",
  "3383": "مَعَارِجُ and related words stem from the root ع-ر-ج, with the root verb عَرَجَ meaning \"he ascended,\" \"he went up,\" or \"he climbed.\" مَعَارِجُ is the plural of مِعْرَاجٌ, meaning \"stairways,\" \"ladders,\" or \"ways of ascent.\" In the Qur'an, it refers to the pathways or means by which the angels ascend to Allah (ﷻ), symbolizing a systematic and divinely ordained progression to higher realms. The connection lies in the physical or metaphysical means of ascent, directly tied to the root's emphasis on rising or moving upward in a purposeful and elevated manner.",
  "3384": "مَعَاشٌ and related words stem from the root ع-ي-ش, with the root verb عَاشَ meaning \"he lived.\" مَعَاشٌ means \"livelihood,\" \"means of subsistence,\" or \"life.\" The connection lies in the aspects of life that sustain and support existence, directly relating to the root's emphasis on living. This term highlights the resources and activities that provide for one's needs, emphasizing the practical means by which life is maintained.",
  "3385": "مَعَايِشُ and related words stem from the root ع-ي-ش, with the root verb عَاشَ meaning \"he lived.\" مَعَايِشُ is the plural form of مَعِيشَةٌ, meaning \"livelihoods,\" \"means of subsistence,\" or \"ways of living.\" The connection lies in the various methods by which life is sustained, directly relating to the root's focus on living and existence. This term encompasses the diverse means through which people obtain their necessities, highlighting the multiplicity of ways life is maintained.",
  "3386": "مَعَرَّةٌ and related words stem from the root ع-ر-ر, with the root verb عَرَّ meaning \"he harmed,\" \"he injured,\" or \"he disgraced.\" عَرٌّ refers to a skin disease in camels that causes mange, scabs, and fur loss, leaving visible blemishes. مَعَرَّةٌ means \"harm,\" \"offense,\" \"injury,\" or \"disgrace.\" The connection lies in how the physical blemishes of عَرٌّ metaphorically extend to moral blemishes. Just as the disease tarnishes a camel's appearance, مَعَرَّةٌ represents actions that harm or disgrace a person's reputation due to sin or crime.",
  "3387": "مَعِيشَةٌ and related words stem from the root ع-ي-ش, with the root verb عَاشَ meaning \"he lived.\" مَعِيشَةٌ means \"livelihood,\" \"mode of living,\" or \"means of subsistence.\" The connection lies in the conditions and resources that support life, directly relating to the root's emphasis on existence and living. This term highlights the quality and manner of one's life, emphasizing how one's needs are met and life is experienced.",
  "3388": "مَعِينٌ and related words stem from the root ع-ي-ن, which conveys meanings like \"flowing\" or \"gushing,\" often used to describe clear, running water. مَعِينٌ refers to a spring or source that is active and abundant, emphasizing clarity and motion. The connection lies in the root’s concept of origination and flow, symbolizing vitality and sustenance from an endless source. This term reflects the life-giving qualities of water, highlighting the continuity and provision inherent in a flowing spring, directly tying to the root’s themes of abundance and clarity.",
  "3389": "مَعْدُودٌ and related words stem from the root ع-د-د, with the root verb عَدَّ meaning \"he counted\" or \"he enumerated.\" مَعْدُودٌ is a passive form meaning \"counted\" or \"numbered.\" The connection is direct, as it describes something that has been counted or is limited in number, reflecting the root's focus on enumeration. This term often implies scarcity or finiteness, reminding us that worldly pleasures and time are counted and limited, encouraging us to focus on what is eternal.",
  "3390": "مَعْدُودَةٌ and related words stem from the root ع-د-د, with the root verb عَدَّ meaning \"he counted,\" \"he enumerated,\" or \"he reckoned.\" مَعْدُودَةٌ is a passive form meaning \"counted\" or \"numbered,\" describing something that has been specifically tallied or is limited in quantity. The root conveys themes of calculation, precision, and limitation, emphasizing the act of defining or setting boundaries through enumeration. مَعْدُودَةٌ is often used to refer to specific numbered days or finite periods, reflecting the root’s focus on measured precision and the awareness of life's finite and countable moments.",
  "3391": "مَعْرُوشَاتٌ and related words stem from the root ع-ر-ش, with the root verb عَرَشَ meaning \"he built\" or \"he erected.\" مَعْرُوشَاتٌ means \"trellised\" or \"supported on trellises,\" used to describe plants that are raised on structures. The connection lies in constructing support for plants to grow upon, directly relating to the root's concept of building or erecting. This term highlights human cultivation efforts and the nurturing of growth through providing structure, reflecting the interplay between human endeavor and the natural world.",
  "3392": "مَعْرُوفٌ and related words stem from the root ع-ر-ف, with the root verb عَرَفَ meaning \"he knew,\" \"he recognized,\" or \"he perceived.\" مَعْرُوفٌ is a passive form meaning \"known,\" \"recognized,\" or \"well-known,\" often referring to what is universally accepted as good, right, or virtuous. It signifies actions or virtues that align with ethical standards recognized by human conscience and society. The term is often used in the context of enjoining good, emphasizing promoting what is just and beneficial. This connection to the root highlights knowledge and recognition, showing how goodness and virtue are inherently understood within collective human awareness.",
  "3393": "مَعْرُوفَةٌ and related words stem from the root ع-ر-ف, with the root verb عَرَفَ meaning \"he knew,\" \"he recognized,\" or \"he perceived.\" مَعْرُوفَةٌ means \"known,\" \"recognized,\" or \"well-known.\" It conveys the idea of something that is acknowledged or familiar, often pertaining to deeds or qualities esteemed in society. The connection lies in the root's emphasis on knowledge and recognition, highlighting that certain virtues or actions are inherently valued and respected across cultures.",
  "3394": "مَعْزٌ and related words stem from the root م-ع-ز, with the root verb مَعَزَ meaning \"he was strong\" or \"he increased in number.\" مَعْزٌ refers to \"goats,\" animals renowned for their resilience and prolific nature. This connection reflects the root's concepts of strength and increase, as goats thrive in challenging environments and reproduce efficiently. In agrarian societies, goats symbolize resilience, abundance, and productivity, embodying qualities of endurance and fertility. This highlights the cultural significance of goats and related terms in classical Arabic, emphasizing themes of robustness and steadfastness.",
  "3395": "مَعْزُولٌ and related words stem from the root ع-ز-ل, with the root verb عَزَلَ meaning \"he separated,\" \"he isolated,\" or \"he removed.\" مَعْزُولٌ is a passive form meaning \"removed,\" \"isolated,\" \"deposed,\" or \"dismissed.\" The nuance here is that of being the object of separation or removal. This connects to the root's concept of separation, emphasizing the state of being set apart or dismissed from a position or group, often implying a loss of status or responsibility.",
  "3396": "مَعْزِلٌ and related words stem from the root ع-ز-ل, with the root verb عَزَلَ meaning \"he separated,\" \"he isolated,\" or \"he removed.\" مَعْزِلٌ means \"place of seclusion,\" \"retreat,\" or \"sanctuary.\" The connection lies in the idea of a location designated for withdrawal or isolation. This reflects the root's emphasis on separation, highlighting a physical space where one can separate from others for contemplation, safety, or privacy, often used for spiritual reflection or refuge.",
  "3397": "مَعْشَرٌ and related words stem from the root ع-ش-ر, with the root verb عَشَرَ meaning \"he became the tenth,\" and عَاشَرَ meaning \"he mixed with,\" \"he maintained social or familial ties,\" or \"he became intimate with.\" مَعْشَرٌ refers to a \"community,\" \"group,\" or \"people,\" representing a collective of individuals. The connection lies in the idea of assembling and associating multiple individuals, metaphorically tied to the number ten, symbolizing unity and completeness. This term highlights the importance of togetherness and collective identity within social structures and communities.",
  "3398": "مَعْصِيَةٌ and related words stem from the root ع-ص-ي, with the root verb عَصَىٰ meaning \"he disobeyed.\" مَعْصِيَةٌ means \"sin\" or \"act of disobedience.\" The connection lies in the action of going against commands or prohibitions, reflecting the root's emphasis on disobedience. This term highlights the moral and ethical implications of defying divine or lawful orders, emphasizing the importance of obedience in maintaining righteousness.",
  "3399": "مَعْكُوفٌ and related words stem from the root ع-ك-ف, with the root verb عَكَفَ meaning \"he remained attached\" or \"he devoted himself.\" مَعْكُوفٌ is a passive form meaning \"detained,\" \"held back,\" or \"confined.\" The connection lies in being kept in a state of continuous attachment or being prevented from proceeding, reflecting the root's emphasis on remaining in place. This term can symbolize obstacles that prevent movement or progress, highlighting themes of restriction and confinement.",
  "3400": "مَعْلُومٌ and related words stem from the root ع-ل-م, with the root verb عَلِمَ meaning \"he knew,\" \"he became aware,\" or \"he understood,\" and عَلَّمَ meaning \"he taught\" or \"he caused to know. مَعْلُومٌ is a passive form meaning \"known\" or \"that which is known,\" referring to something that has been recognized, established, or understood. The root conveys themes of knowledge, awareness, and clarity, emphasizing the process of acquiring and conveying understanding. مَعْلُومٌ highlights the outcome of knowledge, representing facts or truths that are evident, acknowledged, or universally accepted, reflecting the root’s focus on learning and comprehension.",
  "3401": "مَعْلُومَاتٌ and related words stem from the root ع-ل-م, with the root verb عَلِمَ meaning \"he knew,\" \"he became aware,\" or \"he understood,\" and عَلَّمَ meaning \"he taught\" or \"he caused to know.\" مَعْلُومَاتٌ means \"known\" or \"that which is known,\" emphasizing recognition and awareness. The root conveys themes of knowledge, clarity, and understanding, focusing on the process of acquiring and transmitting knowledge. مَعْلُومَةٌ represents the outcome of knowledge, signifying truths or facts that are evident, acknowledged, or universally accepted, embodying the root’s emphasis on comprehension and learning.",
  "3402": "مَعْمُورٌ and related words stem from the root ع-م-ر, with the root verb عَمَرَ meaning \"he inhabited,\" \"he cultivated,\" or \"he enlivened.\" مَعْمُورٌ is a passive form meaning \"inhabited,\" \"populated,\" or \"well-maintained.\" The connection lies in a place being enriched with life and activity, reflecting the root's emphasis on flourishing and prosperity. It conveys the idea of a thriving environment, whether it's a bustling city or a heart filled with faith, embodying the fullness and vitality intended by divine design.",
  "3403": "مَغَارَاتٌ and related words stem from the root غ-و-ر, with the root verb غَارَ meaning \"it receded,\" \"vanished,\" or \"sank.\" مَغَارَاتٌ (plural of مَغَارَةٌ) means \"mountain hollows\" or \"places of refuge,\" specifically referring to natural hollows in mountains large enough to provide seclusion or concealment, functioning similarly to caves. Broader root meanings emphasize depth, withdrawal, and disappearance, reflecting the act of moving inward or becoming hidden. The connection lies in retreating into concealed spaces, symbolizing safety, seclusion, and escape.",
  "3404": "مَغانِمُ and related words stem from the root غ-ن-م, with the root verb غَنِمَ meaning \"he gained,\" \"acquired as booty,\" or \"won.\" مَغانِمُ means \"spoils,\" \"gains,\" or \"booty.\" It refers to assets or benefits acquired, often in the context of war or competition. The connection lies in the collective rewards obtained through effort or conflict, reflecting the root's concept of acquisition. It emphasizes tangible outcomes of endeavors, highlighting themes of success and the responsibilities accompanying material gains.",
  "3405": "مَغْرَمٌ and related words stem from the root غ-ر-م, with the root verb غَرِمَ meaning \"he incurred a debt,\" \"he became liable,\" or \"he suffered loss.\" مَغْرَمٌ means \"debt,\" \"penalty,\" or \"financial burden.\" The connection lies in the concept of a liability or obligation that causes loss or hardship, directly relating to the root's meaning. This term highlights the weight of financial responsibilities that can burden an individual, emphasizing the potential hardships associated with debts or penalties.",
  "3406": "مَغْرِبٌ and related words stem from the root غ-ر-ب, with the root verb غَرَبَ meaning \"it set\" or \"it departed.\" مَغْرِبٌ means \"the west\" or \"place of sunset,\" identifying the direction where the sun sets. The connection lies in the concept of departure and conclusion, as the sun leaves the sky in the west. This term signifies endings and the natural transitions marked by the sun's daily journey, reflecting the root's emphasis on setting and closure.",
  "3407": "مَغْشِيٌّ and related words stem from the root غ-ش-و, with the root verb غَشِيَ meaning \"he covered,\" \"he enveloped,\" or \"he came over (someone).\" مَغْشِيٌّ is a passive form meaning \"covered\" or \"overcome.\" The connection lies in being the recipient of the action of covering, directly relating to the root's meaning. This term can describe someone who is unconscious or overwhelmed, emphasizing a state where normal faculties are obscured or suppressed.",
  "3408": "مَغْضُوبٌ and related words stem from the root غ-ض-ب, with the root verb غَضِبَ meaning \"he was angry\" or \"he became enraged.\" مَغْضُوبٌ is a passive form meaning \"one who has incurred wrath.\" Broader root meanings emphasize intense displeasure, forceful emotional responses, and the consequences of provoking such anger. The connection lies in being the recipient of anger, reflecting the root’s focus on the powerful and consuming nature of displeasure.",
  "3409": "مَغْفِرَةٌ and related words stem from the root غ-ف-ر, with the root verb غَفَرَ meaning \"he forgave,\" \"he covered,\" or \"he concealed.\" مَغْفِرَةٌ means \"forgiveness\" or \"mercy.\" The connection lies in the concept of pardon and covering of sins, directly relating to the root's meaning. This term emphasizes the generous and compassionate aspect of Allah's (ﷻ) forgiveness, encouraging believers to seek His mercy.",
  "3410": "مَغْلُوبٌ and related words stem from the root غ-ل-ب, with the root verb غَلَبَ meaning \"he overcame,\" \"defeated,\" or \"prevailed.\" مَغْلُوبٌ is a passive form meaning \"defeated\" or \"overcome.\" This form signifies someone or something that has been overpowered. The connection lies in embodying the root's concept from the perspective of the one who has been subdued, highlighting the experience of defeat. It emphasizes the dual nature of struggle—where victory and defeat are two sides of the same coin—symbolizing lessons learned through adversity.",
  "3411": "مَغْلُولَةٌ and related words stem from the root غ-ل-ل, with the root verb غَلَّ meaning \"he bound,\" \"tied,\" or \"fettered.\" مَغْلُولَةٌ is a passive form meaning \"bound,\" \"chained,\" or \"fettered.\" This word describes something or someone that is restrained. The connection lies in embodying the root's concept of physical binding, reflecting a state of confinement. In the Qur'anic context, it's used metaphorically to challenge misconceptions about divine attributes, emphasizing that attributing limitations to Allah (ﷻ) is incorrect. It highlights themes of generosity versus miserliness and the importance of proper understanding.",
  "3412": "مَفَازٌ and related words stem from the root ف-و-ز, with the root verb فَازَ meaning \"he succeeded\" or \"he won.\" مَفَازٌ means \"a place of success\" or \"achievement,\" referring to a location or means where success or victory is realized. The root conveys themes of triumph, attainment, and overcoming challenges, and مَفَازٌ embodies this by highlighting a setting or circumstance where such success occurs. It reflects the idea of achieving a desired outcome, emphasizing the attainment of goals through effort or perseverance.",
  "3413": "مَفَازَةٌ and related words stem from the root ف-و-ز, with the root verb فَازَ meaning \"he succeeded\" or \"he won.\" مَفَازَةٌ means \"a place of success\" or \"a place of safety.\" It can also signify \"a desert\" in classical Arabic, as a desert was metaphorically considered a place where survival itself was a form of triumph. The root conveys themes of victory, attainment, and overcoming challenges, which align with the meanings of مَفَازَةٌ as spaces associated with triumph or safety. This reflects the root’s broader idea of achieving success, whether in physical survival or spiritual accomplishment.",
  "3414": "مَفَرٌّ and related words stem from the root ف-ر-ر, with the root verb فَرَّ meaning \"he fled\" or \"he ran away.\" مَفَرٌّ means \"place of escape,\" \"refuge,\" or \"way out.\" The connection lies in the means or location that allows for escape, directly relating to the root's emphasis on fleeing. This term highlights the search for safety or sanctuary, emphasizing the importance of having an option or path to avoid harm.",
  "3415": "مَفْتُونٌ and related words stem from the root ف-ت-ن, with the root verb فَتَنَ meaning \"he tried\" or \"he tested.\" مَفْتُونٌ is a passive form meaning \"one who is tried\" or \"afflicted,\" highlighting someone undergoing trials or captivated by temptation. The connection lies in being the subject of tests, reflecting the root's concept of exposure to trials that challenge faith. It emphasizes vulnerability and the potential for growth or downfall through affliction.",
  "3416": "مَفْرُوضٌ and related words stem from the root ف-ر-ض, with the root verb فَرَضَ meaning \"he imposed\" or \"he prescribed.\" مَفْرُوضٌ is a passive form meaning \"prescribed,\" \"ordained,\" or \"made obligatory.\" The connection lies in something that has been imposed upon individuals as a duty, directly relating to the root's concept of prescription. This term underscores the binding nature of commands or laws that are to be followed, highlighting the authoritative establishment of obligations.",
  "3417": "مَفْعُولٌ and related words stem from the root ف-ع-ل, with the root verb فَعَلَ meaning \"he did\" or \"he acted.\" مَفْعُولٌ is a passive form meaning \"fulfilled,\" \"done,\" or \"acted upon,\" describing something that has received the action of a doer. The root conveys themes of action, performance, and execution, with مَفْعُولٌ reflecting the result or recipient of that action. Grammatically, مَفْعُولٌ refers to the passive participle (اِسْمُ ٱلْمَفْعُولِ), indicating what has been acted upon or affected.",
  "3418": "مَقَابِرُ and related words stem from the root ق-ب-ر, with the root verb قَبَرَ meaning \"he buried.\" مَقَابِرُ means \"cemeteries.\" The connection lies in places designated for burial, directly relating to the root's concept. Cemeteries are collective gravesites, reminding communities of death's certainty and the need for humility and preparation for the afterlife.",
  "3419": "مَقامٌ and related words stem from the root ق-و-م, with the root verb قامَ meaning \"he stood\" or \"he rose.\" The root embodies concepts of standing, establishing, and position. مَقامٌ means \"station,\" \"place,\" or \"standing.\" It refers to a position where one stands or a rank one holds. The connection lies in the idea of a fixed place or status that is established and maintained. It reflects the root's emphasis on uprightness and stability, highlighting the significance of one's position or role, whether physical or metaphorical.",
  "3420": "مَقامِعُ and related words stem from the root ق-م-ع, with the root verb قَمَعَ meaning \"he restrained,\" \"he subdued,\" \"he suppressed,\" or \"he extinguished.\" مَقامِعُ (plural of مِقْمَعَةٌ) refers to \"maces\" or \"rods,\" heavy blunt instruments used for punishment and suppression. The connection to the root lies in the instrument’s purpose: just as قَمَعَ signifies subduing or overpowering, مَقامِعُ embodies the means through which suppression or punishment is physically enacted. These instruments are used to impose restraint and enforce authority, often in the form of severe punishment.",
  "3421": "مَقِيلٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ي-ل, with the root verb قَالَ meaning \"he slept at midday.\" The root conveys concepts of rest, particularly during the hottest part of the day. مَقِيلٌ means \"resting place,\" symbolizing a time of reprieve and restoration. The connection lies in the act of reclining or resting, which reflects the need for rejuvenation. In the context of ultimate peace and reward, مَقِيلٌ emphasizes a state of contentment and tranquility, where one finds true solace and restoration, representing not just physical rest but a deeper sense of fulfillment and harmony.",
  "3422": "مَقْبُوحٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ب-ح, with the root verb قَبُحَ meaning \"he was ugly\" or \"he became bad.\" مَقْبُوحٌ is a passive form meaning \"disgraced,\" \"repelled,\" or \"abhorred.\" The connection lies in being rejected or cast away due to ugliness or foulness, directly relating to the root's concept of being undesirable. It emphasizes a state of being detested or shunned, highlighting moral corruption or physical repulsiveness that leads to disgrace.",
  "3423": "مَقْبُوضَةٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ب-ض, with the root verb قَبَضَ meaning \"he grasped.\" مَقْبُوضَةٌ is a passive form meaning \"seized\" or \"withheld.\" The connection lies in something that has been grasped or withheld, embodying the root's concept of grasping. It highlights the state of being under control or restricted, emphasizing possession or limitation.",
  "3424": "مَقْتٌ and related words stem from the root م-ق-ت, with the root verb مَقَتَ meaning \"he hated intensely\" or \"he abhorred.\" مَقْتٌ refers to \"intense hatred,\" \"abhorrence,\" or \"detestation,\" emphasizing an extreme level of aversion. The root conveys a deep moral or emotional rejection, often tied to actions or traits deemed reprehensible or detestable. مَقْتٌ reflects the strongest form of dislike, capturing the profound disdain associated with morally offensive behaviors or characteristics.",
  "3425": "مَقْدُورٌ and related words stem from the root ق-د-ر, with the root verb قَدَرَ meaning \"he measured,\" \"he determined,\" or \"he decreed.\" مَقْدُورٌ is a passive form meaning \"that which is decreed,\" \"predestined,\" or \"measured out.\" The connection lies in being the object of precise measurement or decree, directly reflecting the root's emphasis on determination and ordainment. This term highlights the aspect of events or outcomes that have been predetermined or allotted, highlighting the concept of destiny.",
  "3426": "مَقْرَبَةٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ر-ب, with the root verb قَرُبَ meaning \"he was near\" or \"he approached.\" مَقْرَبَةٌ means \"closeness\" or \"state of nearness,\" particularly emphasizing familial or relational proximity. Broader root meanings highlight nearness, connection, and intimacy, whether physical, emotional, or social. In context, مَقْرَبَةٌ reflects the closeness of kinship and the importance of supporting and caring for family members, especially those in need, highlighting the moral obligation to strengthen bonds of compassion and mutual support.",
  "3427": "مَقْسُومٌ and related words stem from the root ق-س-م, with the root verb قَسَمَ meaning \"he divided\" or \"he allotted.\" مَقْسُومٌ means \"divided,\" \"apportioned,\" or \"destined,\" signifying something that has been allocated or predetermined. The connection reflects the concept of an allotted share or portion, whether through human effort or divine decree. This term highlights themes of acceptance and contentment with what has been assigned, emphasizing trust in divine wisdom and the inevitability of fate in the distribution of life's opportunities and challenges.",
  "3428": "مَقْصُورَاتٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ص-ر, with the root verb قَصَرَ meaning \"he confined,\" \"he restricted,\" or \"he limited.\" مَقْصُورَاتٌ refers to \"enclosed spaces,\" or \"private chambers.\" The connection lies in the concept of setting apart or secluding a space, emphasizing exclusivity and privacy. This term often denotes specific areas within a larger structure that are designated for particular individuals or purposes, highlighting themes of protection, sanctity, and reserved access.",
  "3429": "مَقْضِيٌّ and related words stem from the root ق-ض-ي, with the root verb قَضَىٰ meaning \"he decreed,\" \"he judged,\" or \"he completed.\" مَقْضِيٌّ refers to \"decreed,\" \"decided,\" or \"fulfilled,\" emphasizing something that has been firmly determined and executed. The connection lies in the finality of an act or decision, where what has been decreed is carried out with certainty and completeness. This root highlights themes of resolution, authority, and the inevitability of outcomes, illustrating the weight and permanence of decrees that leave no room for alteration or doubt.",
  "3430": "مَقْطُوعٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ط-ع, with the root verb قَطَعَ meaning \"he cut,\" \"he severed,\" or \"he separated.\" مَقْطُوعٌ means \"cut off,\" \"severed,\" or \"disconnected,\" referring to a state of complete separation or detachment. The connection lies in the decisive act of cutting, leaving something divided or detached from its origin or connection. This root emphasizes themes of disconnection, interruption, and finality. It can symbolize the end of continuity, relationships, or provision, reflecting the impactful and often irreversible nature of severance in both literal and metaphorical contexts.",
  "3431": "مَقْطُوعَةٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ط-ع, with the root verb قَطَعَ meaning \"he cut,\" \"he severed,\" or \"he separated.\" مَقْطُوعَةٌ means \"cut off,\" \"severed,\" or \"disconnected,\" emphasizing a state of complete separation or disconnection. The connection lies in the decisive and final nature of cutting, which leaves things divided or detached. This root highlights themes of finality, interruption, and division, whether physical, emotional, or metaphorical.",
  "3432": "مَقْعَدٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ع-د, with the root verb قَعَدَ meaning \"he sat,\" \"he remained,\" or \"he stayed behind.\" مَقْعَدٌ refers to a \"seat,\" \"place of sitting,\" or \"abode,\" emphasizing a location where one settles or stays. The connection lies in the act of sitting or remaining stationary, which conveys a sense of stability, rest, or permanence. This becomes particularly significant when considering that a seat or abode often serves as a symbol of authority, rest, or grounding, whether physical or metaphorical. The root reflects themes of stillness, rootedness, and the deliberate choice to remain in a specific place.",
  "3433": "مَكَانٌ and related words stem from the root ك-و-ن, with كَانَ as the root verb meaning \"he was\" or \"he existed.\" مَكَانٌ means \"place,\" \"location,\" or \"space,\" signifying the physical area where existence manifests or resides. The connection to the root lies in the concept of a defined space where \"being\" occurs, highlighting the relationship between existence and spatial presence. This term embodies the idea of something's presence in a tangible, physical context, highlighting the link between existence and the environment it occupies.",
  "3434": "مَكَانَةٌ and related words stem from the root ك-و-ن, with كَانَ meaning \"he was\" or \"he existed.\" مَكَانَةٌ refers to \"status,\" \"rank,\" or \"position,\" extending the concept of \"place\" into a metaphorical or social realm. The connection lies in the idea of one's \"place\" within a structure of importance, significance, or esteem. It reflects the role or standing a person holds in society or a hierarchical context, emphasizing the relational aspect of existence within a broader framework. This term captures the dynamic interplay between being and recognition, linking presence to social value or honor.",
  "3435": "مَكَثَ and related words stem from the root م-ك-ث, and as the root verb, it means \"he remained\" or \"he stayed.\" It conveys the idea of staying in a place or state for an extended period, reflecting persistence, continuity, or lingering. The root emphasizes a deliberate or unhurried stay, often suggesting a purposeful or steadfast presence. In classical usage, مَكَثَ applies to both physical staying, such as remaining in a location, and metaphorical contexts, such as persisting in an action or state. This versatility highlights themes of rootedness and steadiness, illustrating the significance of endurance and continuity in various contexts.",
  "3436": "مَكَرَ and related words stem from the root م-ك-ر, and as the root verb, it means \"he plotted\" or \"he deceived.\" The term carries the idea of strategizing or planning with subtlety, often with hidden or deceptive intentions. مَكَرَ implies a deliberate and calculated effort to achieve a goal, typically in a way that is not immediately apparent to others. The root encompasses themes of cunning, secrecy, and manipulation, reflecting actions undertaken with strategic foresight.",
  "3437": "مَكِيدُونَ and related words stem from the same root ك-ي-د, with كَادَ meaning \"he plotted\" or \"he schemed.\" مَكِيدُونَ is a passive form meaning \"those who are plotted against\" or \"victims of a scheme.\" It highlights the experience of being the target of a cunning or deceitful plan, reflecting the reactive side of the root's concept. The connection lies in the dual nature of plotting, emphasizing not only the one devising the scheme but also the one subjected to its effects.",
  "3438": "مَكِينٌ and related words stem from the root م-ك-ن, with the root verb مَكَنَ meaning \"he was firm\" or \"he was established.\" مَكِينٌ primarily means \"firmly established\" or \"securely positioned,\" emphasizing a state of stability and rootedness. Contextually, it can also convey nuances of being \"trusted\" or \"honored,\" particularly when referring to someone in a position of authority, reliability, or high status. These extended meanings arise from the root’s concept of strength and stability, reflecting the trust or respect often associated with someone firmly established in a role or position.",
  "3439": "مَكَّنَ and related words stem from the root م-ك-ن, with the root verb مَكَنَ meaning \"he was firm\" or \"he was established.\" مَكَّنَ means \"he made firm,\" \"he established,\" or \"he enabled,\" directly reflecting the active act of solidifying or empowering. While مَكَنَ conveys a state of being firm or established, مَكَّنَ emphasizes the deliberate act of granting firmness or authority, actively causing something to be established or strengthened. This distinction highlights مَكَّنَ as a more dynamic and purposeful form, highlighting intentional action rather than a passive state.",
  "3440": "مَكَّةُ refers to the sacred city of Mecca. The name Mecca and related words stem from the root م-ك-ك, with the root verb مَكَّ meaning \"to crush\" or \"to destroy.\" This meaning aligns with the destruction of idols in Mecca during its conquest by Prophet Muhammad (ﷺ), symbolizing the triumph of monotheism over polytheism. While the exact linguistic root of the name is debated, Mecca's spiritual significance remains central in Islam, representing divine protection and the ultimate victory of truth over falsehood and oppression.",
  "3441": "مَكْتُوبٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ت-ب, with the root verb كَتَبَ meaning \"he wrote,\" \"he prescribed,\" or \"he decreed.\" مَكْتُوبٌ is a passive form meaning \"written,\" \"decreed,\" or \"ordained.\" It refers to that which has been inscribed or prescribed, often implying something that is predetermined or destined. The connection lies in the root's focus on writing as formalizing and establishing matters. It highlights the concept of written decrees or destinies that are set and unchangeable, highlighting the permanence and authority of the written word.",
  "3442": "مَكْذُوبٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ذ-ب, with the root verb كَذَبَ meaning \"he lied,\" \"he spoke falsely,\" or \"he gave an untrue account.\" مَكْذُوبٌ is a passive form meaning \"lied about,\" \"falsely accused,\" or \"denied.\" It refers to someone or something subjected to falsehoods, highlighting the harm caused by lies or rejection of truth. The root emphasizes the destructive impact of deceit not only on the one who lies but also on those falsely accused or misrepresented. مَكْذُوبٌ reflects the broader consequences of falsehood, including the moral and social repercussions of distorting reality or denying truth.",
  "3443": "مَكْرٌ and related words stem from the root م-ك-ر, with the root verb مَكَرَ meaning \"he plotted\" or \"he deceived.\" مَكْرٌ means \"plot,\" \"scheme,\" or \"deceit.\" The connection lies in the embodiment of cunning plans or deceptive strategies, reflecting the root's concept of hidden intentions. It emphasizes the presence of deceit and the importance of integrity.",
  "3444": "مَكْرُوهٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ر-ه, with the root verb كَـرِهَ meaning \"he disliked\" or \"he hated.\" مَكْرُوهٌ is a passive form meaning \"detested\" or \"disliked.\" It describes something that is the object of aversion or hatred, often due to its unpleasant, harmful, or offensive nature. In classical Arabic, مَكْرُوهٌ can also imply something undesirable in a moral or spiritual sense, emphasizing its rejection by societal or divine standards. This term encapsulates the essence of repulsion, symbolizing that which is inherently objectionable or unwelcome.",
  "3445": "مَكْظُومٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ظ-م, with the root verb كَظَمَ meaning \"he suppressed\" or \"he restrained.\" مَكْظُومٌ is a passive form meaning \"overwhelmed by suppressed emotions,\" particularly those of distress, grief, or anger. It conveys the state of being burdened by intense feelings held back to the point of near-breaking. The root also conveys imagery of filling a container to its limit, symbolizing a stifling pressure. This term encapsulates the profound emotional weight of suppression and the internal struggle it entails.",
  "3446": "مَكْنُونٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ن-ن, with the root verb كَنَّ meaning \"he concealed\" or \"he hid.\" مَكْنُونٌ is a passive participle meaning \"hidden,\" \"concealed,\" or \"well-protected.\" The connection lies in something kept secret or guarded from exposure, embodying the root’s emphasis on preservation through concealment. This term highlights the value and sanctity of what is hidden, often associating the act of guarding with care, protection, and reverence.",
  "3447": "مَلَأٌ and related words stem from the root م-ل-أ, with the root verb مَلَأَ meaning \"he filled.\" مَلَأٌ refers to \"chiefs\" or \"leaders,\" connected to the root through their role in \"filling\" prominent spaces of authority. Traditionally, مَلَأٌ were those who physically filled the chambers around a king or leader, symbolizing their essential role in completing the structure of governance. This connection reflects their presence as individuals who fulfill critical roles, embodying the root's concept of fullness and completeness in leadership and decision-making.",
  "3448": "مَلَكٌ and related words stem from the root م-ل-ك, with the root verb مَلَكَ meaning \"he possessed,\" \"he ruled,\" or \"he mastered.\" مَلَكٌ means \"angel,\" denoting celestial beings created by Allah (ﷻ) to carry out His commands with precision and submission. The root conveys authority, dominion, and governance, highlighting angels' role as agents of divine will, who act with absolute obedience. This connection reflects the disciplined nature of their existence, embodying submission to Allah’s (ﷻ) supreme authority. It reminds believers of the unseen dimensions of creation, governed with unparalleled order and justice.",
  "3449": "مَلَكَتْ and related words stem from the root م-ل-ك, with the root verb مَلَكَ meaning \"he possessed,\" \"he ruled,\" or \"he controlled.\" مَلَكَتْ means \"it possessed\" or \"it owned,\" emphasizing the root’s concept of mastery and dominion. The connection lies in the act of possessing or exercising control over something, whether physical, spiritual, or intellectual. It reflects the broader theme of stewardship, reminding individuals of their responsibility to act with justice and wisdom over what they possess, as ultimate ownership belongs only to Allah (ﷻ).",
  "3450": "مَلَكُوتٌ and related words stem from the root م-ل-ك, with the root verb مَلَكَ meaning \"he possessed,\" \"he ruled,\" or \"he mastered.\" مَلَكُوتٌ means \"dominion\" or \"sovereignty,\" specifically emphasizing Allah’s (ﷻ) absolute control and possession of the heavens and the earth. This intensified form reflects the vastness and comprehensiveness of Allah’s (ﷻ) authority, extending over all realms, seen and unseen. The connection highlights that nothing in existence lies beyond His grasp or governance, reminding believers of His unmatched power and the need for humility before His Majesty.",
  "3451": "مَلُومٌ and related words stem from the root ل-و-م, with the root verb لَامَ meaning \"he blamed,\" \"he reproached,\" or \"he censured.\" مَلُومٌ is a passive form meaning \"blamed,\" \"reproached,\" or \"censured.\" It describes someone who is the object of blame or criticism, regardless of whether the blame is justified. The connection is direct, highlighting the state of being blamed and reflecting the consequences of actions or circumstances that lead to censure. This term emphasizes the external perception of an individual and the societal or interpersonal response to their actions, focusing on the resulting state rather than the act itself.",
  "3452": "مَلِكٌ and related words stem from the root م-ل-ك, with the root verb مَلَكَ meaning \"he possessed,\" \"he ruled,\" or \"he governed.\" مَلِكٌ means \"king\" or \"ruler,\" reflecting authority and mastery over a domain. The root conveys themes of governance, leadership, and dominion. ٱلْمَلِكُ, one of Allah’s (ﷻ) perfect names, means \"The Sovereign\" or \"The King,\" highlighting His supreme authority and ownership over all creation. Unlike human kingship, Allah’s (ﷻ) sovereignty is absolute, unchallenged, and eternal, encompassing both worldly and spiritual realms. This name reminds believers of Allah’s (ﷻ) justice, mercy, and wisdom in governing the universe.",
  "3453": "مَلِيكٌ and related words stem from the root م-ل-ك, with the root verb مَلَكَ meaning \"he possessed\" or \"he ruled.\" مَلِيكٌ is an intensive form meaning \"sovereign\" or \"supreme king,\" amplifying the concept of kingship to denote absolute and unparalleled authority. The connection reflects ultimate control and mastery, symbolizing Allah’s (ﷻ) exclusive right to rule over all creation. This term highlights the grandeur and perfection of Allah’s (ﷻ) governance, reminding believers of their dependence on Him and the ultimate accountability to the Supreme Sovereign.",
  "3454": "مَلِيًّا and related words stem from the root م-ل-و, with the root verb مَلِيَ meaning \"it lasted long\" or \"it endured.\" مَلِيًّا means \"long-lasting,\" \"sufficient in time,\" or \"ample.\" The connection lies in the root's concept of longevity, emphasizing endurance and the adequacy of time for meaningful actions or decisions. The root also conveys a sense of resilience and the continuity of opportunities, reflecting how time serves as both a resource and a responsibility.",
  "3455": "مَلْجَأٌ and related words stem from the root ل-ج-أ, with the root verb لَجَأَ meaning \"he sought refuge,\" \"he turned to for protection,\" or \"he fled to safety.\" مَلْجَأٌ specifically means \"refuge\" or \"place of shelter,\" emphasizing a location or source of safety during danger or hardship. The root conveys seeking security, relying on protection, or turning toward something in times of need. The connection lies in the act of moving away from vulnerability toward security. It reflects both physical safety and psychological reassurance, highlighting reliance and the human instinct to seek sanctuary in adversity.",
  "3456": "مَلْعُونِينَ and related words stem from the root ل-ع-ن, with the root verb لَعَنَ meaning \"he cursed,\" \"he expelled from mercy,\" or \"he invoked malediction upon.\" مَلْعُونِينَ is a passive form meaning \"accursed,\" \"ones who are cursed,\" or \"banished from mercy.\" The connection lies in being the recipient of a curse, reflecting the root's emphasis on exclusion and condemnation. This term highlights the condition of being deprived of mercy or favor, emphasizing the serious spiritual consequences of certain actions, and serving as a stark warning against behaviors that lead to such a state.",
  "3457": "مَلْعُونَةٌ and related words stem from the root ل-ع-ن, with the root verb لَعَنَ meaning \"he cursed,\" \"he expelled from mercy,\" or \"he invoked malediction upon.\" مَلْعُونَةٌ is a passive participle meaning \"accursed,\" \"the one that is cursed,\" or \"banished from mercy.\" The term reflects a state of being excluded from divine favor or blessings, symbolizing rejection or condemnation. In the context of descriptions involving مَلْعُونَةٌ, it often conveys something inherently associated with harm, trial, or spiritual consequence, emphasizing the profound nature of being marked by divine disfavor.",
  "3458": "مَلْكٌ and related words stem from the root م-ل-ك, with the root verb مَلَكَ meaning \"he possessed,\" \"he ruled,\" or \"he controlled.\" مَلْكٌ means \"possession,\" \"ownership,\" or \"will,\" emphasizing the authority and control associated with holding dominion over something. The connection reflects the root's concept of mastery, highlighting the responsibility and accountability inherent in managing what is entrusted. While human ownership is temporary and limited, Allah’s (ﷻ) dominion is eternal and absolute. This term reminds believers to act with gratitude and care, recognizing that all possession and will ultimately belong to Allah (ﷻ).",
  "3459": "مَمَاتٌ and related words stem from the root م-و-ت, with the root verb مَاتَ meaning \"he died.\" مَمَاتٌ means \"death\" or \"time of death,\" denoting the state or occurrence of dying. This term emphasizes the certainty of death as an inevitable endpoint for all living beings. The word also reflects the importance of understanding death as a transition rather than an end, encouraging individuals to prepare for their meeting with Allah (ﷻ) and to live life in alignment with His guidance.",
  "3460": "مَمْدُودٌ and related words stem from the root م-د-د, with the root verb مَدَّ meaning \"he extended,\" \"he stretched,\" or \"he prolonged.\" مَمْدُودٌ is a passive form meaning \"extended,\" \"stretched out,\" or \"prolonged.\" It highlights the result of being acted upon, where something is lengthened, expanded, or increased. This directly ties to the root's concept of extension, emphasizing a state of being made continuous, vast, or enduring, whether in time, space, or impact.",
  "3461": "مَمْلُوكٌ and related words stem from the root م-ل-ك, with the root verb مَلَكَ meaning \"he possessed\" or \"he owned.\" مَمْلُوكٌ is a passive form meaning \"owned,\" \"slave,\" or \"servant,\" referring to one under the control or possession of another. The connection reflects dependence and subjugation, symbolizing the ultimate servitude of all creation to Allah (ﷻ). It reminds believers that while they may exercise control over others or possessions, they themselves are owned by Allah (ﷻ), emphasizing humility and accountability.",
  "3462": "مَمْنُوعَةٌ and related words stem from the root م-ن-ع, with the root verb مَنَعَ meaning \"he prevented,\" \"he withheld,\" or \"he forbade.\" مَمْنُوعَةٌ means \"prevented,\" \"forbidden,\" or \"prohibited.\" The term signifies being the object of prevention or prohibition, reflecting the root's concept of withholding or denial. It conveys a state of being restricted, barred, or made inaccessible, emphasizing the inability to access or act freely due to external constraints. This highlights the notion of control or authority in imposing barriers, often seen in legal, social, or moral contexts.",
  "3463": "مَمْنُونٌ and related words stem from the root م-ن-ن, with the root verb مَنَّ meaning \"he bestowed a favor,\" \"he conferred a benefit,\" or \"he cut off.\" مَمْنُونٌ is a passive form meaning \"cut off,\" \"interrupted,\" or \"severed.\" The root conveys dual concepts of generosity and termination, reflecting that what is granted can also be taken away. In some contexts, مَمْنُونٌ highlights the temporary nature of worldly favors, reminding us that all blessings in this life are finite. When contrasted with Allah’s (ﷻ) favors, which are continuous and unceasing for those who earn His pleasure, it highlights the ultimate, eternal blessings of the Hereafter that are neither diminished nor cut off.",
  "3464": "The pronoun مَن refers to people, translating to \"who,\" \"whom,\" or \"whoever.\" It functions both as a relative pronoun, introducing clauses that give more information about a person or group, and as an interrogative pronoun to ask questions about people. In the Qur'an, مَن often implies \"whoever,\" emphasizing free will and personal responsibility, where one's actions lead to either reward or punishment.",
  "3465": "مَنَاةُ and related words stem from the root م-ن-ى, with the root verb مَنَىٰ meaning \"he determined,\" \"he allotted,\" or \"he destined.\" مَنَاةُ is the name of a pre-Islamic idol worshipped as a goddess of fate or destiny. The root emphasizes assigning, measuring, and predetermining, reflecting the misguided belief in idols controlling fate. This highlights the error of attributing destiny to false deities and serves as a reminder that Allah (ﷻ) alone determines and governs all affairs with justice and wisdom.",
  "3466": "مَنَازِلُ and related words stem from the root ن-ز-ل, with the root verb نَزَلَ meaning \"he descended,\" or \"he lodged.\" مَنَازِلُ (plural of مَنْزِلٌ) means \"dwelling places,\" \"stations,\" or \"abodes,\" representing places where one descends, pauses, or resides temporarily. The connection lies in the idea of places of settlement or stopping points on a journey. Metaphorically, مَنَازِلُ can symbolize phases of life, spiritual progression, or stages in a process, each serving as a temporary station before moving onward. This reflects the transient nature of existence, emphasizing the significance of each phase or step in a broader journey.",
  "3467": "مَنَاصٌ and related words stem from the root ن-و-ص, with the root verb نَاصَ meaning \"he turned aside or fled,\" \"he drew back, retreated, or escaped,\" and \"he sought safety or became secure.\" مَنَاصٌ means \"a place to which one flees\" or \"a place of safety,\" embodying the root's broader themes of evasion, retreat, and seeking refuge. The connection reflects moments of desperation when individuals seek to avoid impending consequences or danger, yet realize that there is no true escape from divine decree. This term emphasizes the inevitability of accountability and the futility of fleeing from Allah’s (ﷻ) will, highlighting the root's powerful focus on retreat and seeking protection.",
  "3468": "مَنَافِعُ and related words stem from the root ن-ف-ع, with the root verb نَفَعَ meaning \"he benefited\" or \"he was useful.\" مَنَافِعُ means \"benefits\" or \"advantages.\" The connection lies in the multitude of useful outcomes or profits derived from something, directly relating to the root's meaning. It highlights the abundance and variety of benefits available, encouraging gratitude and recognition of the blessings provided.",
  "3469": "مَنَاكِبَ and related words stem from the root ن-ك-ب, with the root verb نَكَبَ meaning \"he turned aside\" or \"he avoided.\" مَنَاكِبَ means \"shoulders\" or \"sides,\" referring to prominent or elevated parts, such as the shoulders of the body or the sides of the earth. The connection lies in the root’s concept of turning or inclining, as shoulders symbolize the ability to pivot or move. In the context of the earth, it reflects its diverse terrains and the human capacity to navigate, explore, and utilize its resources.",
  "3470": "مَنَامٌ and related words stem from the root ن-و-م, with the root verb نَامَ meaning \"he slept.\" مَنَامٌ translates to \"sleep\" or \"dream,\" referring to the state of sleeping, the experiences within it, or the time of sleep. This term reflects the root's fundamental concept of rest and unconsciousness, essential for rejuvenation. In classical Arabic, مَنَامٌ can denote the act of sleeping or the dreams occurring during sleep. Expressions like رَأَىٰ فِي مَنَامِهِ (\"he saw in his sleep\") are commonly understood to mean \"he saw in his dream,\" emphasizing the intrinsic connection between sleep and dreaming.",
  "3471": "مَنْثُورٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ث-ر, with the root verb نَثَرَ meaning \"he scattered\" or \"he dispersed.\" مَنْثُورٌ is a passive form meaning \"scattered\" or \"dispersed,\" describing something that has been spread widely. The root extends to themes of diffusion and separation, emphasizing the act of scattering from a central point.",
  "3472": "مَنْسَكٌ and related words stem from the root ن-س-ك, with the root verb نَسَكَ meaning \"he devoted himself to worship\" or \"he performed acts of devotion.\" مَنْسَكٌ refers to \"a rite\" or \"an act of worship,\" especially in the context of religious ceremonies and rituals. The connection lies in how مَنْسَكٌ embodies the practices through which one expresses devotion and purity, directly relating to the root's emphasis on dedication and sanctity. This term highlights the importance of performing specific acts that bring one closer to Allah (ﷻ), reflecting the essence of worship in both action and intent.",
  "3473": "مَنْسِيٌّ and related words stem from the root ن-س-ي, with the root verb نَسِيَ meaning \"he forgot.\" مَنْسِيٌّ is a passive form meaning \"entirely disregarded\" or \"left out of mind.\" The root conveys themes of neglect and omission, and مَنْسِيٌّ emphasizes the state of being forgotten or purposefully overlooked. This term often describes something treated as insignificant or unworthy of remembrance, directly reflecting the root's focus on the consequences of memory lapse. The connection lies in being the object of forgetfulness, with an emphasis on its passive nature and lack of importance.",
  "3474": "مَنشُورٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ش-ر, with the root verb نَشَرَ meaning \"he spread out,\" \"he unfolded,\" or \"he opened.\" مَنشُورٌ is a passive form meaning \"that which is spread out,\" \"unfolded,\" or \"made manifest.\" The root highlights the state of being revealed or laid open. In the Qur'an, مَنشُورٌ often refers to scrolls or records spread open on the Day of Judgment, symbolizing the unveiling of deeds and the clarity of accountability. The term reflects themes of openness, revelation, and the undeniable truth of divine justice.",
  "3475": "مَنصُورٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ص-ر, with the root verb نَصَرَ meaning \"he helped.\" مَنصُورٌ is a passive form meaning \"helped\" or \"victorious,\" referring to someone who has received support or achieved triumph through assistance. The connection lies in the outcome of being aided, reflecting the root’s focus on support and success. مَنصُورٌ highlights the role of external help in attaining victory.",
  "3476": "مَنضُودٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ض-د, with the root verb نَضَدَ meaning \"he piled up,\" \"he arranged,\" or \"he set things in order by placing one upon another.\" مَنضُودٌ is a passive form meaning \"layered\" or \"piled up,\" referring to items deliberately arranged in an orderly manner. The root emphasizes meticulous organization and abundance, highlighting precision in stacking or layering. Whether describing blessings, provisions, or elements of punishment, مَنضُودٌ reflects the deliberate and purposeful arrangement of objects, highlighting the balance between abundance and orderliness in creation or divine action.",
  "3477": "مَنْطِقٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ط-ق, with the root verb نَطَقَ meaning \"he spoke\" or \"he uttered.\" مَنْطِقٌ refers to \"speech,\" \"utterance,\" or \"manner of speaking,\" emphasizing articulate and purposeful expression. The root highlights clarity and precision in communication, linking speech to thought and intention. This term highlights the significance of speech as a tool for understanding, interaction, and conveying meaning, reflecting the intellectual capacity to articulate ideas effectively.",
  "3478": "مَنْفُوشٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ف-ش, with the root verb نَفَشَ meaning \"he carded wool\" or \"he fluffed up.\" مَنْفُوشٌ is a passive form meaning \"fluffed up\" or \"carded.\" The connection lies in the imagery of wool expanded and dispersed after carding, directly relating to the root's meaning. In the Qur'anic context, it describes how mountains will become like fluffed-up wool on the Day of Judgment, symbolizing their complete disintegration and scattering.",
  "3479": "مَنْقُوصٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ق-ص, with the root verb نَقَصَ meaning \"he diminished\" or \"he decreased.\" مَنْقُوصٌ is a passive form meaning \"diminished\" or \"deficient.\" The connection lies in the state of being lessened or incomplete, directly relating to the root's meaning. It signifies something that has been reduced or is lacking in some aspect.",
  "3480": "مَنَعَ and related words stem from the root م-ن-ع, with the root verb meaning \"he prevented,\" \"he withheld,\" or \"he forbade.\" The root embodies the act of stopping, restraining, or holding back, reflecting authority and control over actions, outcomes, or access. ٱلْمَانِعُ, one of Allah’s (ﷻ) perfect names, means \"The Preventer\" or \"The Withholder,\" highlighting His supreme authority to withhold or prevent with divine wisdom. Unlike human withholding, often selfish or imperfect, Allah’s (ﷻ) withholding is purposeful, wise, and rooted in mercy, protecting creation from harm or delaying blessings for greater benefit. This name emphasizes His justice and mercy, guiding believers to trust in His plan.",
  "3481": "مَنُوعٌ and related words stem from the root م-ن-ع, with the root verb مَنَعَ meaning \"he prevented,\" \"he withheld,\" or \"he forbade.\" مَنُوعٌ means \"very withholding,\" \"stingy,\" or \"reluctant to give.\" The form reflects an excessive tendency to prevent or deny others access to good, aligning with the root's concept of obstruction or withholding. It characterizes a persistent trait of miserliness, where one actively refuses to share or provide, emphasizing selfishness and a lack of generosity. This word often describes someone deeply entrenched in the act of denying others their rightful dues or benefits.",
  "3482": "مَنُونٌ and related words stem from the root م-ن-ن, with the root verb مَنَّ meaning \"he bestowed a favor,\" \"he diminished,\" or \"he cut off.\" مَنُونٌ means \"death\" or \"fate,\" personified as that which cuts off life. The connection lies in the root’s dual meanings of bestowal and severance. Our physical bodies are a divine favor from Allah (ﷻ), enabling us to live, worship, and strive. Death ends this favor physically as the body diminishes and returns to its Creator. Yet, for those who seek Allah’s (ﷻ) ultimate favor, this severance becomes a gateway to eternal blessings in the afterlife.",
  "3483": "مَنِيٌّ stems from the root م-ن-ي, with the root verb مَنَى meaning \"he decreed\" or \"he determined.\" مَنِيٌّ refers to \"semen\" or \"sperm,\" highlighting the role of this fluid in the process of human creation. The root also conveys meanings like \"to ordain\" or \"to destine,\" emphasizing divine determination in life's creation and development. Additionally, it connects to concepts of fate and destiny, intertwining the physical aspect of procreation with metaphysical ideas of divine will and predestination. This term illustrates the profound link between biological processes and the divine plan.",
  "3484": "مَنٌّ and related words stem from the root م-ن-ن, with the root verb مَنَّ meaning \"he bestowed a favor\" or \"he conferred a benefit.\" مَنٌّ means both \"favor\" and \"manna,\" the miraculous food provided by Allah (ﷻ) to the Children of Israel, described in authentic hadiths as a sweet and nourishing substance. The root’s concept of gracious favor highlights manna as a divine provision, bestowed without effort by its recipients. Additionally, مَنٌّ conveys the broader meaning of \"favor,\" emphasizing the act of giving generously. Both meanings reflect Allah’s (ﷻ) unparalleled generosity and mercy, reminding believers of His continuous care and the importance of gratitude for His blessings.",
  "3485": "مَنَّاعٌ and related words stem from the root م-ن-ع, with the root verb مَنَعَ meaning \"he prevented,\" \"he withheld,\" or \"he forbade.\" مَنَّاعٌ is an intensive form, meaning \"habitual preventer,\" \"extremely withholding,\" or \"great hinderer.\" The connection lies in the habitual and excessive nature of prevention, reflecting the root's essence of obstruction and denial. This form intensifies the act of withholding, portraying someone who repeatedly and actively obstructs or denies good. It highlights a persistent characteristic of extreme selfishness and an almost deliberate refusal to contribute, making it a strong condemnation of a habitual negative trait.",
  "3486": "مَنَّ and related words stem from the root م-ن-ن, with the root verb مَنَّ meaning \"he bestowed a favor,\" \"he considered as a favor,\" or \"he reminded of a favor.\" The root also conveys meanings of diminishment and lessening, as reminding someone of a favor can reduce its value or create indebtedness. In human contexts, مَنَّ reflects generosity but also the imperfection of diminishing a gift’s worth by reproaching the recipient. Referring to Allah’s (ﷻ) acts of bestowal, it signifies immense, transformative blessings that uplift without reproach or diminishment. These gifts embody Allah’s (ﷻ) mercy, unmatched generosity, and perfect giving, contrasting with human limitations and modeling generosity.",
  "3487": "مَهِيلٌ and related words stem from the root ه-ي-ل, with the root verb هَالَ meaning \"to pile up\" or \"to pour.\" مَهِيلٌ describes something that becomes scattered or poured forth, often conveying the image of loose particles like sand being dispersed. The root highlights the notions of accumulation, pouring, or scattering, reflecting the transformation of solid or stable forms into loose, unstable matter. This connection highlights themes of impermanence and the fragility of material existence, as solid structures give way to fluid or scattered states.",
  "3488": "مَهِينٌ and related words stem from the root م-ه-ن, with the root verb مَهَنَ meaning \"he was despicable,\" \"he was lowly,\" or \"he was insignificant.\" مَهِينٌ means \"despicable,\" \"insignificant,\" \"worthless,\" or \"lowly.\" The term reflects the root's essence of lowness, baseness, or lack of value. It is often used to describe something or someone considered of little worth, standing, or esteem, emphasizing humility, weakness, or contempt in various contexts.",
  "3489": "مَهَّدَ and related words stem from the root م-ه-د, with the root verb مَهَدَ meaning \"he spread out,\" \"he smoothed,\" or \"he prepared.\" مَهَّدَ means \"he thoroughly prepared,\" \"he facilitated,\" or \"he made smooth,\" intensifying the root action of preparation. The root conveys themes of creating ease, making something level, or laying a foundation for stability. This term emphasizes meticulous effort in making a place or situation suitable, such as preparing a path, smoothing a surface, or laying groundwork for future outcomes.",
  "3490": "مَهِّلْ and related words also stem from the root م-ه-ل, with مَهَّلَ meaning \"he gave respite\" or \"he granted delay.\" مَهِّلْ is the command form, meaning \"give respite\" or \"proceed slowly,\" but with an intensified emphasis compared to أَمْهِلْ. This form suggests a deliberate and measured granting of time, often highlighting the intentional act of patience and slowing down, ensuring care and thoughtfulness in the process.",
  "3491": "مَهْجُورٌ and related words stem from the root ه-ج-ر, with the root verb هَجَرَ meaning \"he forsook,\" \"he abandoned,\" or \"he shunned.\" مَهْجُورٌ is a passive form meaning \"abandoned\" or \"forsaken,\" describing someone or something left behind, neglected, or cast aside. It embodies the root’s concept of disconnection, whether physical, emotional, or social, emphasizing the profound state of being separated or removed from relevance. The root’s broader meanings, including physical departure and social severance, reinforce the sense of intentional or consequential abandonment, central to مَهْجُورٌ as reflecting the impact of being forsaken or isolated.",
  "3492": "مَهْدٌ and related words stem from the root م-ه-د, with the root verb مَهَدَ meaning \"he spread out,\" \"he smoothed,\" or \"he prepared.\" مَهْدٌ refers to a \"cradle\" or \"bed,\" emphasizing the root’s concept of smoothing or preparing a place of comfort. A cradle, carefully designed for an infant’s rest, symbolizes care, nurturing, and foundational support at the start of life. Similarly, مَهْدٌ is also used in the Qur'an to describe the earth as a bed, highlighting Allah’s (ﷻ) preparation of the earth as a stable and nurturing dwelling for humanity. This term reflects themes of tenderness, preparation, and the deliberate effort to provide security and comfort, whether for the beginnings of life or as a foundation for living beings.",
  "3493": "مَهْزُومٌ and related words stem from the root ه-ز-م, with the root verb هَزَمَ meaning \"he defeated,\" \"he overcame,\" or \"he routed.\" مَهْزُومٌ is a passive form meaning \"defeated\" or \"overcome.\" This term connects to the root's concept by describing someone who has been vanquished. It reflects themes of loss and subjugation inherent in the root, emphasizing the state of being overpowered.",
  "3494": "مَهْلِكٌ and related words stem from the root ه-ل-ك, with the root verb هَلَكَ meaning \"he perished,\" \"he died,\" or \"he was destroyed.\" مَهْلِكٌ means \"place or time of destruction\" or \"peril.\" This term connects to the root's concept by indicating where or when destruction occurs. It reflects themes of danger and fatal outcomes inherent in the root, emphasizing critical points leading to demise.",
  "3495": "The pronoun مَهْما introduces conditional clauses expressing indefinite conditions, meaning \"whatever\" or \"no matter what.\" It emphasizes that the outcome applies universally, regardless of circumstances. مَهْما conveys flexibility in the condition or action, covering a wide range of possibilities. In the Qur'an, مَهْما reinforces that divine laws remain constant, regardless of human actions or worldly conditions, highlighting Allah’s (ﷻ) wisdom and justice, applicable in every situation, no matter what anyone attempts to oppose His decree.",
  "3496": "مَوَاخِرُ and related words stem from the root م-خ-ر, with the root verb مَخَرَ meaning \"he cleaved,\" referring to the act of cutting through water. مَوَاخِرُ (plural of مَاخِرَةٌ) describes objects or entities that cleave or cut through a medium, particularly referring to the motion of ships furrowing through the sea. The connection lies in the vivid imagery of cutting or splitting, embodying the root's essence of movement and impact. It emphasizes the dynamic act of cleaving through water, symbolizing strength, purpose, and the transformative interaction with the surrounding environment.",
  "3497": "مَواضِعُ and related words stem from the root و-ض-ع, with the root verb وَضَعَ meaning \"he placed\" or \"he set down.\" مَوْضِعٌ means \"place,\" \"location,\" or \"position,\" and مَواضِعُ is its plural form. The connection to the root is direct, referring to locations where things are placed or situated. It emphasizes specific spots or contexts, highlighting the importance of position and placement in understanding events or actions.",
  "3498": "مَواطِنُ and related words stem from the root و-ط-ن, with the root verb وَطَنَ meaning \"he dwelt\" or \"he resided.\" مَوْطِنٌ means \"homeland,\" \"place of residence,\" or \"location,\" and مَواطِنُ is its plural form. The connection to the root involves the idea of a place where one settles or resides, emphasizing the significance of specific locations in one's life. In the Qur'an, it refers to places where significant events occur, highlighting the importance of context and setting.",
  "3499": "مَواقِعٌ and related words stem from the root و-ق-ع, with the root verb وَقَعَ meaning \"he fell\" or \"it occurred.\" مَواقِعٌ (plural of مَوْقِعٌ) translates as \"positions,\" \"places of occurrence,\" or \"locations where something falls or happens.\" The connection lies in the idea of events or actions \"falling\" into predetermined locations, emphasizing the precision and inevitability of such occurrences. Just as something that falls comes to rest at a specific spot, مَواقِعٌ signifies places where significant events unfold according to Allah's (ﷻ) decree. This reflects the root's emphasis on the certainty and designated nature of occurrences, illustrating divine order and predestination.",
  "3500": "مَوَالِيَ and related words stem from the root و-ل-ي, with the root verb وَلِيَ meaning \"he was near,\" \"he befriended,\" or \"he protected.\" مَوَالِيَ (plural of مَوْلًى) means \"protectors,\" \"heirs,\" \"successors,\" or \"allies,\" reflecting relationships of guardianship, closeness, and mutual support. ٱلْوَالِي, one of Allah's (ﷻ) perfect names, means \"The Protecting Guardian,\" highlighting His role as the one who governs and protects all creation. It emphasizes His ultimate authority, care, and management of all affairs. This name reminds us to rely on Allah’s (ﷻ) constant guardianship, as He alone is the true protector and source of support in all aspects of life.",
  "3501": "مَوَدَّةٌ and related words stem from the root و-د-د, with the root verb وَدَّ meaning \"he loved,\" \"he desired,\" or \"he wished.\" مَوَدَّةٌ means \"affection,\" \"love,\" or \"friendship.\" The connection lies in the expression of love and desire for goodwill, directly reflecting the root's emphasis on affection. This term embodies deep emotional bonds and sincere feelings of warmth and friendship between individuals.",
  "3502": "مَوْءُودَةٌ and related words stem from the root و-أ-د, with the root verb وَأَدَ meaning \"he buried his daughter alive.\" مَوْءُودَةٌ refers specifically to \"a female infant who was buried alive.\" The connection lies in the cruel pre-Islamic practice of burying daughters alive due to shame or fear of poverty, directly relating to the root's meaning of suppressing or extinguishing life. This term highlights a grave moral injustice, highlighting the sanctity of life and the prohibition of such inhumane acts in Islam.",
  "3503": "مَوْئِلٌ and related words stem from the root و-أ-ل, with the root verb وَأَلَ meaning \"he returned to\" or \"he sought refuge.\" مَوْئِلٌ means \"a place of refuge\" or \"a place of escape,\" emphasizing a location one turns to for safety or protection. The connection lies in the idea of returning or resorting to a secure place during times of need, directly reflecting the root’s focus on seeking shelter or solace. This term captures the human instinct to find security in moments of danger or uncertainty, symbolizing both physical refuge and emotional or spiritual comfort.",
  "3504": "مَوْبِقٌ and related words stem from the root و-ب-ق, with the root verb وَبَقَ meaning \"he perished,\" \"he was destroyed,\" or \"he was ruined.\" مَوْبِقٌ refers to \"a barrier of destruction\" or \"a place of ruin.\" The root conveys themes of calamity, overwhelming loss, and entrapment, emphasizing the inescapable nature of destruction. مَوْبِقٌ describes the actual separation or chasm placed on the Day of Judgment, highlighting Allah’s (ﷻ) justice and the ultimate consequences of wrongdoing, where alliances or transgressions result in irrevocable separation and ruin.",
  "3505": "مَوْتٌ stems from the root م-و-ت, with the root verb مَاتَ meaning \"he died.\" مَوْتٌ refers to \"death,\" representing the general concept of life's cessation. It encompasses the inevitability of death as a universal reality and serves as a reminder of life's transience. This term encourages reflection on the fleeting nature of existence and the importance of preparing for the hereafter through righteous deeds.",
  "3506": "مَوْتَةٌ and related words stem from the root م-و-ت, with the root verb مَاتَ meaning \"he died.\" مَوْتَةٌ refers to \"an instance of dying\" or \"a single death,\" emphasizing a specific occurrence of death. It is often used in discussions about the afterlife, such as \"the first death\" or \"the second death,\" to highlight distinct stages within the broader cycle of life and mortality. The term highlights the progression of existence and the transformative nature of death.",
  "3507": "مَوْثِقٌ and related words stem from the root و-ث-ق, with the root verb وَثَقَ meaning \"he trusted\" or \"he was firm or secure.\" مَوْثِقٌ means \"a binding pledge,\" \"a firm promise,\" or \"a security.\" The connection lies in the concept of trustworthiness and firmness in keeping promises, directly reflecting the root's emphasis on reliability and security. This term highlights the importance of commitments and the moral obligation to uphold agreements.",
  "3508": "مَوْجٌ and related words stem from the root م-و-ج, with the root verb مَاجَ meaning \"it surged\" or \"it moved turbulently.\" مَوْجٌ means \"wave\" or \"surge.\" The connection lies in the root's concept of movement and agitation, reflecting the dynamic and often turbulent nature of waves. It symbolizes life's ups and downs and the power of Allah's (ﷻ) creation.",
  "3509": "مَوْرٌ and related words stem from the root م-و-ر, with the root verb مَارَ meaning \"it moved from side to side,\" \"it was in a state of tumult,\" or \"it was in a state of commotion.\" مَوْرٌ means \"tumultuously,\" \"in commotion,\" or \"turbulently,\" capturing the essence of instability and movement. This term vividly illustrates the chaotic and unpredictable nature of the material world, symbolizing the transient and fragile state of creation. The connection highlights the importance of recognizing Allah’s (ﷻ) control over all forms of motion and commotion, reminding us to seek spiritual grounding amidst life’s inevitable upheavals.",
  "3510": "مَوْرُودٌ and related words stem from the root و-ر-د, with the root verb وَرَدَ meaning \"he came\" or \"he arrived.\" مَوْرُودٌ is a passive form meaning \"that which is approached\" or \"destination.\" The connection lies in being the object of arrival or the endpoint of a journey, embodying the root's emphasis on reaching a destination. This term can represent goals, objectives, or even challenges that one encounters on life's path, highlighting the significance of purpose and direction.",
  "3511": "مَوْزُونٌ and related words stem from the root و-ز-ن, with the root verb وَزَنَ meaning \"he weighed.\" مَوْزُونٌ is a passive form meaning \"weighed\" or \"measured.\" The connection lies in being subjected to evaluation or balance, reflecting the root's concept of weighing. This term signifies precision and fairness, whether in physical measurement or in assessing actions and intentions, emphasizing the importance of justice and equilibrium.",
  "3512": "مَوْضُوعَةٌ and related words stem from the root و-ض-ع, with the root verb وَضَعَ meaning \"he placed\" or \"he set down.\" مَوْضُوعَةٌ is a passive form meaning \"placed,\" \"set down,\" or \"laid.\" It can refer to something that has been established or instituted. The connection to the root emphasizes the state of being positioned or assigned, reflecting the act of placement or establishment. In the Qur'an, it describes scales that are \"set up\" for judgment.",
  "3513": "مَوْضُونَةٌ and related words stem from the root و-ض-ن, with the root verb وَضَنَ meaning \"he wove closely\" or \"he made firm.\" مَوْضُونَةٌ is a passive form meaning \"closely woven\" or \"well-knit.\" It describes items that are intricately crafted, such as fine fabrics or adorned furnishings. The connection to the root emphasizes tight weaving or firm construction, reflecting quality, strength, and elegance. In the Qur'an, it is used to describe luxurious couches in Paradise, highlighting their exquisite craftsmanship.",
  "3514": "مَوْطِئٌ and related words stem from the root و-ط-أ, with the root verb وَطِئَ meaning \"he trod upon\" or \"he stepped.\" مَوْطِئٌ means \"footing,\" \"surface,\" or \"place of treading.\" The connection to the root lies in the physical act of stepping or walking upon something, emphasizing areas where one sets foot. Beyond its literal meaning, it can symbolize opportunities, positions, or roles that one occupies, reflecting the foundational support or path one takes. This extends to broader themes of stability, preparation, and the deliberate actions that shape one’s journey or position.",
  "3515": "مَوْعُودٌ and related words stem from the root و-ع-د, with the root verb وَعَدَ meaning \"he promised.\" مَوْعُودٌ is a passive form meaning \"promised\" or \"that which is promised.\" The connection lies in being the recipient or object of a promise, highlighting the anticipation and trust placed in the fulfillment of that promise. This reflects the root's emphasis on commitment and the importance of keeping one's word, highlighting the value of reliability.",
  "3516": "مَوْعِدٌ and related words stem from the root و-ع-د, with the root verb وَعَدَ meaning \"he promised.\" مَوْعِدٌ means \"appointed time\" or \"appointment.\" The connection is the establishment of a specific time or place based on a promise, reflecting the root's focus on commitment and reliability. This emphasizes the importance of honoring agreed-upon times, reinforcing trust and accountability in social and personal interactions.",
  "3517": "مَوْعِدَةٌ and related words stem from the root و-ع-د, with the root verb وَعَدَ meaning \"he promised.\" مَوْعِدَةٌ means \"promise\" or \"appointed time.\" The connection lies in the commitment to fulfill an obligation at a specified time, highlighting the root's emphasis on reliability and trustworthiness. This underscores the moral duty to honor one's word, which strengthens bonds and fosters mutual respect.",
  "3518": "مَوْعِظَةٌ and related words stem from the root و-ع-ظ, with the root verb وَعَظَ meaning \"he admonished\" or \"he advised.\" مَوْعِظَةٌ means \"admonition,\" \"exhortation,\" or \"sermon.\" It refers to words of guidance intended to influence moral conduct or inspire reflection. The connection to the root emphasizes the act of delivering important advice or warnings, highlighting the significance of sincere counsel in guiding others toward righteousness.",
  "3519": "مَوْفُورٌ and related words stem from the root و-ف-ر, with the root verb وَفَرَ meaning \"he increased\" or \"he became abundant.\" مَوْفُورٌ is a passive form meaning \"abundant,\" \"ample,\" or \"full.\" The connection to the root emphasizes the state of being plentiful or complete. It often describes wealth, provisions, or blessings that are abundant and sufficient, highlighting the generosity and bounty that one may receive.",
  "3520": "مَوْقُوتٌ and related words stem from the root و-ق-ت, with the root verb وَقَتَ meaning \"he fixed a time.\" مَوْقُوتٌ is a passive form meaning \"fixed\" or \"appointed.\" The connection lies in being designated to occur at a specific time, reflecting the root's focus on time allocation. This emphasizes the importance of observing prescribed times, such as for prayers or rituals, reinforcing discipline and obedience in fulfilling obligations at their proper times.",
  "3521": "مَوْقُوذَةٌ and related words stem from the root و-ق-ذ, with the root verb وَقَذَ meaning \"he struck\" or \"he beat violently.\" مَوْقُوذَةٌ refers to \"an animal beaten to death,\" which is prohibited for consumption in Islamic dietary laws. The connection lies in the violent method of death, emphasizing the root's focus on fatal striking. This term highlights the importance of adhering to Allah's (ﷻ) guidance regarding lawful and wholesome provisions, reflecting the broader principles of purity, ethics, and mindfulness in consumption.",
  "3522": "مَوْقُوفُونَ and related words stem from the root و-ق-ف, with the root verb وَقَفَ meaning \"he stood\" or \"he stopped.\" مَوْقُوفُونَ is a passive form meaning \"those who are stopped\" or \"those who are made to stand.\" The root conveys themes of halting, standing still, or being restrained, often implying a deliberate pause or cessation. The connection lies in being brought to a halt, reflecting the root's emphasis on immobility and accountability, often symbolizing moments of reckoning or awaiting judgment.",
  "3523": "مَوْلًى and related words stem from the root و-ل-ي, with the root verb وَلِيَ meaning \"he was near,\" \"he befriended,\" or \"he protected.\" The root conveys broader concepts of nearness, guardianship, authority, alliance, and mutual support. مَوْلًى means \"master\" or \"protector\" but can also signify \"dependent\" or \"one being protected,\" reflecting the dual nature of the term. This reciprocal relationship highlights the root's emphasis on closeness and interconnected roles, whether through authority, support, or reliance, emphasizing bonds of trust and responsibility.",
  "3524": "مَوْلُودٌ and related words stem from the root و-ل-د, with the root verb وَلَدَ meaning \"he begot\" or \"he gave birth.\" مَوْلُودٌ primarily means \"one who is born\" or \"newborn,\" directly reflecting the root's core concept of birth and procreation. Depending on context, it can also refer to \"the one to whom the child is born,\" emphasizing relational roles tied to the act of birth. This duality highlights the root’s broader focus on lineage, relationships, and the continuation of life.",
  "3525": "مَيِّتٌ stems from the root م-و-ت, with the root verb مَاتَ meaning \"he died.\" مَيِّتٌ means \"one who will die\" or \"a living being destined to die,\" emphasizing the certainty of mortality for all living creatures. This term highlights the fragility of life and serves as a reminder of human mortality, urging individuals to reflect on their finite existence and their responsibilities in this world.",
  "3526": "مَيْتٌ stems from the root م-و-ت, with the root verb مَاتَ meaning \"he died.\" مَيْتٌ refers to \"a dead person\" or \"something devoid of life,\" often describing those who have already passed away or inanimate entities like a lifeless earth. The term emphasizes the state of being lifeless and invites contemplation on the impermanence of worldly matters and the inevitable return to Allah (ﷻ).",
  "3527": "مَيْتَةٌ and related words stem from the root م-و-ت, with the root verb مَاتَ meaning \"he died.\" مَيْتَةٌ refers to \"a carcass\" or \"a dead animal,\" particularly one that has not been slaughtered according to Islamic law. More generally, مَيْتَةٌ also encompasses the concept of lifelessness, such as a stillborn fetus, an animal born dead, or a dead earth, highlighting a state devoid of vitality or productivity. The term reflects the broader theme of the cessation of life, emphasizing the natural cycle of life and death, as well as the transformative potential of divine intervention, as Allah (ﷻ) revives what is lifeless.",
  "3528": "مَيْسَرَةٌ and related words stem from the root ي-س-ر, with the root verb يَسَرَ meaning \"it became easy.\" مَيْسَرَةٌ means \"ease\" or \"prosperity,\" denoting a state of financial comfort or affluence. The root conveys broader concepts of ease, simplicity, facilitation, and abundance. The connection lies in the root's focus on alleviating hardship and promoting abundance, reflecting a state where resources and opportunities are readily accessible, fostering stability and well-being.",
  "3529": "مَيْسُورٌ and related words stem from the root ي-س-ر, with the root verb يَسَرَ meaning \"it became easy.\" The root conveys broader concepts of ease, simplicity, facilitation, and accessibility, emphasizing the removal of obstacles and the smooth accomplishment of tasks. مَيْسُورٌ means \"easily,\" \"feasibly,\" or \"gently,\" referring to something done within one’s means or capability. The nuance lies in its focus on actions or responses that are approachable, manageable, and free of hardship, reflecting the root's essence of enabling ease and fostering gentleness in behavior and dealings.",
  "3530": "مَيْسِرٌ and related words stem from the root ي-س-ر, with the root verb يَسَرَ meaning \"it became easy.\" The root encompasses broader concepts of ease, simplicity, and facilitation. مَيْسِرٌ refers to \"gambling\" or \"games of chance,\" perceived by humans as an easy way to gain wealth. However, the root reflects that this perceived simplicity is deceptive—gambling lacks true effort and purpose, leading to instability and turmoil. Rather than fostering ease and prosperity, it destroys spiritual and physical well-being, undermines family structures, and disrupts societal harmony.",
  "3531": "مَيْلٌ and related words stem from the root م-ي-ل, with the root verb مَالَ meaning \"he inclined,\" \"he leaned,\" or \"he bent.\" مَيْلٌ means \"inclination\" or \"deviation,\" reflecting both physical leaning and metaphorical tendencies, such as biases or preferences. The connection lies in a natural movement toward or away from something, highlighting a departure from neutrality or uprightness.",
  "3532": "مَيْلَةٌ and related words stem from the root م-ي-ل, with the root verb مَالَ meaning \"he inclined,\" \"he leaned,\" or \"he bent.\" مَيْلَةٌ refers to \"a single act of inclining,\" \"an overthrow,\" or \"an attack,\" especially in contexts implying a decisive or sudden movement. The term reflects the forceful or abrupt nature of inclining, emphasizing a shift that can signify aggression or dominance.",
  "3533": "مَيْمَنَةٌ and related words stem from the root ي-م-ن, with the root verb يُمِنَ meaning \"he was prosperous\" or \"he was fortunate.\" مَيْمَنَةٌ means \"the right-hand side\" or \"right wing,\" often associated with blessings or good fortune. The connection lies in the right side's representation of favor and success, directly reflecting the root's emphasis on prosperity, positive outcomes, and well-being.",
  "3534": "مُؤَجَّلٌ and related words stem from the root أ-ج-ل, with the root verb أَجَلَ meaning \"he deferred\" or \"he delayed.\" أَجَّلَ means \"he defined the term,\" \"assigned,\" \"appointed,\" or \"delayed,\" emphasizing the act of specifying or postponing something to a later time. مُؤَجَّلٌ is a passive form meaning \"deferred\" or \"postponed,\" referring to something that is not only set for a specific time but also delayed until that exact moment. This reflects the root's core idea of determination along with delay, highlighting both its fixed timing and extension.",
  "3535": "مُؤَذِّنٌ and related words stem from the root أ-ذ-ن, with the root verb أَذِنَ meaning \"he listened\" or \"he permitted.\" The root also conveys meanings of being attentive, granting access, or making something known. مُؤَذِّنٌ means \"an announcer,\" someone tasked with delivering an important proclamation. In the Qur'an, it refers to announcing significant news or decisions. This role reflects the responsibility of transforming attentiveness into the active conveyance of messages. An example of this in practice is the مُؤَذِّن who announces the call to prayer, inviting people to listen and respond to the reminder of worship.",
  "3536": "مُؤَلَّفَةٌ and related words stem from the root أ-ل-ف, with the root verb أَلِفَ meaning \"he became familiar\" or \"he was accustomed.\" أَلَّفَ means \"he united\" or \"he joined together,\" and مُؤَلَّفَةٌ is a passive form meaning \"one who is made to incline\" or \"one who is conciliated.\" The root emphasizes familiarity, unity, and forming bonds. The phrase مُؤَلَّفَةُ قُلُوبُهُمْ refers to a group whose hearts are softened or inclined, a category eligible for zakat, including new converts or individuals whose faith is not yet firmly established. This fosters familiarity and unity, strengthening the bonds of faith within the community.",
  "3537": "مُؤْتُونَ and related words stem from the root أ-ت-ى, with the root verb أَتَى meaning \"he came\" or \"he arrived.\" آتَى means \"he gave\" or \"he bestowed,\" while مُؤْتُونَ refers to \"those who give.\" The connection lies in actively causing something to come to another, reflecting the root's focus on purposeful arrival transformed into the act of giving. This term emphasizes the role of generosity and the deliberate effort to provide for others.",
  "3538": "مُؤْتَفِكَةٌ and related words stem from the root أ-ف-ك, with the root verb أَفَكَ meaning \"he turned away,\" \"he lied,\" or \"he changed his/its manner of being.\" مُؤْتَفِكَةٌ means \"overturned city\" or \"overthrown community,\" referring to towns destroyed due to their transgressions. The connection lies in the root's theme of turning away, which manifests in the literal overturning of these cities as a consequence of persistent falsehood and deviation from the truth. In the Qur'an, it serves as a stark warning of the dire consequences of moral corruption.",
  "3539": "مُؤْصَدَةٌ and related words stem from the root و-ص-د, with the root verb أَوْصَدَ meaning \"he closed firmly\" or \"he shut tight.\" مُؤْصَدَةٌ is a passive form meaning \"closed over,\" \"shut tightly,\" or \"sealed.\" The connection to the root involves the action of securely closing something, leaving no possibility of escape or entry. In the Qur'anic context, it describes the gates of Hell being closed over the disbelievers, highlighting the inescapable and final nature of their punishment.",
  "3540": "مُؤْمِنٌ and related words stem from the root أ-م-ن, with the root verb آمَنَ meaning \"he believed\" or \"he had faith.\" مُؤْمِنٌ means \"believer\" or \"one who has faith,\" describing someone who trusts and relies on Allah (ﷻ), embodying the root's emphasis on trust, security, and assurance. This term highlights a believer's inner peace and resilience derived from their unwavering conviction in Allah's (ﷻ) wisdom and guidance. ٱلْمُؤْمِنُ, one of Allah's (ﷻ) beautiful names, means \"The Giver of Faith\" or \"The Granter of Security,\" emphasizing His role in instilling faith, providing spiritual guidance, and ensuring protection and safety in both this life and the Hereafter.",
  "3541": "مُؤْمِنَةٌ and related words stem from the root أ-م-ن, with the root verb آمَنَ meaning \"he believed\" or \"he had faith.\" مُؤْمِنَةٌ means \"believer\" or \"faithful woman.\" The connection lies in a person who places her trust and belief in Allah (ﷻ), reflecting the root’s emphasis on trust, security, and assurance. مُؤْمِنَةٌ embodies faith, peace and resilience.",
  "3542": "مُبارَكٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ر-ك, with the root verb بَرَكَ meaning \"he or it was firm, steady, or fixed,\" or \"he or it continued, remained, or stayed.\" مُبارَكٌ means \"blessed\" or \"endowed with blessings.\" Reflecting the root's sense of stability, مُبارَكٌ describes something with enduring, divinely given benefits. The term suggests continuous, fruitful growth, much like بَرَك (a pool of water), which provides life and nourishment in the desert. In the Qur'an, مُبارَكٌ is used for people, places, and objects that offer lasting guidance or goodness, marking them as special sources of Allah’s (ﷻ) blessings.",
  "3543": "مُبارَكَةٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ر-ك, with the root verb بَرَكَ meaning \"he or it was firm, steady, or fixed,\" or \"he or it continued, remained, or stayed.\" مُبارَكَةٌ means \"blessed\" or \"endowed with blessings.\" Reflecting the root’s sense of continuity and stability, مُبارَكَةٌ describes something with enduring, divinely given benefits. Symbolically, it is linked to بَرَك (a pool of water), a life-sustaining source in deserts, illustrating blessings that nourish and persist. In the Qur'an, مُبارَكَةٌ describes objects or places of Allah’s (ﷻ) special favor, bringing lasting goodness or guidance.",
  "3544": "مُبَدِّلٌ and related words stem from the root ب-د-ل, with the root verb بَدَلَ meaning \"he exchanged\" or \"he replaced.\" بَدَّلَ, an intensified form, means \"he changed\" or \"he altered,\" implying a more deliberate transformation. مُبَدِّلٌ translates as \"one who changes\" or \"alterer.\" The root emphasizes substitution or transformation, and مُبَدِّلٌ identifies the agent responsible for this change. This term highlights the role and impact of an individual or force in causing transformation, whether through replacement, alteration, or exchange, reflecting the root’s concept of purposeful and significant change.",
  "3545": "مُبَذِّرٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ذ-ر, with the root verb بَذَرَ meaning \"he scattered\" or \"he sowed seeds.\" مُبَذِّرٌ means \"one who wastes\" or \"a spendthrift,\" referring to someone who squanders resources through excessive or irresponsible behavior. The root conveys the idea of scattering, which, when done carelessly, leads to wastefulness. مُبَذِّرٌ highlights the negative traits of extravagance and misuse of resources, emphasizing the importance of adhering to Allah’s (ﷻ) commands to manage blessings responsibly and avoid wastefulness.",
  "3546": "مُبَرَّءُونَ and related words stem from the root ب-ر-أ, with the root verb بَرَأَ meaning \"he became free from\" or \"he disassociated from,\" and بَرَّأَ meaning \"he acquitted\" or \"he declared free from guilt.\" مُبَرَّءُونَ is a passive form meaning \"those who are exonerated\" or \"those absolved,\" referring to individuals cleared of blame or wrongdoing. The connection to the root lies in the concept of separation, where exoneration signifies being freed or detached from accusations or faults. The root conveys themes of purity, freedom, and vindication, emphasizing the restoration of honor through truth and justice.",
  "3547": "مُبَشِّرٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ش-ر, with the root verb بَشِرَ meaning \"he rejoiced\" or \"he was cheerful,\" and بَشَّرَ meaning \"he gave glad tidings\" or \"he informed of good news.\" مُبَشِّرٌ means \"one who brings good news,\" emphasizing an active, intentional role in delivering glad tidings. This term highlights a purposeful mission to spread encouragement, where the bearer seeks to uplift and inspire others. Unlike بَشِيرٌ, which may convey a natural or inherent source of encouragement, مُبَشِّرٌ reflects a deliberate effort to share joy and foster hope, often sparking a transformative and uplifting response.",
  "3548": "مُبَشِّرَاتٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ش-ر, with the root verb بَشِرَ meaning \"he rejoiced\" or \"he was cheerful,\" and بَشَّرَ meaning \"he gave glad tidings\" or \"he informed of good news.\" مُبَشِّرَاتٌ means \"those who bring or deliver good news,\" often referring to natural phenomena, like winds that signal rain, symbolizing renewal and sustenance. The root emphasizes delivering news that brings joy, relief, and reassurance, while مُبَشِّرَاتٌ highlights how such signs foster hope and security. Unlike بَشِيرٌ, which represents a natural source of encouragement, مُبَشِّرَاتٌ suggests intentional or active signs that uplift and refresh the spirit.",
  "3549": "مُبَوَّأَ and related words stem from the root ب-و-أ, with the root verb بَاءَ meaning \"he returned\" or \"he withdrew.\" It can also imply \"returning with something,\" often indicating a sense of responsibility or burden. مُبَوَّأَ refers to a place of dwelling or a settled location. It can signify a residence, station, or position prepared for someone. The term emphasizes a fixed place designed for stability, comfort, or strategic importance. The root meaning highlights that after a return or withdrawal, particularly when burdened with responsibility, one requires a place of settlement to find stability and relief.",
  "3550": "مُبَيِّنَة and related words stem from the root ب-ي-ن, with the root verb بَانَ meaning \"it became separated, severed, disunited, or cut off,\" or \"it became apparent, manifest, evident, or clear\" or \"it became distinct,\" implying separation from others. مُبَيِّنَة means \"something that is clear\" or \"something that makes clear,\" referring to anything that actively provides clarity or explanation. The root also conveys ideas of separating and distinguishing, as if bringing something out of obscurity. مُبَيِّنَة thus implies an active role in revealing or illuminating, highlighting an object or idea that clarifies by distinguishing truth from ambiguity.",
  "3551": "مُبِينٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ي-ن, with the root verb بَانَ meaning \"it became separated, severed, disunited, or cut off,\" or \"it became apparent, manifest, evident, or clear\" or \"it became distinct,\" implying separation from others. مُبِينٌ means \"clear\" or \"evident,\" often used to describe something unmistakably obvious or self-explanatory. The root also conveys ideas of separation and distinction, as if something stands apart in clarity. مُبِينٌ emphasizes a clarity so strong that it separates truth from falsehood, making something evident and leaving no room for confusion.",
  "3552": "مُبْتَلِينَ and related words stem from the root ب-ل-و, with the root verb بَلَا meaning \"he tested\" or \"he tried,\" referring to testing in a general sense to reveal the nature of someone or something. مُبْتَلِينَ means \"the Ones who test,\" referring to Allah (ﷻ) as the examiner who brings about trials to assess the sincerity and endurance of His servants. The root also carries the meaning of \"smelting,\" a process of purifying metal through intense heat. This metaphor highlights how trials refine and purify a person's character and faith, revealing their true qualities, much like smelting reveals the pure essence of metal.",
  "3553": "مُبْدِي and related words stem from the root ب-د-و, with the root verb بَدَا meaning \"he or it became apparent\" or \"he or it appeared.\" مُبْدِي means \"one who reveals\" or \"one who makes apparent,\" emphasizing the act of disclosing or bringing hidden matters to light. The root conveys themes of appearance, revelation, and making things visible. مُبْدِي reflects the role of unveiling truths or manifesting hidden realities, and in the Qur'an, it highlights Allah’s (ﷻ) power to reveal and make known what is concealed.",
  "3554": "مُبْرِمُونَ and related words stem from the root ب-ر-م, with the root verb بَرِمَ meaning \"he was affected with disgust, loathing, or vexation,\" often implying irritation that prompts decisive action. أَبْرَمَ means \"he made it of two strands and twisted it,\" or \"he made firm or strong,\" referring to intertwining ropes for added strength and security. مُبْرِمُونَ means \"ones who firmly establish, arrange, or settle matters,\" reflecting the root’s idea of reinforcing through twisting, resolutely setting plans and making them firm. While for humans this resolve stems from emotion, limited knowledge, or defiance, Allah (ﷻ), to whom belongs the highest example, decrees with perfect authority, wisdom, and justice.",
  "3555": "مُبْصِرٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ص-ر, with the root verb بَصُرَ meaning \"he saw\" or \"he was endowed with mental perception, belief, knowledge, understanding, intelligence, or skill.\" مُبْصِرٌ refers to \"one who enables seeing or gives light,\" describing something that illuminates or brings insight. The root conveys themes of clarity, illumination, and discernment, linking physical sight with mental and spiritual perception. This term highlights both light, which allows vision, and remembrance of Allah (ﷻ), which enlightens the heart and grants true insight.",
  "3556": "مُبْصِرَةٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ص-ر, with the root verb بَصُرَ meaning \"he saw\" or \"he was, or became, endowed with mental perception; or belief, or firm belief; or knowledge, understanding, intelligence, or skill.\" مُبْصِرَةٌ refers to \"something that makes or causes one to see, or gives insight or clarity.\" In the Qur'an, it describes signs and miracles that provide clear evidence and understanding, enabling people to see the truth both physically and spiritually. These signs act as reminders from Allah (ﷻ), guiding believers to recognize His power and wisdom.",
  "3557": "مُبْطِلُونَ and related words stem from the root ب-ط-ل, with the root verb بَطَلَ meaning \"it was, or became, false, untrue, fictitious, spurious, unfounded, or unsound.\" مُبْطِلُونَ means \"those who falsify\" or \"those who engage in falsehood.\" The root conveys themes of falsehood, invalidation, and deception, highlighting efforts to render things void or undermine truth. مُبْطِلُونَ describes deliberate attempts to mislead, discredit, or promote baseless ideas, reflecting actions that distort reality by presenting the false as valid.",
  "3558": "مُبْعَدُونَ and related words stem from the root ب-ع-د, with the root verb بَعُدَ meaning \"he became distant, remote, or aloof,\" signifying physical, temporal, or spiritual distance. مُبْعَدُونَ means \"ones who are made distant\" or \"those kept away,\" referring to people or things intentionally removed from a specific place, condition, or state. The term carries the sense of deliberate separation, whether for protection, exclusion, or consequence, and can imply both physical distance and a state of being set apart from a particular sphere or influence.",
  "3559": "مُبْلِسُونَ and related words stem from the root ب-ل-س, with the root verb بَلَسَ meaning \"he was confused, and silenced by grief or misfortune,\" and أَبْلَسَ meaning \"he despaired.\" The root conveys themes of being overwhelmed by silent anguish, as if cut off from hope or reprieve. مُبْلِسُونَ refers to those crushed in spirit, so consumed by despair that they are rendered mute, unable to express their anguish or find solace. This silence reflects a profound emptiness and spiritual paralysis, emphasizing a state of isolation and loss. The term highlights the ultimate consequence of despair, where hope and comfort feel entirely out of reach, leaving one disconnected and alone.",
  "3560": "مُتَبَرِّجَاتٍ and related words stem from the root ب-ر-ج, with the root verb بَرَجَ meaning \"he became prominent\" or \"he became visible.\" مُتَبَرِّجَاتٍ refers to women who openly display their beauty or adornment, making themselves visible in a way that draws attention. The root conveys ideas of prominence and visibility, often linked to structures that stand out, like towers. In this context, it implies an immodest or unrestrained display, emphasizing a choice to reveal what is typically private.",
  "3561": "مُتَبَّرٌ and related words stem from the root ت-ب-ر, with the root verb تَبَرَ meaning \"he or it perished.\" مُتَبَّرٌ refers to a thing or people \"destroyed,\" capturing the aftermath of total annihilation. This form suggests a state of having been utterly dismantled or broken down, devoid of life or purpose. The passive quality of مُتَبَّرٌ reflects the completeness of destruction, highlighting a condition in which everything is lost or laid waste, aligning with the root’s sense of perishing.",
  "3562": "مُتَتَابِعَيْنِ and related words stem from the root ت-ب-ع, with the root verb تَبِعَ meaning \"he followed.\" مُتَتَابِعَيْنِ means \"following one another,\" or \"consecutive,\" conveying a sense of continuity and unbroken sequence, often implying regularity or sustained effort. This term suggests not only two things that follow one after the other without interruption but also the idea of consistency and continuity in an ongoing series. This adds depth to its use, especially when expressing persistence or a steady, disciplined following of actions or duties.",
  "3563": "مُتَجَانِفٌ and related words stem from the root ج-ن-ف, with the root verb جَنَفَ meaning \"he deviated from the right course,\" or \"he acted unjustly.\" مُتَجَانِفٌ means \"inclining\" or \"deviating,\" specifically referring to someone or something leaning away from a straight or just course. The root conveys the idea of leaning, turning aside, or moving away from balance or fairness, often with a moral or ethical implication. The connection lies in the active nature of the inclination, where deviation from the correct or just path reflects themes of misalignment, partiality, or error.",
  "3564": "مُتَجَاوِرَاتٌ and related words stem from the root ج-و-ر, with the root verb جاوَرَ meaning \"he became a neighbor.\" The root broadly conveys meanings of proximity, adjacency, and association. مُتَجَاوِرَاتٌ means \"adjacent\" or \"neighboring,\" emphasizing the state of being side by side or in close proximity. This term highlights the inherent connection between things placed near one another, reflecting relationships defined by closeness, interaction, and mutual influence.",
  "3565": "مُتَحَرِّفٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ر-ف, with the root verb حَرَفَ meaning \"he altered\" or \"he distorted.\" مُتَحَرِّفٌ means \"one who maneuvers\" or \"strategically withdraws.\" The connection lies in intentionally changing direction or strategy, reflecting the root's sense of turning aside. It emphasizes adaptability and tactical movement, often in challenging situations.",
  "3566": "مُتَرَاكِبٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ك-ب, with the root verb رَكِبَ meaning \"he rode\" or \"he mounted.\" مُتَرَاكِبٌ means \"layered,\" \"stacked,\" or \"one upon another.\" The connection lies in elements being mounted or placed atop each other, directly relating to the root's concept of joining or assembling. This term can describe things like layers of clouds or foliage, evoking the image of intricate, interconnected structures.",
  "3567": "مُتَرَبِّصٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ب-ص, with the root verb رَبَصَ meaning \"to lie in wait\" or \"to watch.\" مُتَرَبِّصٌ means \"one who waits,\" \"watcher,\" or \"lurker.\" The term refers to someone who is waiting or anticipating, reflecting the root's emphasis on watchfulness. Depending on context, it can describe someone who is patiently awaiting an outcome or someone who harbors ill intent, highlighting the dual nature of anticipation.",
  "3568": "مُتَرَدِّيَةٌ and related words stem from the root ر-د-ي, with the root verb رَدِيَ meaning \"he perished\" or \"he fell into ruin.\" مُتَرَدِّيَةٌ means \"that which has fallen\" or \"fallen animal.\" The connection reflects an animal that has perished by falling, embodying the root's essence of perishing. In Islamic law, such an animal is considered carrion and is not permissible for consumption, highlighting the importance of lawful sustenance.",
  "3569": "مُتَشَابِهَاتٌ and related words stem from the root ش-ب-ه, with the root verb شَبَهَ meaning \"he resembled\" or \"he was similar to.\" مُتَشَابِهَاتٌ means \"similar\" or \"resembling,\" describing things that are alike or share common features. The connection lies in the root's focus on resemblance, emphasizing the state of being similar, which can lead to confusion if not properly distinguished.",
  "3570": "مُتَشَاكِسٌ and related words stem from the root ش-ك-س, with the root verb شَكِسَ meaning \"he was ill-tempered\" or \"he was quarrelsome.\" مُتَشَاكِسٌ means \"one who is contentious\" or \"one who disputes with others.\" The connection lies in the root's concept of contrariness. مُتَشَاكِسٌ embodies the characteristic of being argumentative or difficult to get along with, reflecting a tendency toward discord and opposition in interactions.",
  "3571": "مُتَصَدِّعٌ and related words stem from the root ص-د-ع, with the root verb تَصَدَّعَ meaning \"it split apart\" or \"it cracked.\" مُتَصَدِّعٌ means \"cracked,\" \"splitting,\" or \"fragmented.\" The connection lies in the root's concept of something breaking down or disintegrating. مُتَصَدِّعٌ describes an object or structure that is undergoing division or fragmentation. In the Qur'an, it depicts a mountain splitting due to the impact of divine revelation, emphasizing the profound effect of spiritual truths on the physical world.",
  "3572": "مُتَصَدِّقَاتٍ and related words stem from the root ص-د-ق, with the root verb صَدَّقَ meaning \"he confirmed\" or \"he believed.\" تَصَدَّقَ means \"he gave charity\" or \"he voluntarily supported others through giving.\" مُتَصَدِّقَاتٍ means \"women who give charity,\" focusing on the voluntary and self-motivated aspect of their giving. The root emphasizes truthfulness and sincerity, highlighting the genuine intention behind acts of charity. مُتَصَدِّقَاتٍ represents women who actively and willingly perform charitable deeds, emphasizing their role in fostering generosity and compassion within society.",
  "3573": "مُتَطَهِّرِينَ and related words stem from the root ط-ه-ر, with the root verb طَهَرَ meaning \"he was or became clean or pure.\" مُتَطَهِّرِينَ means \"ones who purify themselves.\" It denotes a person actively engaged in self-purification. This connects to the root by embodying the individual commitment to attain purity, emphasizing personal responsibility in cleansing oneself from impurities to grow spiritually.",
  "3574": "مُتَعَالٍ and related words stem from the root ع-ل-و, with the root verb عَلا meaning \"he rose\" or \"he ascended.\" مُتَعَالٍ means \"Exalted\" or \"Most High,\" emphasizing Allah’s (ﷻ) supreme elevation and transcendence above all creation. ٱلْمُتَعَالِي, one of Allah's (ﷻ) perfect names, signifies \"The Most Exalted\" or \"The Transcendent,\" highlighting His unmatched greatness, free from imperfection or limitation. This reflects the root’s dimensions of rising and elevation, symbolizing Allah’s (ﷻ) supreme and unparalleled nature, inspiring reverence and humility in acknowledging His transcendence beyond human comprehension.",
  "3575": "مُتَعَمِّدٌ and related words stem from the root ع-م-د, with the root verb عَمَدَ meaning \"he intended\" or \"he aimed.\" تَعَمَّدَ means \"he did intentionally.\" مُتَعَمِّدٌ means \"intentional\" or \"one who acts deliberately.\" The connection lies in embodying deliberate intent, reflecting the root's emphasis on purposeful action and conscious decision-making.",
  "3576": "مُتَفَرِّقٌ and related words stem from the root ف-ر-ق, with the root verb فَرَقَ meaning \"he separated\" or \"he divided.\" تَفَرَّقَ means \"he dispersed\" or \"he became divided.\" مُتَفَرِّقٌ means \"dispersed,\" \"divided,\" or \"separate.\" The connection lies in the state of being scattered, directly relating to the root's concept of separation. This term emphasizes the condition of being apart, highlighting the effects of disunity.",
  "3577": "مُتَفَرِّقَةٌ and related words stem from the root ف-ر-ق, with the root verb فَرَقَ meaning \"he separated,\" \"he divided,\" or \"he distinguished.\" مُتَفَرِّقَةٌ means \"dispersed,\" \"divided,\" or \"separate,\" describing a state of being scattered or fragmented. The root conveys themes of division, differentiation, and separation, emphasizing the act or result of breaking into parts. مُتَفَرِّقَةٌ reflects the consequences of disunity or dispersion, whether physical or metaphorical, highlighting the root’s focus on the absence of cohesion or the deliberate act of setting things apart.",
  "3578": "مُتَقَابِلِينَ and related words stem from the root ق-ب-ل, with the root verb قَبِلَ meaning \"he took, received, or admitted willingly,\" or \"he accepted.\" تَقَابَلَ means \"they met each other,\" and مُتَقَابِلِينَ means \"facing each other\" or \"opposite.\" The connection lies in the reciprocal action of meeting or aligning, reflecting the root's essence of willingly engaging or coming together. This emphasizes symmetry, balance, and mutual interaction, symbolizing harmonious relationships and mutual recognition. The word embodies a sense of intentional connection or alignment, illustrating the root’s themes of reception and engagement in a relational or social context.",
  "3579": "مُتَقَلَّبٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ل-ب, with the root verb قَلَبَ meaning \"he turned over,\" \"he inverted,\" or \"he changed.\" مُتَقَلَّبٌ means \"place of turning,\" \"abode,\" or \"state of change.\" The connection lies in the place or condition where changes occur. The root emphasizes the dynamics of movement and transformation. In the Qur'an, it may refer to one's movements and rest, encompassing all states of being, reminding that Allah (ﷻ) is aware of all conditions.",
  "3580": "مُتَكَبِّرٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ب-ر, with the root verb كَبُرَ meaning \"he became great\" or \"he was exalted.\" مُتَكَبِّرٌ means \"one who exalts himself\" or \"one who is arrogant,\" reflecting the misuse of the root's themes of greatness and magnitude. When applied negatively, it represents a distorted perception of superiority, leading to arrogance and misguidance. In contrast, ٱلْمُتَكَبِّرُ, one of Allah’s (ﷻ) perfect names, means \"The Supreme,\" signifying His absolute superiority, perfection, and freedom from all imperfection. This highlights the distinction between Allah’s (ﷻ) rightful greatness and the flawed self-exaltation of creation.",
  "3581": "مُتَكَلِّفِينَ and related words stem from the root ك-ل-ف, with the root verb كَـلَّفَ meaning \"he imposed a burden\" or \"he tasked,\" and كَـلِفَ meaning \"he was burdened\" or \"he was fond of.\" مُتَكَلِّفِينَ refers to \"those who overburden themselves unnecessarily,\" emphasizing self-imposed hardship or affectation. The term reflects actions or behaviors taken beyond what is natural or required, often involving artificiality or excessive effort. The root highlights the distinction between genuine effort and unnecessary burdens, capturing the idea of creating undue difficulty for oneself. In context, it highlights authenticity and sincerity, rejecting pretentiousness and excessive strain in actions or speech.",
  "3582": "الْمُتَلَقِّيَانُ and related words stem from the root ل-ق-ي, with the root verb لَقِيَ meaning \"he met,\" \"he encountered,\" or \"he found.\" الْمُتَلَقِّيَانُ translates to \"the two receivers\" or \"the two who receive,\" emphasizing the act of encountering or receiving something. In the Qur'an, it refers to the two angels assigned to every individual, tasked with recording their deeds. The connection to the root lies in the concept of meeting, where the angels \"meet\" a person's actions through their act of receiving and recording. This highlights themes of accountability and the ever-present observation of our deeds, reflecting the profound responsibility and awareness inherent in human actions.",
  "3583": "مُتَنَافِسُونَ and related words stem from the root ن-ف-س, with the root verb نَفِسَ meaning \"it was precious\" or \"valuable,\" and the derived verb تَنَافَسَ meaning \"they competed\" or \"vied with one another.\" مُتَنَافِسُونَ means \"ones who compete\" or \"aspirers.\" The connection lies in the pursuit of something precious, driving individuals to compete eagerly, directly relating to the root's emphasis on value and desirability. It reflects the human inclination to strive for valuable goals, much like seeking rare treasures.",
  "3584": "مُتَوَسِّمِينَ and related words stem from the root و-س-م, with the root verb وَسَمَ meaning \"he marked,\" \"he branded,\" or \"he distinguished.\" تَوَسَّمَ means \"he perceived,\" \"he discerned,\" or \"he observed attentively.\" مُتَوَسِّمِينَ means \"those who discern\" or \"those who perceive.\" The connection to the root involves recognizing marks or signs that distinguish something. It reflects deep insight and the ability to read subtle indications.",
  "3585": "مُتَوَفٍّ and related words stem from the root و-ف-ى, with the root verb وَفَىٰ meaning \"he fulfilled.\" مُتَوَفٍّ means \"one who takes fully.\" The connection lies in the act of bringing something to completion, reflecting the root's emphasis on fulfillment. In a divine context, it refers to Allah (ﷻ) as the one who takes souls at death, highlighting His sovereignty over life and death and the completion of each soul's earthly journey.",
  "3586": "مُتَوَكِّلِينَ and related words stem from the root و-كـ-ل, with the root verb وَكَـلَ meaning \"he entrusted\" or \"he relied upon.\" مُتَوَكِّلِينَ means \"ones who put trust.\" The connection highlights the state of entrusting oneself to another, reflecting the root's emphasis on dependence and confidence in someone else's support. It denotes a person who places their trust beyond themselves, embodying humility and faith.",
  "3587": "مُتِمٌّ and related words stem from the root ت-م-م, with the root verb تَمَّ meaning \"it became complete, entire, or full.\" مُتِمٌّ means \"one who completes\" or \"perfecter,\" referring to someone who brings something to completion. The root here emphasizes the role of an agent who fulfills or completes something to its ideal form, highlighting both the responsibility and skill of perfecting what was begun.",
  "3588": "مُتَّبَعُونَ and related words stem from the root ت-ب-ع, with the root verb تَبِعَ meaning \"he followed,\" and اتَّبَعَ meaning \"he followed closely.\" مُتَّبَعُونَ means \"those who are followed\" or \"the pursued.\" It captures the notion of a group being closely pursued by others, highlighting a dual sense of following: the followers themselves are being pursued by another group, creating a layered dynamic of leadership and pursuit. This context underlines the cyclical relationship where both followers and pursuers are aligned in motion, each following a determined course, emphasizing continuity and purpose.",
  "3589": "مُتَّخِذٌ and related words stem from the root أ-خ-ذ, with the root verb أَخَذَ meaning \"he took,\" and اتَّخَذَ meaning \"he adopted,\" or \"he took as.\" مُتَّخِذٌ means \"one who adopts,\" \"adopter,\" or \"one who takes for oneself.\" The connection lies in the individual's role in choosing to adopt or embrace something, embodying the root's concept of taking. مُتَّخِذٌ highlights personal responsibility in the decisions one makes, particularly in matters of faith, alliances, or lifestyle. It highlights the active participation in shaping one's path and the importance of conscious choices.",
  "3590": "مُتَّقِينَ and related words stem from the root و-ق-ي, with the root verb وَقَىٰ meaning \"he guarded\" or \"he preserved.\" اتَّقَوْا means \"they guarded themselves\" or \"they were God-conscious,\" and مُتَّقِينَ means \"ones who guard themselves.\" The root conveys themes of shielding, safeguarding, and maintaining a protective barrier, emphasizing proactive measures to prevent harm. The term مُتَّقِينَ describes individuals who actively engage in self-protection through consciousness and mindfulness of Allah (ﷻ). It reflects the root's emphasis on guarding oneself from sin by adhering to Allah's (ﷻ) guidance, striving to embody righteousness, maintain moral integrity, and secure spiritual well-being.",
  "3591": "مُتَّكَأً and related words stem from the root و-ك-أ, with the root verb وَكَأَ meaning \"he leaned.\" مُتَّكَأً means \"a place to recline\" or \"a sitting room or a chamber.\" The broader root concepts include leaning for physical support, finding stability, and creating a space of ease or relaxation. The connection lies in providing a means of rest or comfort, reflecting the root's emphasis on reliance, physical support, and the act of resting upon something dependable.",
  "3592": "مُتَّكِئُونَ and related words stem from the root و-ك-أ, with the root verb وَكَأَ meaning \"he leaned.\" مُتَّكِئُونَ means \"ones who recline\" or \"reclining.\" The broader root meanings encompass the act of leaning for support, seeking stability, and resting on something dependable. This directly connects to the root, emphasizing a state of ease, comfort, and reliance, often associated with relaxed or reflective postures that signify both physical rest and symbolic dependence.",
  "3593": "مُتْرَفِينَ and related words stem from the root ت-ر-ف, with the root verb تَرِفَ meaning \"he lived in luxury\" or \"he enjoyed a life of ease and plenty\" or \"he indulged in pleasures and desires.\" مُتْرَفِينَ refers to \"ones who live a life of ease and plenty\" or \"ones who are not prevented from enjoying themselves,\" describing privileged individuals who live in abundance. The root also carries the idea of this privilege leading to ingratitude and arrogance.",
  "3594": "مُثْقَلُونَ and related words stem from the root ث-ق-ل, with the root verb ثَقُلَ meaning \"it was heavy, weighty, or burdensome.\" مُثْقَلٌ is a passive form meaning 'burdened' or 'weighed down,' describing someone carrying a heavy load, whether physical, emotional, or moral. Directly tied to the root's sense of heaviness, it emphasizes the strain, pressure, or fatigue that comes with significant obligations or overwhelming circumstances, reflecting the weight of responsibility or hardship.",
  "3595": "مُثْقَلَةٌ and related words stem from the root ث-ق-ل, with the root verb ثَقُلَ meaning \"it was heavy, weighty, or burdensome.\" مُثْقَلَةٌ means \"that which is burdened,\" or \"a burdened one.\" Rooted in the concept of heaviness, it often refers to a pregnant woman carrying the weight of life or an entity laden with significant burdens. This term embodies both physical weight and metaphorical responsibilities, reflecting the strain of obligations or hardships, directly tied to the root's emphasis on weight and gravity.",
  "3596": "مُثْلَىٰ and related words stem from the root م-ث-ل, with the root verb مَثَلَ meaning \"he resembled,\" \"he was like,\" or \"he set forth an example.\" مُثْلَىٰ means \"most excellent,\" \"ideal,\" or \"perfect.\" The connection lies in representing the highest standard or epitome of excellence, relating to the root's concept of exemplification and likeness. It embodies the notion of the ultimate model that others aspire to emulate.",
  "3597": "مُجَاهِدُونَ and related words stem from the root ج-ه-د, with the root verb جَهَدَ meaning \"he exerted effort.\" مُجَاهِدُونَ means \"those who strive\" or \"strugglers,\" referring to individuals who actively engage in جِهَاد. The connection lies in their dedication and perseverance in striving for righteousness, self-improvement, and the betterment of society. This term also emphasizes their commitment to exerting effort in the path of Allah (ﷻ), whether through personal struggles, resisting temptations, or working for justice and the welfare of the community.",
  "3598": "مُجِيبٌ and related words stem from the root ج-و-ب, with the root verb جَابَ meaning \"he cut through\" or \"he pierced.\" The root conveys meanings of cutting, piercing, and addressing directly, symbolizing clarity and resolution. أَجَابَ means \"he answered,\" and مُجِيبٌ means \"one who answers\" or \"responder,\" referring to someone who responds to calls or provides answers. This reflects the idea of directly resolving a matter, akin to cutting through uncertainty. ٱلْمُجِيبُ, one of Allah's (ﷻ) perfect names, means \"The Responsive\" or \"The Answerer of Prayers,\" emphasizing His attentiveness and wisdom in responding to the supplications and needs of His servants.",
  "3599": "مُجْتَمِعُونَ and related words stem from the root ج-م-ع, with the root verb جَمَعَ meaning \"he gathered\" or \"he collected.\" مُجْتَمِعُونَ means \"those who gather\" or \"those who assemble,\" referring to individuals brought together with a shared purpose or intent. The root conveys the act of bringing separate elements into a unified whole, emphasizing organization, intentionality, and collaboration. The connection lies in collective action and the cooperation required to achieve unity and shared goals.",
  "3600": "مُجْرِمٌ and related words stem from the root ج-ر-م, with the root verb جَرَمَ meaning \"he cut off,\" \"he severed,\" or \"he committed a crime.\" مُجْرِمٌ means \"criminal\" or \"sinner,\" describing one who persistently engages in acts of wrongdoing. The root reflects themes of severance and transgression, with مُجْرِمٌ emphasizing the habitual violation of moral or legal boundaries. This term embodies the root’s essence of deliberate harm or sin, symbolizing the severance of the wrongdoer from righteousness or guidance.",
  "3601": "مُحَرَّرٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ر-ر, with the root verb حَرَّ meaning \"he was free.\" مُحَرَّرٌ is a passive form meaning \"dedicated\" or \"set free.\" The connection lies in the idea of release from restrictions and devotion to a higher purpose. Just as freedom removes external constraints, مُحَرَّرٌ conveys the idea of being liberated from worldly obligations and assigned to a specific, noble role. This is often associated with spiritual dedication, purity, and refinement, where one is freed from distractions to focus entirely on service or worship.",
  "3602": "مُحَرَّمٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ر-م, with the root verb حَرُمَ meaning \"it was forbidden or prohibited,\" and حَرَّمَ meaning \"he forbade, prohibited, or made unlawful.\" مُحَرَّمٌ means \"forbidden,\" \"prohibited,\" or \"sacred,\" referring to something declared unlawful or inviolable. The term can also signify the Sacred House (Kaaba), highlighting its sanctity and inviolable status. The root conveys meanings of prohibition, protection, restriction, and sacredness. The connection lies in the act of setting something apart as inviolable, whether by forbidding it or by elevating it to a state of sanctity, reflecting the root's emphasis on reverence and restraint.",
  "3603": "مُحَرَّمَةٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ر-م, with the root verb حَرُمَ meaning \"it was forbidden or prohibited,\" and حَرَّمَ meaning \"he forbade, prohibited, or made unlawful.\" The root also carries broader meanings of sacredness, protection, and restraint, emphasizing the concept of setting boundaries or safeguarding something from harm. مُحَرَّمَةٌ translates as \"forbidden\" or \"prohibited,\" referring to something declared unlawful or sacred. The connection lies in the root's focus on restriction, protection, and sanctity, highlighting the state of being safeguarded from violation or harm, whether through prohibition or reverence.",
  "3604": "مُحَصَّنَةٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ص-ن, with the root verb حَصُنَ meaning \"it was fortified,\" and حَصَّنَ meaning \"he fortified,\" \"he protected,\" or \"he made inaccessible.\" مُحَصَّنَةٌ is a passive form meaning \"fortified,\" \"protected,\" or \"chaste woman.\" This reflects a state of being guarded against harm or immorality, directly connecting to the root's emphasis on protection and fortification. The term often refers to women who are married or who maintain their chastity, highlighting the virtues of purity and honor safeguarded by social or moral boundaries.",
  "3605": "مُحَلِّقِينَ and related words stem from the root ح-ل-ق, with the root verb حَلَقَ meaning \"he shaved.\" مُحَلِّقِينَ means \"those who shave.\" The connection lies in removal and purification, as shaving symbolizes renewal and completion, particularly in pilgrimage. The root also conveys circularity and enclosure, reflecting both shaving motions and the encircling of the Kaaba. Cutting off entirely relates to shaving as an exit from ihram—the sacred state restricting certain actions. This marks the completion of a sacred phase and transition into a new state, reinforcing themes of separation, transformation, and renewal.",
  "3606": "مُحَمَّدٌ and related words stem from the root ح-م-د, with the root verb حَمِدَ meaning \"he praised\" or \"he thanked.\" مُحَمَّدٌ is the name of Prophet Muhammad (ﷺ) and is a passive form meaning \"the oft-praised\" or \"praised repeatedly.\" It reflects his esteemed status and the abundant praise he receives not only from believers and angels but also from Allah (ﷻ) Himself. The connection lies in the intensified form of the root, signifying someone who is praised extensively and continuously. It highlights his exemplary character, his high station, and the profound impact of his prophethood.",
  "3607": "مُحِلِّيُّ and related words stem from the root ح-ل-ل, with the root verb حَلَّ meaning \"he untied\" or \"he loosened.\" From this comes أَحَلَّ, meaning \"he made lawful,\" and تَحَلَّلَ, meaning \"he became free from restriction.\" مُحِلِّيُّ means \"one who makes lawful\" or \"one who permits.\" The connection lies in actively untying or lifting prohibitions, making actions or statuses permissible. This term can refer to those who interpret or apply laws, emphasizing the responsibility of ensuring that permissibility aligns with Allah's (ﷻ) guidance.",
  "3608": "مُحِيطٌ and related words stem from the root ح-و-ط, with the root verb حَاطَ meaning \"he surrounded or encompassed,\" \"he protected,\" or \"he comprehended or had full knowledge.\" مُحِيطٌ means \"encompassing\" or \"surrounding,\" emphasizing complete enclosure. It conveys the idea of something being fully encircled, whether in knowledge, protection, or authority. This term reflects absolute control—whether referring to Allah’s (ﷻ) knowledge that leaves nothing beyond its reach or a punishment that fully surrounds wrongdoers, making escape impossible.",
  "3609": "مُحْتَضَرٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ض-ر, with the verb حَضَرَ meaning \"he was present,\" \"he attended,\" or \"he came,\" referring to general presence or attendance. In contrast, اِحْتَضَرَ means \"he was present\" in a heightened or solemn context, such as being present at the moment of death or at an appointed critical event. مُحْتَضَرٌ can mean \"the dying person,\" \"the place of death,\" or \"something to be attended.\" This reflects the root’s emphasis on presence and attentiveness, whether in everyday situations or significant moments, highlighting themes of accountability and reflection in pivotal transitions.",
  "3610": "مُحْتَظِرٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ظ-ر, with حَظَرَ meaning \"he forbade,\" \"he restricted,\" or \"he placed a barrier around something.\" اِحْتَظَرَ means \"he built an enclosure,\" \"he fenced in,\" or \"he enclosed something for protection.\" مُحْتَظِرٌ refers to \"one who builds an enclosure\" or \"one who fences off,\" reflecting the act of establishing physical or symbolic barriers. This aligns with the root’s core theme of prohibition and limitation. In the Qur'an, it describes animal enclosures made from dry branches and thorns to protect livestock, symbolizing both security and fragility.",
  "3611": "مُحْدَثٌ and related words stem from the root ح-د-ث, with the root verb حَدَثَ meaning \"it was new or recent,\" or \"it came into existence,\" or \"it happened.\" مُحْدَثٌ is a passive form meaning \"newly created\" or \"innovated.\" The connection lies in something that has come into existence, reflecting the root's concept of occurrence. It denotes an event or object that has been recently brought about, emphasizing novelty and the introduction of new elements.",
  "3612": "مُحْسِنٌ and related words stem from the root ح-س-ن, with the root verb حَسُنَ meaning \"he was good\" or \"he became beautiful,\" and أَحْسَنَ meaning \"he did excellently\" or \"he did good.\" مُحْسِنٌ translates as \"doer of good\" or \"benefactor,\" referring to someone who consistently performs acts of kindness, excellence, and generosity. The root reflects themes of beauty, virtue, and refinement, emphasizing the pursuit of goodness in both actions and character. The connection lies in striving for excellence and embodying selflessness, aligning with the root’s focus on enhancing and perfecting what one does, while fostering harmony and virtue.",
  "3613": "مُحْسِنَاتٌ and related words stem from the root ح-س-ن, with the root verb حَسُنَ meaning \"he was good\" or \"he became beautiful,\" and أَحْسَنَ meaning \"he did excellently\" or \"he did good.\" مُحْسِنَاتٌ translates as \"doers of good,\" referring to a woman who exemplifies kindness, generosity, and excellence. The root encompasses themes of beauty, virtue, and moral uprightness, emphasizing the pursuit of goodness in both character and deeds. This term highlights the value of fostering harmony and refinement through benevolent intentions and exemplary actions.",
  "3614": "مُحْصَنَاتٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ص-ن, with the root verb حَصُنَ meaning \"it was fortified,\" حَصَّنَ meaning \"he fortified, protected, or made inaccessible,\" and أَحْصَنَ meaning \"he safeguarded\" or \"he ensured chastity.\" مُحْصَنَاتٌ is a passive form meaning \"protected,\" \"chaste women,\" or \"married women.\" The connection lies in a state of being safeguarded, whether through moral integrity, marriage, or legal status, directly relating to the root's emphasis on protection and fortification. This term often refers to women who are chaste or in wedlock, highlighting the sanctity and security provided by marriage, personal virtue, or social protection.",
  "3615": "مُحْصِنِينَ and related words stem from the root ح-ص-ن, with the root verb حَصُنَ meaning \"it was fortified,\" حَصَّنَ meaning \"he fortified, protected, or made inaccessible,\" and أَحْصَنَ meaning \"he safeguarded\" or \"he ensured chastity.\" مُحْصِنِينَ means \"those who seek chastity\" or \"those who seek to protect themselves.\" The connection lies in the active effort to safeguard oneself from harm or immorality, directly aligning with the root’s emphasis on fortification and security. This term embodies qualities of integrity and self-discipline, emphasizing the importance of maintaining moral and legal safeguards in one’s life.",
  "3616": "مُحْضَرٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ض-ر, with the root verb حَضَرَ meaning \"he was present,\" \"he attended,\" or \"he came,\" and أَحْضَرَ meaning \"he brought,\" \"he presented,\" or \"he made present.\" مُحْضَرٌ is a passive form meaning \"one who is brought,\" \"one who is presented,\" or \"the one made present.\" This reflects the state of being brought before someone or something, directly connecting to the root's emphasis on presence and presentation. The term can refer to individuals brought forth for judgment, testimony, or other significant encounters, highlighting themes of accountability and revelation.",
  "3617": "مُحْكَمَةٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ك-م, with the root verb حَكَمَ meaning \"he judged\" or \"he governed.\"  مُحْكَمَةٌ means \"firmly constructed,\" \"decisive,\" or \"clear.\" The root also conveys meanings of restraining, making firm, and ensuring precision. The connection lies in the quality of being well-established and precise, reflecting the root's focus on sound judgment and wisdom. In the Qur'an, it describes verses that are clear, conclusive, authoritative, and unambiguous, emphasizing the necessity of clarity and firmness in conveying guidance and truth.",
  "3618": "مُحْيِي and related words stem from the root ح-ي-ي, with the root verb حَيَّ meaning \"he lived\" or \"he became fresh or lively.\" أَحْيَا means \"He gave life,\" \"He revived or restored to life,\" or \"He caused to be lively or active.\" مُحْيِي translates as \"one who gives life,\" referring to Allah’s (ﷻ) attribute as the originator and restorer. ٱلْمُحْيِي, one of His perfect names, means \"The Giver of Life\" or \"The Reviver,\" emphasizing His power to bring forth existence, revive what has perished, and restore vitality. The connection lies in how مُحْيِي extends the meaning of حَيَّ from simply existing to the act of bringing into existence, reinforcing that life and renewal are solely by His will.",
  "3619": "مُخَلَّدُونَ and related words stem from the root خ-ل-د, with the root verb خَلَدَ meaning \"he remained\" or \"he lasted long.\" مُخَلَّدُونَ is a passive form meaning \"made eternal\" or \"immortalized.\" The root conveys permanence, timelessness, and enduring existence. The connection lies in being granted perpetual existence, free from change or decay. In the Qur'an, it describes youths of everlasting freshness in Paradise, symbolizing the unchanging perfection and permanence of the Hereafter.",
  "3620": "مُخَلَّفُونَ and related words stem from the root خ-ل-ف, with the root verb خَلَفَ meaning \"he came after\" or \"he succeeded.\" The root conveys succession, substitution, and contrast, where one follows another or is left in place of something else. مُخَلَّفُونَ is a passive form meaning \"left behind\" or \"abandoned,\" indicating those who were deliberately or forcibly excluded, set aside, or delayed. This reflects a state of being withheld from participation or progression, whether due to external circumstances or personal shortcomings, highlighting the implications of being left behind in responsibility or action.",
  "3621": "مُخَلَّقَةٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ل-ق, with the root verb خَلَقَ meaning \"he created,\" \"he shaped,\" or \"he formed.\" The root conveys precise measurement, formation, and the process of bringing something into existence. مُخَلَّقَةٌ is a passive form meaning \"formed\" or \"shaped,\" emphasizing something carefully fashioned with intention and precision. In the Qur'an, it refers to both fully formed and unformed embryos, highlighting Allah’s (ﷻ) perfect creation and control over every stage of development. This emphasiezes the meticulous design and wisdom behind all creation, reflecting both purpose and divine decree.",
  "3622": "مُخْبِتِينَ and related words stem from the root خ-ب-ت, with the root verb خَبَتَ meaning \"it (a fire) became extinguished,\" \"it subsided or became still,\" \"he became quiet or calm,\" or \"he was or became humble.\" مُخْبِتِينَ means \"humble ones,\" referring to those who lower themselves in humility and submission. The connection lies in the idea of stillness and surrender—just as a fire that dies down becomes subdued, true humility requires quieting one's ego and submitting with sincerity, embodying a state of calm, devotion, and reverence.",
  "3623": "مُخْتَالٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ي-ل, with the root verb خَالَ meaning \"he imagined (something to be in a certain way)\" or \"he perceived (something) in his mind.\" The root revolves around imagination, perception, illusion, and grandeur, conveying both mental perception and physical presence. مُخْتَالٌ means \"arrogant\" or \"conceited,\" referring to someone who perceives themselves as grand or superior, often in an exaggerated or deceptive manner. The connection to the root highlights how arrogance stems from an inflated self-image, where one imagines their own greatness, reinforcing the link between perception, illusion, and a false sense of superiority.",
  "3624": "مُخْتَلِفٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ل-ف, with the root verb خَلَفَ meaning \"he came after\" or \"he succeeded.\" The root conveys succession, substitution, and contrast, where one thing follows another or differs from what came before. مُخْتَلِفٌ means \"differing\" or \"various,\" emphasizing diversity, variation, and opposition. This reflects the natural distinctions that arise in thoughts, appearances, and conditions, highlighting how contrast and difference are fundamental aspects of existence, shaping perspectives, interactions, and change.",
  "3625": "مُخْرَجٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ر-ج, with the root verb خَرَجَ meaning \"he went out\" or \"he exited.\" مُخْرَجٌ is a passive form meaning \"brought out\" or \"produced.\" The root conveys themes of emergence, extraction, and making something known. This word emphasizes the result of an action where something hidden, contained, or undeveloped is drawn out or made apparent, highlighting the process of bringing something into visibility or existence.",
  "3626": "مُخْرِجٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ر-ج, with the root verb خَرَجَ meaning \"he went out\" or \"he exited.\" مُخْرِجٌ means \"one who brings out\" or \"producer.\" The root conveys themes of emergence, extraction, and bringing something into existence. This word highlights the role of an agent who causes something to come forth, whether by creating, revealing, or producing. It emphasizes facilitation and initiation, reflecting the process of making something visible, known, or realized.",
  "3627": "مُخْزِيٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ز-ي, with the root verb خَزِيَ meaning \"he was ashamed\" or \"he was disgraced.\" مُخْزِيٌ translates as \"one who disgraces\" or \"disgracing,\" referring to the active role of causing shame or dishonor to others. The root emphasizes the act of bringing humiliation or shame as a response to wrongdoing or defiance. The connection lies in the deliberate act of degrading another, reflecting the root’s focus on the imposition of shame and dishonor.",
  "3628": "مُخْسِرِينَ and related words stem from the root خ-س-ر, with the root verb خَسِرَ meaning \"he lost.\" مُخْسِرِينَ means \"those who cause loss\" or \"defrauders.\" The root conveys themes of deprivation, failure, and ruin. This word emphasizes the act of making others incur loss, whether through deception, fraud, or unfair dealings. It highlights unethical behavior that leads to harm, reinforcing the consequences of causing deprivation and injustice to others.",
  "3629": "مُخْضَرَّةٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ض-ر, with the root verb اِخْضَرَّ meaning \"it became green\" or \"it was fresh or flourishing.\" مُخْضَرَّةٌ means \"with what is green\" or \"lush,\" emphasizing an advanced state of greenness and luxuriant growth. The connection reflects flourishing vitality and abundance in nature, symbolizing the richness of creation and the boundless generosity of Allah’s (ﷻ) provision.",
  "3630": "مُخْلَصِينَ and related words stem from the root خ-ل-ص, with the root verb خَلَصَ meaning \"he was pure\" or \"he became sincere.\" مُخْلَصِينَ is a passive form meaning \"purified\" or \"chosen ones,\" referring to those purified by an external force or set apart due to their sincerity. The root conveys separation, exclusivity, and refinement, whether physically or spiritually. The connection lies in being distinguished through purity, where one is selected for a noble purpose. This reflects being chosen by Allah (ﷻ) for a higher state of devotion, emphasizing divine favor and grace.",
  "3631": "مُخْلِصِينَ and related words stem from the root خ-ل-ص, with the root verb خَلَصَ meaning \"he was pure\" or \"he became sincere.\" مُخْلِصِينَ means \"ones who are sincere,\" referring to individuals who actively strive to achieve sincerity in their intentions and actions. The root encompasses themes of purity, refinement, and dedication, focusing on the human effort to align oneself fully with a singular purpose. This term emphasizes individual effort and determination in dedicating oneself entirely to Allah (ﷻ), free from distractions or ulterior motives, highlighting the importance of personal responsibility in achieving purity and sincerity.",
  "3632": "مُخْلِفٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ل-ف, with the root verb خَلَفَ meaning \"he came after\" or \"he succeeded.\" The root conveys succession, substitution, and contrast, where one follows another or deviates from what preceded. مُخْلِفٌ means \"one who leaves behind,\" emphasizing the act of abandoning, failing to fulfill, or breaking a commitment.",
  "3633": "الْمُدَبِّرَاتُ and related words stem from the root د-ب-ر, with the root verb دَبَرَ meaning \"it came after or followed\" or \"he turned his back or went away.\" دَبَّرَ means \"he planned\" or \"he managed,\" highlighting the act of arranging matters with foresight. الْمُدَبِّرَاتُ means \"those who manage\" or \"organizers,\" referring to those who oversee and direct affairs. The root revolves around sequential occurrence, management, and decline, conveying planning, order, and administration. The connection lies in structuring and executing tasks with precision. In the Qur'an, الْمُدَبِّرَات refers to angels who, under Allah’s (ﷻ) command, regulate the universe’s affairs with perfect order.",
  "3634": "مُدَّةٌ and related words stem from the root م-د-د, with the root verb مَدَّ meaning \"he extended,\" \"he stretched,\" or \"he prolonged.\" مُدَّةٌ means \"term,\" \"duration,\" or \"period.\" The connection lies in the extension of time, where a specific span is stretched or defined as a measurable duration. It reflects the root’s focus on elongation by emphasizing time as something that can be extended, bounded, or allocated, highlighting the concept of temporal progression or continuity.",
  "3635": "مُدَّثِّرٌ and related words stem from the root د-ث-ر, with the root verb دَثَرَ meaning \"it became covered with sand and dust blown over it by the wind,\" signifying disappearance or being overtaken. دَثَّرَ means \"he covered with a garment\" or \"he wrapped or enshrouded,\" emphasizing concealment or protection. مُدَّثِّرٌ means \"one who is wrapped up,\" reflecting the act of being enveloped. The root conveys both the fading of something over time and the intentional act of covering for warmth, security, or withdrawal. The connection highlights how wrapping can symbolize both being overtaken—like something buried by dust—and a conscious act of shielding oneself for comfort, rest, or preparation.",
  "3636": "مُدَّخَلٌ and related words stem from the root د-خ-ل, with the root verb دَخَلَ meaning \"he entered.\" مُدَّخَلٌ means \"an entrance\" or \"a place of entry,\" emphasizing the point of access or passage. The root revolves around entry, penetration, mixture, and involvement, conveying both physical and metaphorical entry. Just as an entrance grants access to a space, this word reflects being admitted into a secure or favorable state, highlighting transition into safety, ease, or blessing, whether in a physical or abstract sense.",
  "3637": "مُدَّكِرٌ and related words stem from the root ذ-ك-ر, with the root verb ذَكَرَ meaning \"he remembered\" or \"he mentioned\" and the verb اِدَّكَرَ meaning \"he vividly remembered\" or \"he took heed.\" مُدَّكِرٌ means \"one who remembers\" or \"one who takes heed,\" emphasizing active reflection and mindfulness. The connection lies in recalling and internalizing lessons, reflecting the root's focus on remembrance and awareness. This term highlights the importance of being receptive to reminders, leading to spiritual growth and righteous action.",
  "3638": "مُدْبِرٌ and related words stem from the root د-ب-ر, with the root verb دَبَرَ meaning \"it came after or followed\" or \"he turned his back or went away.\" أَدْبَرَ means \"he turned away\" or \"he departed,\" while مُدْبِرٌ means \"one who turns away\" or \"retreater,\" emphasizing the act of withdrawing or stepping back. The root revolves around sequence, positioning, and retreat, conveying the idea of moving away, being positioned at the back, or shifting out of focus. The connection highlights turning one's back—whether physically, in avoidance, or in decline—reinforcing themes of separation, retreat, or loss.",
  "3639": "مُدْحَضِينَ and related words stem from the root د-ح-ض, with the root verb دَحَضَ meaning \"it slipped, slided, or became unstable\" or \"it became null, void, or baseless.\" مُدْحَضِينَ is a passive form meaning \"refuted\" or \"overcome,\" describing those whose positions or arguments have been invalidated. The root revolves around slipping, instability, refutation, and invalidation, conveying both physical unsteadiness and the conceptual weakening or disproving of an argument or claim. Just as something that slips loses its footing and collapses, those described by this word are rendered powerless, their stance unable to hold ground against truth, emphasizing its ultimate unsustainability.",
  "3640": "مُدْخَلٌ and related words stem from the root د-خ-ل, with the root verb دَخَلَ meaning \"he entered.\" This root conveys the act of entry, both physically and metaphorically, signifying the transition from one space to another. مُدْخَلٌ refers to \"entrance\" or \"place of entry,\" emphasizing the location or means by which entry occurs. The root revolves around entry, penetration, mixture, and involvement, reflecting both movement into a place and engagement in a situation. Just as an entrance serves as a point of access, this word highlights pathways—whether a literal doorway, a gateway to knowledge, or an opportunity—marking the beginning of inclusion or transition into something new.",
  "3641": "مُدْرَكُونَ and related words stem from the root د-ر-ك, with the root verb دَرَكَ meaning \"it reached or attained\" or \"it overtook or caught up with.\" The root revolves around reaching, comprehension, and consequences, conveying both physical arrival and intellectual realization. مُدْرَكُونَ is a passive form meaning \"ones who are overtaken,\" reflecting the state of being caught or reached by something, often with an undertone of inevitability. Just as what is pursued is eventually reached, this word highlights an unavoidable outcome, emphasizing how one is ultimately overtaken, whether by events, consequences, or fate.",
  "3642": "مُدْهَامَّتَانِ and related words stem from the root د-ه-م, with the root verb دَهِمَ meaning \"it became intensely dark.\" مُدْهَامَّتَانِ means \"two intensely green,\" inclining to blackness due to their lushness. The root conveys suddenness and intensity, darkness and blackness, and extends to ideas of overwhelming presence, covering, or concealing. The connection lies in the depth of color—just as extreme darkness signifies intensity, the richness of these gardens is so deep that their green appears almost black. This term vividly portrays the luxuriant, abundant gardens in Paradise, reflecting both their overwhelming beauty and the depth of their lushness.",
  "3643": "مُدْهِنُونَ and related words stem from the root د-ه-ن, with the root verb دَهَنَ meaning \"he anointed\" or \"he oiled.\" أَدْهَنَ means \"he compromised,\" while مُدْهِنُونَ means \"those who compromise.\" The connection lies in the metaphorical extension of oil’s smoothness—just as oil makes surfaces sleek and pliable, this word reflects speech or actions that soften, flatter, or conceal truth. It conveys the idea of moral compromise, where principles are adjusted or truth is smoothed over to appease others or avoid conflict, often at the expense of sincerity and integrity.",
  "3644": "مُذَبْذَبٌ and related words stem from the quadriliteral root ذ-ب-ذ-ب, which conveys the idea of moving back and forth, shaking, or wavering. مُذَبْذَبٌ means \"wavering,\" \"unstable,\" or \"oscillating,\" describing someone who is indecisive or inconsistent. The connection lies in the repeated motion implied by the root, reflecting a lack of firmness or stability. It serves as a caution against indecision and inconsistency in faith or actions, highlighting the importance of conviction and steadfastness.",
  "3645": "مُذَكِّرٌ and related words stem from the root ذ-ك-ر, with the root verb ذَكَرَ meaning \"he remembered\" or \"he mentioned\" and the verb ذَكَّرَ meaning \"he reminded\" or \"he admonished.\" مُذَكِّرٌ means \"one who reminds\" or \"admonisher,\" referring to someone who actively brings others to remembrance. The connection lies in guiding others to recall and reflect on important truths, aligning with the root's focus on memory and mention. This term highlights the critical role of teachers, prophets, and leaders in encouraging righteousness and mindfulness through consistent reminders.",
  "3646": "مُذْعِنِينَ and related words stem from the root ذ-ع-ن, with the root verb ذَعَنَ meaning \"he obeyed,\" \"he submitted,\" or \"he complied.\" مُذْعِنِينَ means \"promptly obedient\" or \"readily submitting,\" emphasizing a state of swift and willing compliance without resistance. The root conveys themes of surrender and acceptance, highlighting a readiness to align with authority or truth. The connection lies in the immediacy and wholehearted nature of this submission, reflecting the root’s focus on yielding and conforming with sincerity.",
  "3647": "مُرَاغَمٌ and related words stem from the root ر-غ-م, with the root verb رَغِمَ meaning \"he was compelled\" or \"he was humiliated.\" مُرَاغَمٌ means \"place of refuge\" or \"place of exile.\" The connection lies in the act of leaving one's home due to compulsion or seeking refuge, embodying the root's emphasis on necessity and humility. This term reflects the struggle and sacrifice involved in migration for the sake of a higher purpose, highlighting themes of perseverance and reliance on divine assistance.",
  "3648": "مُرِيبٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ي-ب, with the root verb رَابَ meaning \"he doubted\" or \"he suspected.\" مُرِيبٌ means \"causing doubt\" or \"suspicious.\" The connection lies in something that provokes uncertainty or mistrust, directly relating to the root’s concept of inducing doubt. It refers to a person, action, or situation that stirs suspicion, leading others to question what is true. This emphasizes the power of external forces to disrupt certainty, evoking a state of doubt in the hearts of others.",
  "3649": "مُرْتَابٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ي-ب, with the root verb رَابَ meaning \"he doubted\" or \"he suspected.\" مُرْتَابٌ means \"one who doubts\" or \"a skeptic.\" The connection lies in the person who harbors doubt or suspicion, reflecting the root’s emphasis on internal skepticism. This form emphasizes a person who is internally unsettled, constantly questioning and unable to fully trust what is before them. It reflects the mental state of doubt, where uncertainty prevails and clarity is hindered by suspicion.",
  "3650": "مُرْتَفَقٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ف-ق, with the root verb رَفَقَ meaning \"he was kind\" or \"he was gentle.\" مُرْتَفَقٌ means \"resting place\" or \"couch.\" The connection lies in a place of comfort and ease, embodying the root's emphasis on gentleness and relaxation. This term reflects the comfort provided by a resting place, highlighting the theme of tranquility and repose.",
  "3651": "مُرْتَقِبٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ق-ب, with the root verb رَقَبَ meaning \"he watched\" or \"he observed.\" مُرْتَقِبٌ means \"one who waits\" or \"observer.\" The connection lies in the act of waiting attentively, embodying the root's emphasis on observation and anticipation. This term reflects the state of being expectant and vigilant, highlighting themes of patience and foresight.",
  "3652": "مُرْجَوْنَ and related words stem from the root ر-ج-و, with the root verb رَجَا meaning \"he hoped\" or \"he expected,\" and أَرْجَىٰ meaning \"he delayed\" or \"he postponed.\" The root conveys anticipation, expectation, and delay. مُرْجَوْنَ is a passive form meaning \"those deferred\" or \"those postponed,\" reflecting a state of being left in suspense. The connection lies in delay, causing suspense through hope and expectation, symbolizing individuals whose judgment or fate is pending. This term emphasizes uncertainty, reinforcing the tension of unresolved outcomes and the emotional weight of awaiting decisions.",
  "3653": "مُرْجِفٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ج-ف, with the root verb رَجَفَ meaning \"it shook\" or \"it trembled.\" مُرْجِفٌ means \"agitator\" or \"rumor-monger.\" The connection lies in causing disturbance or unrest, reflecting the root's emphasis on shaking. This term refers to individuals who spread fear or uncertainty through false information, highlighting the disruptive impact of such actions on societal stability.",
  "3654": "مُرْدِفٌ and related words stem from the root ر-د-ف, with the root verb رَدِفَ meaning \"he followed closely\" or \"he came after.\" مُرْدِفٌ means \"one who follows\" or \"a follower.\" The connection lies in describing someone who comes after another, reflecting the root's essence of close succession. It emphasizes the role of following in leadership, guidance, or events that unfold in sequence.",
  "3655": "مُرْسَلٌ and related words stem from the root ر-س-ل, with the root verb رَسَلَ meaning \"he sent.\" مُرْسَلٌ is a passive form meaning \"sent.\" The connection describes someone or something that has been dispatched, reflecting the root's essence of sending. In the Islamic context, it often refers to prophets who have been sent by Allah (ﷻ), emphasizing their role as messengers.",
  "3656": "مُرْسَلَةٌ and related words stem from the root ر-س-ل, with the root verb رَسَلَ meaning \"he sent.\" مُرْسَلَةٌ is a passive form meaning \"sent.\" The connection reflects something that has been dispatched or sent forth, embodying the root's essence of sending. It may refer to messages, winds, or other entities sent by Allah (ﷻ), highlighting His control over all affairs.",
  "3657": "مُرْسِلٌ and related words stem from the root ر-س-ل, with the root verb رَسَلَ meaning \"he sent\" or \"he dispatched.\" مُرْسِلٌ means \"sender,\" referring to one who initiates the act of sending. The root conveys themes of communication, transmission, and purposeful dispatching, emphasizing deliberate and meaningful action. The connection lies in the act of sending something of importance, often linked to Allah (ﷻ) as the sender of messengers, revelations, or decrees, highlighting His authority and wisdom in delivering guidance.",
  "3658": "مُرْسِلَةٌ and related words stem from the root ر-س-ل, with the root verb رَسَلَ meaning \"he sent\" or \"he dispatched.\" مُرْسِلَةٌ means \"sender,\" often referring to feminine entities such as the wind or other natural forces. The root highlights the deliberate and purposeful act of sending, connecting to the idea of natural phenomena as agents of Allah's (ﷻ) will. This term reflects the harmony and order in creation, where all actions serve a defined purpose under Allah's (ﷻ) command.",
  "3659": "مُرْشِدٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ش-د, with the root verb رَشَدَ meaning \"he was rightly guided\" or \"he was sensible.\" مُرْشِدٌ means \"guide\" or \"one who guides.\" The connection reflects someone who leads others to the right path, embodying the root's essence of guidance. It emphasizes the role of providing direction and wisdom to others.",
  "3660": "مُرْضِعَةٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ض-ع, with the root verb رَضَعَ meaning \"he suckled\" or \"he nursed.\" مُرْضِعَةٌ means \"a nursing woman\" or \"one who breastfeeds.\" The connection lies in the role of actively providing nourishment and care through breastfeeding, embodying the root's focus on nurturing and sustaining life. This term highlights the significance of the nursing mother, whose act of breastfeeding fosters growth, health, and the foundational emotional bond with the child.",
  "3661": "زَحْفٌ stems from the root ز-ح-ف, with the verb meaning \"he crawled\" or \"he advanced slowly.\" It refers to \"march\" or \"advancement,\" particularly describing the slow, deliberate movement of an army. The root conveys the concept of steady, intentional progress, reflected in the term as it highlights methodical and purposeful advancement toward a goal. This connection signifies the emphasis on slow, determined movement, often in challenging or deliberate circumstances.",
  "3662": "مُزَّمِّلٌ and related words stem from the root ز-م-ل, with the root verb زَمَلَ meaning \"he ran and went along quickly, leaning or bearing to one side as if carrying a weight,\" and زَمَّلَ meaning \"he wrapped.\" مُزَّمِّلٌ means \"one who wraps himself up\" or \"the enwrapped one.\" The root also conveys meanings of bundling, enclosing, or concealing something for protection or comfort. The connection lies in the imagery of running with a burden, transitioning into wrapping oneself for shelter or preparation. It reflects the need to pause and process a perceived burden, emphasizing a balance between action and introspection during moments of preparation or significant change.",
  "3663": "مُزِّقَ and related words stem from the root م-ز-ق, with the root verb مَزَّقَ meaning \"he tore\" or \"he tore to pieces.\" مُزِّقَ means \"it was torn\" or \"it was ripped apart.\" The root encompasses dimensions of violent tearing, fragmentation, and disintegration, often implying the complete separation or scattering of something. This includes both literal tearing, such as rending an object, and metaphorical meanings, such as the shattering of unity or order. مُزِّقَ emphasizes the action’s result, highlighting themes of destruction, loss, and fragmentation, where something once whole is violently divided or scattered.",
  "3664": "مُزْجَاةٌ and related words stem from the root ز-ج-و, with the verb زَجَا meaning \"he drove forward\" or \"he presented.\" مُزْجَاةٌ refers to \"slightly pushed forward\" or \"meager,\" often describing a humble or modest offering. The root conveys the idea of gentle propulsion or modest presentation, which is evident in مُزْجَاةٌ as it signifies something small or insufficient being presented with humility. This connection reflects the root's concept of advancing something forward in a subtle or restrained manner, emphasizing the modesty or limited nature of what is offered.",
  "3665": "مُزْدَجَرٌ and related words stem from the root ز-ج-ر, with the verb زَجَرَ meaning \"he rebuked,\" \"he restrained,\" or \"he admonished.\" مُزْدَجَرٌ refers to \"a place of restraint\" or \"a strong warning,\" signifying a location or means designed to deter wrongdoing. The root encompasses ideas of authority, control, and discipline, which are reflected in مُزْدَجَرٌ as a means of preventing deviation or enforcing correction. This connection underscores the root’s core concept of imposing restraint and delivering stern admonition to maintain order and prevent harm.",
  "3666": "مُزْنٌ and related words stem from the root م-ز-ن, which encompasses meanings related to rain and clouds. مُزْنٌ specifically refers to \"rain clouds,\" emphasizing the life-giving properties of water descending from the sky. The root also carries nuances of swiftness and firmness, reflecting the nature of rain clouds as they swiftly traverse the sky while appearing solid and firm in their formation. This connection highlights the dynamic and powerful presence of rain clouds, symbolizing vitality, sustenance, and the balance between motion and stability in nature’s processes.",
  "3667": "مُسَافِحِينَ and related words stem from the root س-ف-ح, with the root verb سَفَحَ meaning \"he poured forth\" or \"he shed.\" سِفَاحٌ means \"fornication\" or \"unlawful intimate acts,\" and مُسَافِحِينَ refers to \"fornicators\" or \"those who engage in unlawful intimate acts.\" The root’s theme of pouring forth extends metaphorically to the unrestrained indulgence of desires, highlighting the grave moral and spiritual consequences of violating boundaries. This term emphasizes the importance of chastity and moral integrity to preserve personal and societal well-being.",
  "3668": "مُسَافِحَاتٍ and related words stem from the root س-ف-ح, with the root verb سَفَحَ meaning \"he poured forth\" or \"he shed.\" سِفَاحٌ means \"fornication\" or \"unlawful intimate relations,\" and مُسَافِحَاتٍ refers to \"fornicatresses\" or \"women who engage in unlawful intimate acts.\" The root’s connection to shedding or pouring forth metaphorically reflects the unrestrained nature of unlawful desires. This term highlights the moral prohibition against such behavior and emphasizes the critical role of chastity for both men and women in fostering societal harmony and spiritual well-being.",
  "3669": "مُسَبِّحٌ and related words stem from the root س-ب-ح, with the root verb سَبَّحَ meaning \"he glorified.\" مُسَبِّحٌ means \"one who glorifies\" or \"one who praises.\" The connection lies in actively engaging in praise, embodying the root's concept of continuous movement towards Allah (ﷻ). مُسَبِّحٌ represents those who constantly remember and exalt the Creator.",
  "3670": "مُسَحَّرٌ and related words stem from the root س-ح-ر, with the root verb سَحَرَ meaning \"he bewitched.\" مُسَحَّرٌ is a passive form meaning \"enchanted\" or \"bewitched,\" possibly emphasizing a continual state. The connection highlights enduring effects of magic, relating to the root's concept. This term highlights prolonged influence of sorcery.",
  "3671": "مُسَخَّرٌ and related words stem from the root س-خ-ر, with the root verb سَخَّرَ meaning \"he subjugated.\" مُسَخَّرٌ is a passive form meaning \"subjugated\" or \"made subservient.\" It describes something brought under control or harnessed, directly relating to the root's concept. This term often refers to natural phenomena, such as the wind or the sun, which are made to serve human needs by Allah's (ﷻ) will, emphasizing divine wisdom and power.",
  "3672": "مُسَخَّرَاتٍ and related words stem from the root س-خ-ر, with the root verb سَخَّرَ meaning \"he subjugated.\" مُسَخَّرَاتٍ is a passive form meaning \"subjugated\" or \"made subservient.\" It describes entities that have been controlled or harnessed, often referring to natural elements like birds or forces in nature. This term highlights universal subjugation under Allah’s (ﷻ) command, emphasizing the purposeful design and harmony in creation.",
  "3673": "مُسَلَّمَةٌ and related words stem from the root س-ل-م, with the root verb سَلِمَ meaning \"he was safe,\" \"he was sound,\" or \"he was unharmed.\" مُسَلَّمَةٌ is a passive form meaning \"delivered,\" \"submitted,\" or \"granted,\" and can also mean \"unblemished\" in specific contexts. The connection to \"unblemished\" lies in the idea of being complete, intact, or free from defect, directly reflecting the root's emphasis on safety, soundness, and purity. It signifies something that has been preserved or handed over in its ideal state, aligning with the broader root dimensions of protection, reliability, and integrity.",
  "3674": "مُسَمًّى and related words stem from the root س-م-و, with the root verb سَمَا meaning \"he was high\" or \"he elevated.\" مُسَمًّى is a passive form, meaning \"named,\" \"designated,\" \"specified,\" or \"appointed.\" It refers to something or someone that has been officially recognized. The connection lies in the root's focus on elevation, where naming or assigning a title raises the status of the person or object. By being named, something is given recognition and importance, reflecting the root's theme of distinguishing and elevating through designation.",
  "3675": "مُسَنَّدَةٌ and related words stem from the root س-ن-د, with the root verb سَنَدَ meaning \"he supported\" or \"he leaned upon.\" مُسَنَّدَةٌ is a passive form meaning \"supported\" or \"propped up.\" The connection lies in something being given support or being reclined upon. It evokes the idea of rest, reliance, or reinforcement, emphasizing the need for support in both physical and metaphorical contexts.",
  "3676": "مُسَوَّمَةٌ and related words stem from the root س-و-م, with the root verb سَامَ meaning \"he marked,\" \"he branded,\" or \"he signified.\" مُسَوَّمَةٌ is a passive form meaning \"marked,\" \"branded,\" or \"designated.\" The connection is direct, indicating something that has been marked or assigned a sign, reflecting the root's focus on distinguishing features. In the Qur'an, this term is used to describe stones marked for punishment, symbolizing readiness and designation for a purpose.",
  "3677": "مُسَوِّمِينَ and related words stem from the root س-و-م, with the root verb سَامَ meaning \"he marked,\" \"he branded,\" or \"he signified.\" مُسَوِّمِينَ means \"those who have marks\" or \"those who are marked.\" The root emphasizes the act of marking or distinguishing, often used to make something clearly identifiable. In the Qur'an, this term refers to angels bearing distinct signs or marks, symbolizing their unmistakable role as helpers sent by Allah (ﷻ). These marks distinguish the angels, signifying their authority, purpose, and mission in supporting the believers.",
  "3678": "مُسِيءٌ and related words stem from the root س-و-أ, with the root verb سَاءَ meaning \"it was bad.\" مُسِيءٌ means \"one who does evil\" or \"offender.\" The connection identifies a person who actively engages in harmful actions. It emphasizes accountability and the moral character of individuals, urging self-reflection and improvement.",
  "3679": "مُسْتَأْخِرِينَ and related words stem from the root أ-خ-ر, with the root verb أَخَّرَ meaning \"he delayed\" or \"he postponed,\" and اسْتَأْخَرَ meaning \"he sought to delay\" or \"he stayed behind.\" مُسْتَأْخِرِينَ means \"ones who delay themselves\" or \"ones who lag behind,\" reflecting the intentional act of holding back or seeking postponement. When written as الْمُسْتَأْخِرِينَ, it is often translated as \"later generations,\" referring to those who come after in time or sequence. This reflects the concept of deferral or succession inherent in the root, emphasizing a position or group that follows after others.",
  "3680": "مُسْتَأْنِسِينَ and related words stem from the root أ-ن-س, with the root verb أَنَسَ meaning \"he was sociable,\" \"he found comfort,\" or \"he became familiar.\" مُسْتَأْنِسِينَ translates to \"those who seek familiarity,\" \"sociable,\" or \"companionable.\" The connection lies in the quality of being sociable and actively seeking comfort in companionship, reflecting the root’s emphasis on social interaction and familiarity. A  person who is مُسْتَأْنِسٌ is one who values social bonds and finds ease and enjoyment in the presence of others.",
  "3681": "مُسْتَبِين and related words stem from the root ب-ي-ن, with the root verb بَانَ meaning \"it became separated, severed, disunited, or cut off,\" or \"it became apparent, manifest, evident, or clear\" or \"it became distinct,\" implying separation from others. مُسْتَبِين means \"something that has become clear\" or \"one who is clear,\" describing clarity that emerges after ambiguity. The root conveys separating truth from obscurity, as if distinguishing one thing from another to make it fully visible, emphasizing clarity that is now unmistakably evident.",
  "3682": "مُسْتَبْشِرَةٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ش-ر, with the root verb بَشِرَ meaning \"he rejoiced\" or \"he was cheerful.\" مُسْتَبْشِرَةٌ refers to \"one who is joyful or delighted upon receiving good news,\" emphasizing the happiness and optimism that comes with hearing positive news. The root highlights themes of joy, relief, and hope, with مُسْتَبْشِرَةٌ capturing the uplifting and grateful response of the recipient. Unlike مُبَشِّرَةٌ (one who delivers good news), مُسْتَبْشِرَةٌ focuses on the joyful reaction, celebrating the emotional impact of the hopeful message.",
  "3683": "مُسْتَبْصِرِينَ and related words stem from the root ب-ص-ر, with the root verb بَصُرَ meaning \"he saw\" or \"he was endowed with mental perception, belief, firm belief, knowledge, understanding, intelligence, or skill.\" مُسْتَبْصِرِينَ refers to \"those endowed with perceptive faculties of the mind, knowledge, or skill,\" emphasizing a state of ongoing insight and deeper understanding. This form suggests individuals who continuously seek clarity, discernment, and awareness, highlighting a commitment to perceiving truth and gaining wisdom.",
  "3684": "مُسْتَخْفٍ and related words stem from the root خ-ف-ي, with the root verb خَفِيَ meaning \"he or it was hidden or concealed\" or \"he or it became unapparent.\" اِسْتَخْفَى means \"he sought to hide himself,\" and مُسْتَخْفٍ means \"one who seeks to hide\" or \"one who hides himself.\" The connection emphasizes the deliberate action of seeking concealment, reflecting a conscious effort to remain unseen. This symbolizes the human tendency to hide faults or actions, reminding us that while we may hide from others, nothing is hidden from Allah (ﷻ).",
  "3685": "مُسْتَخْلَفِينَ and related words stem from the root خ-ل-ف, with the root verb خَلَفَ meaning \"he came after\" or \"he succeeded.\" The root conveys succession, substitution, and contrast, where one follows or takes the place of another in position or responsibility. مُسْتَخْلَفِينَ is a passive form meaning \"successors\" or \"trustees,\" referring to those who have been entrusted with stewardship. This reflects both the honor and accountability of inheriting responsibilities, emphasizing the duty to uphold justice, maintain what has been entrusted, and act with wisdom in fulfilling one's role.",
  "3686": "مُسْتَسْلِمُونَ and related words stem from the root س-ل-م, with the root verb سَلِمَ meaning \"he was safe,\" \"he was sound,\" or \"he was unharmed.\" مُسْتَسْلِمُونَ means \"ones who submit\" or \"those who surrender.\" The connection lies in the act of willingly submitting or surrendering oneself, reflecting the root's focus on achieving safety and peace through submission. It emphasizes the conscious decision to yield or comply, often in pursuit of harmony or avoidance of conflict, highlighting themes of humility, acceptance, and reconciliation.",
  "3687": "مُسْتَضْعَفُونَ and related words stem from the root ض-ع-ف, with the root verb ضَعُفَ meaning \"he became weak.\" اسْتَضْعَفَ means \"he deemed weak\" or \"he considered someone weak.\" مُسْتَضْعَفُونَ is a passive form meaning \"those who are oppressed\" or \"those considered weak,\" referring to individuals who are rendered powerless, marginalized, or subjugated. The root’s themes of weakness and insufficiency connect to the plight of those who are exploited or denied agency due to their perceived lack of strength. This term highlights the injustices faced by the vulnerable, emphasizing the moral responsibility to support and uplift those who are oppressed and ensure justice prevails.",
  "3688": "مُسْتَطَرٌ and related words stem from the root س-ط-ر, with the root verb سَطَرَ meaning \"he wrote\" or \"he inscribed.\" مُسْتَطَرٌ is a passive form meaning \"that which is written\" or \"recorded.\" The connection lies in being inscribed or documented, reflecting the root's emphasis on writing and recording. This term highlights the comprehensive nature of what is written, suggesting all details have been meticulously inscribed.",
  "3689": "مُسْتَطِيرٌ and related words stem from the root ط-ي-ر, with the root verb طَارَ meaning \"he flew.\" مُسْتَطِيرٌ means \"spreading far and wide\" or \"scattering.\" The connection lies in the idea of something dispersing through the air like birds in flight, reflecting the root's concept of expansive movement. This term often describes things like fire or light that rapidly spread, symbolizing how quickly events or ideas can proliferate.",
  "3690": "مُسْتَعَانٌ and related words stem from the root ع-و-ن, with the root verb عَانَ meaning \"he helped,\" \"he assisted,\" or \"he supported.\" اسْتَعَانَ means \"he sought help,\" and مُسْتَعَانٌ is a passive form meaning \"one whose help is sought.\" The connection lies in focusing on the source of assistance, embodying the root's concept of aid but highlighting the entity from whom help is requested. This term refers to Allah (ﷻ) as the ultimate helper, emphasizing reliance on Allah (ﷻ) for support and guidance.",
  "3691": "مُسْتَغْفِرِينَ and related words stem from the root غ-ف-ر, with the root verb غَفَرَ meaning \"he forgave,\" \"he covered,\" or \"he concealed.\" مُسْتَغْفِرِينَ means \"those who seek forgiveness,\" describing individuals who actively request pardon and concealment of their sins from Allah (ﷻ). The connection lies in the root's dual meanings of forgiveness and covering, as seeking forgiveness inherently involves a plea for both pardon and the concealment of one's faults. This term reflects humility and self-awareness, as the seeker acknowledges their shortcomings and turns to Allah (ﷻ) in repentance, trusting in His mercy to cover and forgive their errors.",
  "3692": "مُسْتَقَرٌّ and related words stem from the root ق-ر-ر, with the root verb قَرَّ meaning \"he settled\" or \"he remained.\" اسْتَقَرَّ means \"he settled\" or \"he became stable,\" and مُسْتَقَرٌّ is the place or time meaning \"resting place,\" \"abode,\" or \"destination.\" The connection lies in embodying the root's concept of settling by denoting the place or time where one ultimately settles. This term emphasizes the idea of a final abode or destination, reminding believers of the temporary nature of worldly life and the importance of preparing for the everlasting settlement in the hereafter.",
  "3693": "مُسْتَقِرٌّ and related words stem from the root ق-ر-ر, with the root verb قَرَّ meaning \"he settled,\" \"he remained,\" or \"he became established.\" اِسْتَقَرَّ means \"he settled\" or \"he became firmly established,\" and مُسْتَقِرٌّ refers to \"a place of settlement,\" \"something firmly fixed,\" or \"a destination.\" It can also denote a state or condition that has been reached. As a noun, it can refer to a settled outcome, whether positive or negative, including matters such as punishment, final destinations, or firmly established truths. The root emphasizes themes of stability, permanence, and resolution, reflecting the idea of reaching a definitive point or state, whether in physical, emotional, or metaphysical contexts.",
  "3694": "مُسْتَقِيمٌ and related words stem from the root ق-و-م, with the root verb قامَ meaning \"he stood\" or \"he rose.\" The root conveys concepts of standing upright, straightness, and maintaining balance. مُسْتَقِيمٌ means \"straight,\" \"upright,\" or \"correct.\" It describes something that is straight or someone who is steadfast. The connection lies in embodying the state of being upright and unwavering, reflecting the root's essence of uprightness and stability. It emphasizes the importance of following a straight path, both physically and morally, aligning with themes of righteousness and integrity.",
  "3695": "مُسْتَقْبِلٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ب-ل, with the root verb قَبِلَ meaning \"he took, received, or admitted willingly,\" or \"he accepted.\" اِسْتَقْبَلَ means \"he faced\" or \"he approached,\" and مُسْتَقْبِلٌ means \"facing\" or \"approaching.\" The connection lies in the deliberate action of turning toward or orienting oneself toward something, reflecting the root's concept of receiving or directing attention. This highlights anticipation, readiness, and intentional engagement, often symbolizing an open and purposeful stance toward the future or welcoming forthcoming opportunities, perfectly aligning with the themes of acceptance and approach in the root.",
  "3696": "مُسْتَقْدِمِينَ and related words stem from the root ق-د-م, with the root verb قَدُمَ meaning \"he was ancient\" or \"he preceded.\" مُسْتَقْدِمِينَ means \"those who advance,\" \"those who come forward,\" or \"those who seek to proceed.\" It reflects an intentional effort to move ahead or occupy a leading position, emphasizing initiative and proactive pursuit. The root conveys themes of advancement, precedence, and being at the forefront, whether in action, thought, or position. This term highlights the deliberate nature of striving for progress, highlighting the importance of taking initiative in life’s endeavors and seeking to excel.",
  "3697": "مُسْتَكْبِرٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ب-ر, with the root verb كَبُرَ meaning \"he became great.\" مُسْتَكْبِرٌ means \"one who is arrogant,\" \"one who seeks to be great,\" or \"one who acts arrogantly.\" It emphasizes actively striving for greatness in a haughty manner, misusing the root’s concept of magnitude. This reflects the moral danger of arrogance, where self-aggrandizement overshadows humility and righteousness, leading to defiance and moral corruption.",
  "3698": "مُسْتَمِرٌّ and related words stem from the root م-ر-ر, with the root verb مَرَّ meaning \"he passed by,\" and اسْتَمَرَّ meaning \"he continued,\" \"he persisted,\" or \"he maintained.\" مُسْتَمِرٌّ means \"continuing,\" \"ongoing,\" or \"persistent.\" The root also conveys ideas of sharpness, bitterness, and resilience, symbolizing strength and the capacity to endure over time. These dimensions emphasize movement and progression, whether physical or metaphorical, where persistence leads to unbroken continuity. The connection to مُسْتَمِرٌّ reflects these qualities, highlighting a state of endurance and steadfastness, embodying the lasting nature of an action, condition, or process.",
  "3699": "مُسْتَمِعُونَ and related words stem from the root س-م-ع, with the root verb سَمِعَ meaning \"he heard\" or \"he listened.\" مُسْتَمِعُونَ means \"listeners\" or \"ones who listen attentively.\" It reflects someone who actively engages in listening, seeking to understand or learn. The connection highlights the role of the listener in communication, emphasizing attentiveness and the pursuit of knowledge through careful listening.",
  "3700": "مُسْتَمْسِكُونَ and related words stem from the root م-س-ك, with the root verb مَسَكَ meaning \"he held,\" and اسْتَمْسَكَ meaning \"he held firmly.\" مُسْتَمْسِكُونَ means \"those who hold fast\" or \"those who cling firmly.\" The connection lies in embodying the act of firmly grasping, reflecting the root's emphasis on holding. This highlights qualities of steadfastness and unwavering adherence to principles.",
  "3701": "مُسْتَنْفِرَةٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ف-ر, with the root verb نَفَرَ meaning \"he fled\" or \"he ran away.\" اسْتَنْفَرَ means \"he was alarmed\" or \"he took flight.\" مُسْتَنْفِرَةٌ means \"alarmed,\" \"startled,\" or \"fleeing.\" The connection lies in the imagery of animals or people reacting to sudden fright, fleeing in panic. In the Qur'anic context, it describes disbelievers turning away from the truth like startled donkeys fleeing from a lion, emphasizing their aversion and irrational fear, reflecting the root's emphasis on fleeing and being alarmed.",
  "3702": "مُسْتَهْزِئٌ and related words stem from the root ه-ز-أ, with the root verb هَزَأَ meaning \"he mocked,\" \"he ridiculed,\" or \"he scoffed.\" Derived from اسْتَهْزَأَ meaning \"he mocked,\" مُسْتَهْزِئٌ means \"one who mocks\" or \"a mocker.\" This term connects to the root's concept by describing someone who engages in ridicule. It emphasizes the act of belittling others, reflecting themes of scorn and contempt inherent in the root.",
  "3703": "مُسْتَوْدَعٌ and related words stem from the root و-د-ع, with the root verb وَدَعَ meaning \"he deposited,\" \"he left,\" or \"he entrusted.\" مُسْتَوْدَعٌ means \"repository,\" \"place of deposit,\" or \"temporary abode.\" The connection lies in the concept of something being entrusted for safekeeping, reflecting the transient nature of worldly life. This term emphasizes that all possessions and even life itself are temporary trusts from Allah (ﷻ), highlighting the root's focus on leaving or placing something in trust. In the Qur'an, it reminds us of the impermanence of our dwellings and the importance of preparing for the eternal hereafter.",
  "3704": "مُسْتَيْقِنِينَ and related words stem from the root ي-ق-ن, with the root verb يَقِنَ meaning \"he was certain.\" مُسْتَيْقِنِينَ means \"ones who have realized certainty\" or \"ones who are fully convinced.\" This term emphasizes certainty attained through effort, reflection, or investigation, highlighting an active process of seeking clarity and arriving at assurance. The connection lies in embodying the journey toward certainty, aligning with the root's focus on achieving firm belief through conscious examination and understanding.",
  "3705": "مُسْرِفٌ and related words stem from the root س-ر-ف, with the root verb سَرَفَ meaning \"he exceeded,\" \"he was extravagant,\" or \"he transgressed limits.\" مُسْرِفٌ means \"one who is extravagant,\" \"transgressor,\" or \"immoderate person.\" The connection lies in embodying the quality of exceeding proper bounds, directly reflecting the root's emphasis on excess. This term describes someone who habitually goes beyond limits, highlighting moral implications.",
  "3706": "مُسْفِرَةٌ and related words stem from the root س-ف-ر, with the root verb أَسْفَرَ meaning \"he made bright\" or \"he illuminated.\" مُسْفِرَةٌ means \"radiant\" or \"bright-faced.\" The connection lies in the state of being illuminated or shining, directly relating to the root's emphasis on unveiling brightness. This term conveys the image of faces beaming with happiness or enlightenment, symbolizing joy, clarity, and the positive effects of receiving guidance and embracing truth.",
  "3707": "مُسْلِمٌ and related words stem from the root س-ل-م, with the root verb سَلِمَ meaning \"he was safe,\" \"he was sound,\" or \"he was unharmed.\" مُسْلِمٌ means \"one who submits,\" specifically \"one who submits to Allah (ﷻ)\"—in other words, a \"Muslim.\" The connection lies in surrendering oneself to Allah’s (ﷻ) will to attain safety, peace, and spiritual harmony, reflecting the root's emphasis on soundness and well-being. It signifies an individual who embraces Islam, committing to its teachings and striving for obedience and devotion as a path to fulfillment.",
  "3708": "مُسْلِمَةٌ and related words stem from the root س-ل-م, with the root verb سَلِمَ meaning \"he was safe,\" \"he was sound,\" or \"he was unharmed.\" مُسْلِمَةٌ means \"female who submits,\" specifically \"Muslim woman.\" In some contexts, the feminine noun is used more broadly, such as to refer to a \"nation submitting\" to Allah (ﷻ). It highlights the act of willing submission and surrender to Allah’s (ﷻ) will to attain safety and peace, directly reflecting the root’s focus on soundness, security, and well-being.",
  "3709": "مُسْمَعٌ and related words stem from the root س-م-ع, with the root verb سَمِعَ meaning \"he heard\" or \"he listened.\" مُسْمَعٌ is a passive form meaning \"one who is made to hear\" or \"informed.\" It signifies someone who is caused to hear something, perhaps being given news or taught. The connection reflects the transmission of information from one party to another, emphasizing the reception of knowledge or messages.",
  "3710": "مُسْمِعٌ and related words stem from the root س-م-ع, with the root verb سَمِعَ meaning \"he heard\" or \"he listened.\" مُسْمِعٌ means \"one who makes others hear\" or \"communicator.\" It denotes someone who conveys information or speaks so that others may hear and understand. The connection emphasizes the role of the speaker or informer in facilitating understanding, highlighting the importance of clear and effective communication.",
  "3711": "مُسْوَدٌّ and related words stem from the root س-و-د, with the root verb اِسْوَدَّ meaning \"he became black\" or \"it turned dark.\" مُسْوَدٌّ is a passive form meaning \"blackened\" or \"darkened,\" describing something that has turned black. The root also includes سَادَ, meaning \"he attained dignity,\" and سَوَّدَ, meaning \"he blackened,\" often signifying sorrow or disgrace. مُسْوَدٌّ metaphorically describes faces darkened with grief or shame upon hearing news one dislikes, reflecting the emotional weight of discontent.",
  "3712": "مُسْوَدَّةٌ and related words stem from the root س-و-د, with the root verb اِسْوَدَّ meaning \"it became black\" or \"it turned dark.\" مُسْوَدَّةٌ is a passive form meaning \"blackened\" or \"darkened,\" describing something that has turned black. The root also includes سَادَ, meaning \"he attained dignity,\" and سَوَّدَ, meaning \"he blackened,\" often symbolizing sorrow or disgrace. In the Qur'an, مُسْوَدٌّ describes faces darkened with grief or shame on the Day of Judgment, emphasizing that dishonorable actions in this life lead to disgrace in the Hereafter.",
  "3713": "مُشَيَّدَةٌ and related words stem from the root ش-ي-د, with the root verb شَيَّدَ meaning \"he fortified\" or \"he built solidly.\" مُشَيَّدَةٌ is a passive form meaning \"fortified\" or \"strongly built.\" The connection lies in constructing something with exceptional strength and durability. مُشَيَّدَةٌ describes fortified structures designed for protection and endurance, symbolizing human attempts at creating security. It emphasizes the contrast between human-made fortifications and the ultimate security provided by faith.",
  "3714": "مُشْتَبِهٌ and related words stem from the root ش-ب-ه, with the root verb شَبَهَ meaning \"he resembled\" or \"he was similar to.\" مُشْتَبِهٌ means \"resembling\" or \"similar.\" The root conveys the idea of likeness or similarity, often highlighting shared characteristics or qualities between two things. It emphasizes how one thing can be compared to another, whether in appearance, behavior, or essence.",
  "3715": "مُشْتَرِكُونَ and related words stem from the root ش-ر-ك, with the root verb شَرَكَ meaning \"he shared\" or \"he participated.\" مُشْتَرِكُونَ means \"participants\" or \"those who share jointly.\" This form emphasizes mutual involvement and collaboration. The connection lies in the root's focus on partnership and collective action, highlighting active engagement in a shared endeavor and the shared consequences of the deeds committed.",
  "3716": "مُشْرِقٌ and related words stem from the root ش-ر-ق, with the root verb شَرَقَ meaning \"it rose\" or \"it shone.\" مُشْرِقٌ means \"shining\" or \"radiant,\" describing someone or something that is bright or illuminated. The connection lies in the root's focus on emitting light, highlighting qualities of brightness and the dispelling of darkness.",
  "3717": "مُشْرِكٌ and related words stem from the root ش-ر-ك, with the root verb شَرَكَ meaning \"he shared\" or \"he participated.\" مُشْرِكٌ means \"one who associates partners with Allah (ﷻ)\" or \"polytheist.\" This term embodies the root's concept of sharing in the context of divinity, where sharing is a profound misdeed. It highlights the act of violating \"Tawhid\", by attributing divine attributes to others besides Allah (ﷻ).",
  "3718": "مُشْرِكَةٌ and related words stem from the root ش-ر-ك, with the root verb شَرَكَ meaning \"he shared\" or \"he participated.\" مُشْرِكَةٌ means \"a female who associates partners with Allah (ﷻ)\" or \"female polytheist.\" The connection lies in the root's emphasis on sharing, applied here to denote a woman who engages in \"shirk\". It highlights the universal accountability in matters of faith and the prohibition of associating partners with Allah (ﷻ).",
  "3719": "مُشْفِقُونَ and related words stem from the root ش-ف-ق, with the root verb شَفِقَ meaning \"he was compassionate\" or \"he feared.\" مُشْفِقُونَ refers to \"those who fear\" or \"those who are compassionate,\" specifically individuals who show compassion out of fear for the well-being of others. The root emphasizes a combination of compassion and concern, where fear arises from empathy for others' safety or welfare. This fear is not mere dread, but a protective concern, reflecting deep care for others, particularly in times of potential harm.",
  "3720": "مُصَدِّقٌ and related words stem from the root ص-د-ق, with the root verb صَدَّقَ meaning \"he confirmed\" or \"he believed.\" مُصَدِّقٌ means \"one who confirms\" or \"believer.\" The connection lies in the root's focus on affirming truth. مُصَدِّقٌ describes someone who acknowledges the truthfulness of messages, particularly those from divine revelation.",
  "3721": "مُصَفًّى and related words stem from the root ص-ف-و, with the root verb صَفَا meaning \"it was pure\" or \"it was clear.\" صَفَّىٰ means \"he purified\" or \"he refined.\" مُصَفًّى is a passive form meaning \"purified\" or \"refined.\" The connection lies in the process of removing impurities to attain clarity, reflecting the root's emphasis on purity. In the Qur'an, it describes rivers in Paradise that are \"purified,\" signifying the ultimate refinement and perfection of blessings bestowed upon the righteous, free from any imperfections or discomforts of the worldly life.",
  "3722": "مُصَلِّينَ and related words stem from the root ص-ل-و, with the root verb صَلَّىٰ meaning \"he prayed.\" مُصَلِّينَ means \"those who pray.\" The connection lies in actively engaging in prayer, reflecting the root's emphasis on devotion and continuous worship. In the Qur'an, it describes the believers who are constant in their prayers, highlighting prayer as a defining characteristic of the faithful and a means to attain success.",
  "3723": "مُصَلًّىٰ and related words stem from the root ص-ل-و, with the root verb صَلَّىٰ meaning \"he prayed.\" مُصَلًّىٰ means \"place of prayer\" or \"prayer area.\" The connection lies in the designated space for performing prayers, embodying the root's focus on worship and devotion. In Islamic practice, مُصَلًّى can refer to any clean place suitable for prayer, emphasizing that the earth has been made a place of worship, facilitating the believer's connection with Allah (ﷻ) anywhere.",
  "3724": "مُصَوِّرٌ and related words stem from the root ص-و-ر, with the root verb صَوَّرَ meaning \"he fashioned,\" \"he shaped,\" or \"he gave form.\" مُصَوِّرٌ means \"the one who forms\" or \"the fashioner,\" highlighting the act of creating distinct forms and features. ٱلْمُصَوِّرُ, one of Allah's (ﷻ) perfect names, refers to \"The Fashioner\" or \"The Shaper,\" emphasizing Allah’s (ﷻ) role in giving every creation its unique form and characteristics. The root conveys themes of artistry, precision, and uniqueness in design. This name signifies that Allah (ﷻ) not only creates but meticulously shapes every being, reflecting His infinite wisdom and care.",
  "3725": "مُصَيْطِرٌ and related words stem from the root س-ط-ر, with the root verb سَطَرَ meaning \"he wrote\" or \"he inscribed,\" and سَيْطَرَ meaning \"he controlled,\" \"he dominated,\" or \"he exercised authority.\" مُصَيْطِرٌ means \"one who has authority,\" \"controller,\" or \"dominator.\" The connection lies in the root's emphasis on control and governance, where the act of writing or inscribing metaphorically extends to shaping, directing, and overseeing. This term reflects someone who exercises dominance or power over others, symbolizing authority, leadership, and the capacity to regulate or command. It highlights the dynamic of exerting influence and control, whether in a physical, social, or organizational context.",
  "3726": "مُصِيبٌ and related words stem from the root ص-و-ب, with the root verb صَابَ meaning \"he aimed at\" or \"he hit the mark.\" مُصِيبٌ means \"one who hits the mark\" or \"one who strikes accurately.\" The connection lies in the act of precision, where the target is reached without deviation. This term conveys the idea of accuracy, as well as the inevitable and precise nature of events or actions that befall a person, reflecting the root's focus on correctness, impact, and the inevitability of outcomes.",
  "3727": "مُصِيبَةٌ and related words stem from the root ص-و-ب, with the root verb صَابَ meaning \"he aimed at\" or \"he hit the mark.\" مُصِيبَةٌ refers to \"a calamity,\" \"an affliction,\" or \"a misfortune.\" The connection lies in the notion of a distressing event that precisely strikes or befalls an individual, as though aimed specifically at them. This term emphasizes the precision and inevitability of trials and hardships, highlighting how afflictions reach people with exactness and purpose, reflecting the root's concept of accuracy and hitting the intended target.",
  "3728": "مُصَّدِّقِينَ and related words stem from the root ص-د-ق, with the root verb صَدَّقَ meaning \"he believed,\" \"he confirmed,\" or \"he considered truthful.\" مُصَّدِّقِينَ means \"men who give charity,\" emphasizing consistent and faithful engagement in charitable acts. The root conveys themes of truthfulness and steadfastness, linking the act of giving charity to the idea of confirming one’s faith through action. مُصَّدِّقِينَ portrays charity as a regular and truthful expression of one’s belief, connecting sincerity in faith with outward acts of generosity.",
  "3729": "مُصَّدِّقَاتٍ and related words stem from the root ص-د-ق, with the root verb صَدَّقَ meaning \"he believed,\" \"he confirmed,\" or \"he considered truthful.\" مُصَّدِّقَاتٍ means \"women who give charity,\" emphasizing sincerity and faithfulness in their acts of giving. The root highlights themes of truth and reliability, linking charity to the expression of belief through generous actions. مُصَّدِّقَاتٍ represents women who consistently and truthfully give in charity, highlighting their dedication and faith through acts of compassion.",
  "3730": "مُصْبِحِينَ and related words stem from the root ص-ب-ح, with the root verb صَبَحَ meaning \"he entered the morning.\" مُصْبِحِينَ means \"ones who enter the morning\" or \"morning arrivers.\" The connection lies in the action of beginning a new day. مُصْبِحِينَ refers to someone who wakes up to embrace the opportunities of the morning, highlighting the theme of renewal and readiness to engage with life's tasks.",
  "3731": "مُصْرِخِيَّ and related words stem from the root ص-ر-خ, with the root verb صَرَخَ meaning \"he cried out.\" مُصْرِخِيَّ means \"one who makes another cry out\" or \"one who responds to a cry.\" The connection lies in causing someone to cry out or in providing assistance when they do, symbolizing the act of aiding someone in distress or responding to a call for help. This term emphasizes the role of intervening or offering support during moments of anguish or need.",
  "3732": "مُصْطَفَيْنَ and related words stem from the root ص-ف-و, with the root verb صَفَا meaning \"it was pure\" or \"it was clear.\" اِصْطَفَىٰ means \"he selected\" or \"he chose for himself.\" مُصْطَفَيْنَ is a passive form meaning \"those who are chosen\" or \"the selected ones.\" The connection lies in being chosen for purity and excellence, embodying the root's focus on selection of the finest. In the Qur'an, it refers to prophets and righteous individuals chosen by Allah (ﷻ), emphasizing their elevated status and the trust placed in them to convey His message.",
  "3733": "مُصْفَرٌّ and related words stem from the root ص-ف-ر, with the root verb اصْفَرَّ meaning \"it turned yellow\" or \"it became pale.\" مُصْفَرٌّ is a passive form meaning \"turned yellow,\" describing the process by which an object or entity changes color. The root encompasses meanings of brightness, yellowness, and paleness, reflecting a visible transformation. مُصْفَرٌّ specifically refers to the result of this change, often indicating a shift in appearance associated with external conditions, such as sunlight or natural aging. This term directly ties to the root’s focus on color and its observable variations, emphasizing the state of yellowing as a physical transformation.",
  "3734": "مُصْلِحُونَ and related words stem from the root ص-ل-ح, with the root verb صَلَحَ meaning \"he was righteous,\" or \"he was good.\" أَصْلَحَ means \"he reformed.\" مُصْلِحُونَ means \"reformers\" or \"ones who set things right.\" The connection lies in actively working to improve or correct, embodying the root's emphasis on rectification. In the Qur'an, it describes those who strive to spread goodness and prevent corruption, highlighting the commendable role of individuals who contribute positively to society and uphold moral values.",
  "3735": "مُضَارٌّ and related words stem from the root ض-ر-ر, with the root verb ضَرَّ meaning \"he harmed\" or \"he injured.\" مُضَارٌّ means \"one who causes reciprocal harm\" or \"an opponent in causing injury.\" The connection lies in embodying the root's concept of harm within mutual opposition, emphasizing the dynamics of conflict where harm is both given and received. This term highlights the destructive nature of retaliatory harm.",
  "3736": "مُضَاعَفَةٌ and related words stem from the root ض-ع-ف, with the root verb ضَعُفَ meaning \"he became weak.\" The verb ضَاعَفَ means \"he doubled\" or \"he increased,\" and مُضَاعَفَةٌ refers to \"doubling\" or \"multiplication,\" describing the act of increasing something in size, amount, or magnitude. The root connection lies in the notion of amplifying or augmenting beyond its original state. In certain contexts, this term highlights wrongful or excessive increase, where such multiplication becomes harmful, unjust, or exploitative, emphasizing the need for fairness and ethical conduct in dealings.",
  "3737": "مُضِلٌّ and related words stem from the root ض-ل-ل, with the root verb ضَلَّ meaning \"he went astray.\" مُضِلٌّ means \"one who misleads\" or \"misleader.\" The connection lies in the causative aspect of the root, emphasizing the act of leading others into error. This term highlights the significant influence one can have on others, with a focus on the ethical responsibility tied to guiding others, emphasizing the consequences of misleading and the importance of acting in truth.",
  "3738": "مُضِيٌّ and related words stem from the root م-ض-ي, with the root verb مَضَىٰ meaning \"he proceeded\" or \"he departed.\" مُضِيٌّ refers to \"passing,\" \"proceeding,\" or \"departure,\" emphasizing an ongoing state of movement or transition. This term reflects the root's core concept of progression, highlighting the continuous flow of time and the inevitability of moving forward. مُضِيٌّ embodies themes of transience and impermanence, symbolizing the relentless progression of events and the passage of life’s moments. It can also signify purposeful motion, where movement is not merely passive but a deliberate act of advancing or leaving something behind.",
  "3739": "مُضْطَرٌّ and related words stem from the root ض-ر-ر, with the root verb ضَرَّ meaning \"he harmed\" or \"he injured.\" مُضْطَرٌّ means \"one who is compelled\" or \"the desperate one,\" referring to a person in a state of necessity. The connection lies in how compulsion arises from harmful or pressing circumstances, aligning with the root's emphasis on harm affecting one's condition. This term highlights human vulnerability and the urgency of dire situations.",
  "3740": "مُضْعِفُونَ and related words stem from the root ض-ع-ف, with the root verb ضَعُفَ meaning \"he became weak.\" مُضْعِفُونَ refers to \"those who receive manifold increase\" or \"those whose efforts are multiplied.\" It describes individuals whose limited actions or contributions are abundantly increased, often in a way that surpasses their original effort. The root’s connection to weakness highlights the idea of transforming insufficiency into abundance through purposeful action, highlighting themes of reward, growth, and the immense potential for increase beyond one's means.",
  "3741": "مُضْغَةٌ and related words stem from the root م-ض-غ, with the root verb مَضَغَ meaning \"he chewed\" or \"he masticated.\" مُضْغَةٌ refers to \"a piece of chewed flesh\" or \"an embryo at the stage where it resembles a lump of chewed flesh.\" The connection lies in the striking visual and structural resemblance of the embryo at this stage to a small, chewed piece of flesh, directly reflecting the root's concept of chewing. This imagery vividly highlights the intricate and miraculous stages of human development, symbolizing the precision and wonder of creation as described in the Qur'an.",
  "3742": "مُطَاعٌ and related words stem from the root ط-و-ع, with the root verb طَاعَ meaning \"he obeyed\" or \"he complied willingly.\" مُطَاعٌ is a passive form meaning \"one who is obeyed\" or \"obeyed.\" It denotes someone who commands obedience from others. This connects to the root by emphasizing the authority or status of being the object of others' willingness to comply. In certain contexts, it may refer to figures of authority or leadership who are followed out of respect and recognition.",
  "3743": "مُطَفِّفِينَ and related words stem from the root ط-ف-ف, with the root verb طَفَّ meaning \"he made deficient\" or \"he gave short measure.\" مُطَفِّفِينَ means \"ones who defraud\" or \"cheaters,\" particularly by giving less in measure or weight. The connection lies in the act of diminishing what is due to others, directly reflecting the root's concept of deficiency and deceit. This term highlights the moral failing of dishonesty in transactions, emphasizing the importance of fairness and integrity.",
  "3744": "مُطَلَّقَةٌ and related words stem from the root ط-ل-ق, with the root verbs طَلَقَ meaning \"he released\" or \"he made free,\" and طَلَّقَ meaning \"he divorced.\" مُطَلَّقَةٌ is a passive form meaning \"divorced woman.\" The connection lies in being released from the marriage bond, directly reflecting the root's concept of liberation or separation, symbolizing freedom from the mutually agreed contractual obligations of the marital relationship.",
  "3745": "مُطَهَّرٌ and related words stem from the root ط-ه-ر, with the root verb طَهَرَ meaning \"he was or became clean or pure.\" مُطَهَّرٌ is a passive form meaning \"purified\" or \"cleansed.\" It signifies something that has undergone purification. This connects back to the root by representing the state of having achieved purity through an external action, highlighting the result of the purification process.",
  "3746": "مُطَهَّرَةٌ and related words stem from the root ط-ه-ر, with the root verb طَهَرَ meaning \"he was or became clean,\" \"he was purified,\" or \"he became free from impurities.\" مُطَهَّرَةٌ is a passive form meaning \"purified\" or \"cleansed,\" describing something that has been made clean or free from physical or spiritual impurities. The root conveys themes of cleanliness, purity, and freedom from blemish or corruption, whether physical, moral, or spiritual. مُطَهَّرَةٌ signifies an elevated state of purity, often associated with sanctity or refinement. The term reflects the root’s emphasis on the process and result of purification, highlighting the importance of cleanliness and purity in fostering spiritual and moral excellence.",
  "3747": "مُطَهِّرٌ and related words stem from the root ط-ه-ر, with the root verb طَهَرَ meaning \"he was or became clean or pure.\" مُطَهِّرٌ means \"one who purifies\" or \"purifier.\" It denotes an agent who purifies others or things, reflecting the act of cleansing or purifying from impurity. This term highlights the importance of purity in both physical and spiritual realms, emphasizing the role of purification in achieving a state of cleanliness.",
  "3748": "مُطَّلِعُونَ and related words stem from the root ط-ل-ع, with the root verb طَلَعَ meaning \"he rose\" or \"he emerged,\" indicating the appearance or rising of something. اِطَّلَعَ means \"he became aware\" or \"he discovered,\" reflecting the emergence of awareness or knowledge. مُطَّلِعُونَ means \"observers\" or \"ones who are informed,\" emphasizing those who have gained insight, as though they have witnessed or perceived something that has emerged. The connection lies in the idea of knowledge or awareness surfacing, mirroring the root's focus on emergence and visibility. This highlights the pursuit of understanding and the active discovery of truth.",
  "3749": "مُطَّهِّرِينَ and related words stem from the root ط-ه-ر, with the root verb طَهَرَ meaning \"he was or became clean or pure.\" مُطَّهِّرِينَ in an intensified form meaning \"ones who thoroughly purify.\" The emphasis in this form signifies someone who purifies extensively or completely. This connects to the root by amplifying the concept of purification, highlighting an enhanced role in cleansing and purifying, possibly in a spiritual or moral sense.",
  "3750": "مُطَّوِّعٌ and related words stem from the root ط-و-ع, with the root verb طَاعَ meaning \"he obeyed\" or \"he complied willingly.\" مُطَّوِّعٌ means \"one who volunteers\" or \"volunteer.\" This form emphasizes the person who willingly offers themselves for service or extra deeds. The connection to the root highlights the aspect of self-motivated compliance and eagerness to perform good acts beyond obligation.",
  "3751": "مُطْمَئِنٌّ and related words stem from the root ط-م-أ-ن, with the root verb طَمَأَنَ meaning \"he was tranquil.\" مُطْمَئِنٌّ means \"tranquil\" or \"content,\" describing one who possesses inner peace. The connection lies in embodying a state of serenity, directly reflecting the root's concept of tranquility. This term emphasizes steadfastness and composure, often in the face of adversity.",
  "3752": "مُطْمَئِنَّةٌ and related words stem from the root ط-م-أ-ن, with the root verb طَمَأَنَ meaning \"he was tranquil,\" \"he was at ease,\" or \"he was reassured.\" مُطْمَئِنَّةٌ means \"tranquil,\" \"serene,\" or \"at peace,\" describing a state of deep calmness and reassurance. The root conveys themes of stillness, stability, and inner harmony, emphasizing a state free from agitation or doubt. مُطْمَئِنَّةٌ reflects ultimate spiritual tranquility, famously used to describe the \"soul at peace\" (النَّفْسُ الْمُطْمَئِنَّةُ), highlighting the profound contentment achieved through submission to Allah (ﷻ) and the alignment of one's heart and actions with divine guidance.",
  "3753": "مُظْلِمُونَ and related words stem from the root ظ-ل-م, with the root verb ظَلَمَ meaning \"he wronged\" or \"he oppressed,\" and أَظْلَمَ meaning \"it became dark\" or \"he made dark.\" مُظْلِمُونَ means \"those who cause darkness\" or \"those who are in a state of darkness.\" The connection highlights both the literal and metaphorical meanings of darkness, reflecting the root's concept of oppression and injustice. It emphasizes a state of moral or physical obscurity, where clarity and righteousness are obscured. This term can be understood as a description of those who act unjustly, bringing about harm or confusion, or those immersed in spiritual or ethical darkness, disconnected from truth and guidance.",
  "3754": "مُعَاجِزِينَ and related words stem from the root ع-ج-ز, with the root verb عَجَزَ meaning \"he was weak\" or \"he failed.\" مُعَاجِزِينَ means \"those who cause failure\" or \"those who challenge to the point of incapacity.\" The connection lies in the root's concept of weakness or inability, and this form highlights the active role of causing someone or something to fail, whether through direct opposition or by creating conditions where success becomes impossible. This emphasizes a sense of struggle or conflict, where one seeks to overwhelm or incapacitate the other.",
  "3755": "مُعَذَّبٌ and related words stem from the root ع-ذ-ب, with the root verb عَذَّبَ meaning \"he punished.\" مُعَذَّبٌ is a passive form meaning \"one who is punished\" or \"tormented.\" The connection is direct, describing someone who is undergoing punishment, reflecting the root's focus on restraint and correction. This term serves as a reminder of the consequences of wrongdoing and the importance of seeking forgiveness and adhering to righteous conduct.",
  "3756": "مُعَذِّبٌ and related words stem from the root ع-ذ-ب, with the root verb عَذَّبَ meaning \"he punished.\" مُعَذِّبٌ means \"one who punishes\" or \"tormentor.\" The connection lies in the role of administering punishment, directly relating to the root's emphasis on restraint and correction. This term highlights the aspect of justice and the execution of consequences for wrongdoing, emphasizing the seriousness of transgression.",
  "3757": "مُعَذِّرُونَ and related words stem from the root ع-ذ-ر, with the root verb عَذَرَ meaning \"he excused\" or \"he pardoned.\" مُعَذِّرُونَ means \"ones who make excuses.\" It reflects the action of continually presenting justifications or apologies, connected to the root's concept of excusing and seeking pardon. This term may carry a connotation of excessive excuse-making, highlighting the moral lesson of taking responsibility rather than constantly deflecting blame through excuses.",
  "3758": "مُعَطَّلَةٌ and related words stem from the root ع-ط-ل, with the root verb عَطَلَ meaning \"he left empty\" or \"he neglected.\" مُعَطَّلَةٌ means \"abandoned,\" \"idle,\" or \"neglected.\" The connection lies in something being left without care or use, reflecting the root's emphasis on emptiness and neglect. This term can describe objects, duties, or even societies that are left unfulfilled or unattended, highlighting the consequences of abandonment.",
  "3759": "مُعَقِّبٌ and related words stem from the root ع-ق-ب, with the root verb عَقِبَ meaning \"he followed.\" مُعَقِّبٌ means \"one who follows up\" or \"one who overturns.\" The connection lies in the act of pursuing or coming after something to alter or reverse it, reflecting the root's emphasis on succession and action. This term can signify someone who revises or changes what has been established, highlighting the potential for alteration or correction.",
  "3760": "مُعَقِّبَاتٌ and related words stem from the root ع-ق-ب, with the root verb عَقِبَ meaning \"he followed.\" مُعَقِّبَاتٌ refers to \"ones who follow up\" or \"successive ones,\" highlighting a continuous and organized sequence of actions or entities. This term signifies beings or forces that act in succession, ensuring no interruption in their assigned roles or duties. In this context, it refers to angels who follow one another in turns, guarding and overseeing individuals by Allah’s (ﷻ) command. These angels provide protection and ensure divine decrees are fulfilled, symbolizing the meticulous and unceasing nature of their duties.",
  "3761": "مُعَلَّقَةٌ and related words stem from the root ع-ل-ق, with the root verb عَلِقَ meaning \"he clung\" or \"he adhered,\" conveying a sense of attachment, adherence, or sticking firmly to something. عَلَّقَ intensifies this meaning, signifying \"he hung\" or \"he suspended,\" often implying a deliberate act of attaching or suspending something in a way that it remains connected or dependent on another. مُعَلَّقَةٌ means \"suspended,\" \"hanging,\" or \"dependent,\" capturing the state of being hung or left in suspension. The root extends to themes of attachment, dependence, or something being left in an uncertain or intermediate state, as with something suspended in the air or metaphorically left unresolved.",
  "3762": "مُعَلَّمٌ and related words stem from the root ع-ل-م, with the root verb عَلِمَ meaning \"he knew,\" \"he became aware,\" or \"he understood,\" and عَلَّمَ meaning \"he taught\" or \"he caused to know.\" مُعَلَّمٌ is a passive form meaning \"taught\" or \"instructed,\" denoting the state of having been given knowledge. This reflects the root's essence of knowledge transfer and education, emphasizing the relationship between the learner and the one who imparts understanding, embodying the concept of acquired knowledge and instruction.",
  "3763": "مُعَمَّرٌ and related words stem from the root ع-م-ر, with the root verb عَمَرَ meaning \"he lived long,\" \"he inhabited,\" or \"he enriched.\" مُعَمَّرٌ is a passive form meaning \"granted long life\" or \"made to live long.\" The connection lies in the blessing of extended life, reflecting the root's focus on longevity and the continued opportunity to contribute to the world's enrichment. It highlights the honor of advanced age, suggesting wisdom and experience that can benefit others and further the cultivation of goodness.",
  "3764": "مُعَوِّقِينَ and related words stem from the root ع-و-ق, with the root verb عَاقَ meaning \"he hindered,\" \"he prevented,\" or \"he restrained.\" It encompasses \"obstructing,\" \"delaying,\" and \"holding back.\" مُعَوِّقِينَ means \"those who hinder.\" The connection lies in actively causing delays or creating obstacles, embodying the root's essence of hindrance. This term highlights the role of someone who intentionally impedes progress, reflecting the root's emphasis on obstruction. It serves as a caution against being a barrier to positive actions, highlighting the negative impact of such hindrances on individual and collective advancement.",
  "3765": "مُعْتَبِينَ and related words stem from the root ع-ت-ب, with the root verb عَتَبَ meaning \"he blamed\" or \"he reproached.\" أَعْتَبَ means \"he satisfied\" or \"he made content.\" مُعْتَبِينَ is a passive form meaning \"ones who are satisfied\" or \"appeased.\" The connection lies in transforming blame into satisfaction, reflecting the root's concept of moving from displeasure to contentment. It highlights reconciliation and the restoration of harmony after discord, emphasizing the act of bringing peace and settling conflicts.",
  "3766": "مُعْتَدٍ and related words stem from the root ع-د-و, with the root verb عَدَا meaning \"he transgressed\" or \"he acted aggressively.\" اِعْتَدَىٰ means \"he transgressed,\" and مُعْتَدٍ means \"transgressor\" or \"aggressor.\" The connection is direct, describing one who exceeds limits or violates rights, reflecting the root's emphasis on transgression. This term serves as a warning against becoming one who commits injustice, emphasizing the moral imperative to respect boundaries set by divine law.",
  "3767": "مُعْتَدِينَ and related words stem from the root ع-د-و, with the root verb عَدَا meaning \"he transgressed\" or \"he acted aggressively.\" اِعْتَدَىٰ means \"he transgressed,\" and مُعْتَدِينَ means \"ones who commit aggression\" or \"transgressors.\" The connection lies in describing someone who actively exceeds limits, directly relating to the root's emphasis on transgression. This term highlights the personal responsibility to avoid injustice and aggression, emphasizing the ethical call to uphold justice.",
  "3768": "مُعْتَرٌّ and related words stem from the root ع-ر-ر, with the verb عَرَّ meaning \"it became mangy or scabby,\" often referring to camels afflicted by a skin disease causing visible lesions. مُعْتَرٌّ refers to \"a person who, without explicitly asking, shows interest in receiving assistance through indirect means or gestures.\" This person’s need is evident through presence or behavior that indicates hardship. The connection lies in the metaphor of being \"marked\" by difficulty, reflecting visible signs of affliction or need. This term highlights the importance of recognizing and addressing unspoken struggles, embodying the root’s themes of visibility and hardship.",
  "3769": "مُعْجِزِينَ and related words stem from the root ع-ج-ز, with the root verb عَجَزَ meaning \"he was weak\" or \"he failed.\" أَعْجَزَ means \"he made incapable\" or \"he incapacitated.\" مُعْجِزِينَ means \"ones who incapacitate\" or \"overpowering.\" The connection emphasizes causing others to experience weakness or failure, reflecting the root's concept of incapacity, but directed outwardly. This form highlights the active role of overwhelming or rendering others unable to achieve their goals, emphasizing power and control in the context of incapacitation.",
  "3770": "مُعْرِضُونَ and related words stem from the root ع-ر-ض, with the root verb عَرَضَ meaning \"he presented\" or \"he offered.\" مُعْرِضُونَ means \"ones who turn away\" or \"ones who avoid.\" The connection lies in the action of deliberately turning away from something presented, directly relating to the root's concept of presentation but indicating a rejection. This term highlights the moral implications of ignoring guidance or truth, emphasizing the need for attentiveness and receptiveness in spiritual matters.",
  "3771": "مُعْصِرَاتٌ and related words stem from the root ع-ص-ر, with the root verb عَصَرَ meaning \"he squeezed\" or \"he pressed.\" مُعْصِرَاتٌ refers to \"rain-bearing clouds\" ready to release rain. The connection lies in the imagery of clouds squeezing out rain, reflecting the root's emphasis on pressing or extracting. This term beautifully illustrates how clouds release their stored water, much like juice is extracted from fruit through pressing.",
  "3772": "مُغَاضِبٌ and related words stem from the root غ-ض-ب, with the root verb غَضِبَ meaning \"he was angry\" or \"he became enraged.\" مُغَاضِبٌ means \"one who distances themselves due to angry\" or \"one who departs in anger,\" emphasizing a person actively expressing or acting upon their anger. Broader root meanings include intense displeasure and forceful emotional responses, reflecting the consuming and often impulsive nature of anger. The connection lies in describing someone driven by strong emotions to the extent of leaving or distancing themselves due to anger.",
  "3773": "مُغَيِّرٌ and related words stem from the root غ-ي-ر, with the root verb غَارَ meaning \"he brought provision,\" \"he benefited,\" \"he bestowed something good,\" \"he was jealous,\" or \"he was protective.\" The derived verb غَيَّرَ conveys the idea of \"altering\" or \"changing something.\" مُغَيِّرٌ means \"one who changes\" or \"transformer,\" emphasizing the active role of initiating transformation. This word reflects the power, intentionality, and responsibility of those who bring about change, whether within themselves or in their surroundings, tying directly to the root's themes of alteration, benefit, and proactive influence.",
  "3774": "مُغِيرَةٌ and related words stem from the root غ-ي-ر, with the root verb غَارَ meaning \"he brought provision,\" \"he benefited,\" \"he bestowed something good,\" \"he was jealous,\" or \"he was protective.\" The word مُغِيرَةٌ is connected to sudden and decisive action, meaning \"one who attacks\" or \"raider,\" highlighting a swift and impactful change in circumstances. It reflects the root's association with movement and the disruption or alteration of the existing state of affairs, illustrating both the intensity and the transformative nature of such actions.",
  "3775": "مُغْتَسَلٌ and related words stem from the root غ-س-ل, with the root verb غَسَلَ meaning \"he washed\" or \"he cleansed.\" مُغْتَسَلٌ means \"a place of washing\" or \"water used for washing.\" The connection lies in the means or location associated with the act of cleansing, directly relating to the root's meaning of washing. This term highlights the provision of a facility or resource for purification, emphasizing the importance of cleanliness in physical and spiritual contexts.",
  "3776": "مُغْرَقُونَ and related words stem from the root غ-ر-ق, with the root verb غَرِقَ meaning \"he drowned,\" \"he sank,\" or \"he was submerged.\" مُغْرَقُونَ is a passive form meaning \"ones who are drowned\" or \"ones who are submerged.\" The connection lies in being the recipient of the action of drowning, directly relating to the root's meaning of submersion. This term highlights a state of being completely overwhelmed or consumed, often used to describe those overtaken by calamity or judgment, such as the people drowned during the time of Prophet Noah (ﷺ).",
  "3777": "مُغْرَمٌ and related words stem from the root غ-ر-م, with the root verb غَرِمَ meaning \"he incurred a debt,\" \"he became liable,\" or \"he suffered loss.\" مُغْرَمٌ means \"one who is indebted\" or \"one who is liable,\" describing a person burdened by an obligation or liability, often financial. The connection lies in the root’s emphasis on incurring responsibility or loss, reflecting the weight and obligation associated with being in debt. This term highlights the emotional and material toll of indebtedness, linking the state of being burdened with the broader root themes of liability and hardship.",
  "3778": "مُغْنُونَ and related words stem from the root غ-ن-ي, with the root verb غَنِيَ meaning \"he was rich,\" \"self-sufficient,\" or \"free from want.\" مُغْنُونَ means \"those who are self-sufficient\" or \"those free from want,\" describing individuals who possess sufficiency and independence without reliance on others. This reflects the root's emphasis on abundance and self-sufficiency. ٱلْمُغْنِي, one of Allah's (ﷻ) perfect names, refers to \"The Enricher\" or \"The Provider of Sufficiency,\" highlighting Allah’s (ﷻ) limitless ability to bestow independence and wealth upon whomever He wills. It emphasizes that Allah (ﷻ) is the ultimate source of provision, reminding us to seek sufficiency and sustenance from Him alone.",
  "3779": "مُفَتَّحَةٌ and related words stem from the root ف-ت-ح, with the root verb فَتَحَ meaning \"he opened.\" مُفَتَّحَةٌ is a passive form meaning \"opened\" or \"wide open,\" often describing gates or doors. The connection lies in the state of being fully opened, reflecting the root's concept of accessibility. It emphasizes readiness and welcome, such as the gates of Paradise being open to the righteous, symbolizing ultimate acceptance and reward.",
  "3780": "مُفَصَّلٌ and related words stem from the root ف-ص-ل, with the root verb فَصَلَ meaning \"he separated,\" \"he divided,\" or \"he distinguished.\" مُفَصَّلٌ is a passive form meaning \"detailed,\" \"elaborated,\" or \"distinctly explained,\" referring to something that has been divided into clear and separate parts for better understanding. The root conveys themes of separation, clarity, and distinction, emphasizing the act of making something explicit and unambiguous. مُفَصَّلٌ describes information, rulings, or texts that have been systematically broken down and clarified, reflecting the root’s focus on precision and thoroughness in explanation.",
  "3781": "مُفَصَّلَاتٍ and related words stem from the root ف-ص-ل, with the root verb فَصَلَ meaning \"he separated,\" \"he divided,\" or \"he distinguished.\" مُفَصَّلَاتٍ is a passive form meaning \"detailed\" or \"elaborated,\" applied to feminine nouns that have been broken down into distinct parts. The root conveys themes of distinction, clarity, and separation, highlighting the process of comprehensively explaining or dividing for better understanding. مُفَصَّلَةٌ reflects the root’s emphasis on clarity and structure, often applied to texts, information, or subjects that require detailed elaboration.",
  "3782": "مُفْتَرٍ and related words stem from the root ف-ر-ي, with the root verb فَرَىٰ meaning \"he cut,\" \"he cleaved,\" or \"he fabricated.\" مُفْتَرٍ means \"one who fabricates\" or \"one who forges lies,\" particularly in a deceptive manner. Broader root meanings emphasize the act of cutting or reshaping, likening fabrication to metaphorically \"cutting into\" the truth and distorting it into falsehood. The connection lies in actively crafting and reshaping facts into misleading constructs, emphasizing the moral and social harm caused by deceit.",
  "3783": "مُفْتَرَيَاتٍ and related words stem from the root ف-ر-ي, with the root verb فَرَىٰ meaning \"he cut,\" \"he cleaved,\" or \"he fabricated.\" مُفْتَرَيَاتٍ is the plural passive form of مُفْتَرًى, meaning \"fabricated lies,\" \"falsehoods,\" or \"forgeries.\" Broader root meanings emphasize the act of cutting or shaping, likening fabrications to the severing or reshaping of truth. The connection lies in representing multiple instances of falsehoods created deceptively.",
  "3784": "مُفْتَرًى and related words stem from the root ف-ر-ي, with the root verb فَرَىٰ meaning \"he cut,\" \"he cleaved,\" or \"he fabricated.\" مُفْتَرًى is a passive form meaning \"fabricated,\" \"forged,\" or \"falsely created.\" Broader root meanings highlight the idea of cutting and reshaping, with مُفْتَرًى describing something that has been subjected to fabrication, often with the intent to deceive. The connection lies in being the object of distortion, where the truth has been metaphorically severed and manipulated into something false, highlighting the destructive consequences of such fabrications.",
  "3785": "مُفْتَرَيَاتٍ and related words stem from the root ف-ر-ي, with the root verb فَرَىٰ meaning \"he cut,\" \"he cleaved,\" or \"he fabricated.\" مُفْتَرَيَاتٍ is a passive form meaning \"fabricated\" or \"forged.\" Broader root meanings highlight the concept of cutting or crafting, emphasizing how fabrications metaphorically sever truth and reshape it into falsehood.",
  "3786": "مُفْرَطُونَ and related words stem from the root ف-ر-ط, with the root verb فَرَطَ meaning \"he went ahead\" or \"he exceeded bounds.\" أَفْرَطَ means \"he caused to exceed\" or \"he was immoderate.\" مُفْرَطُونَ, in its passive form, means \"those who are sent ahead\" or \"those made to precede,\" capturing the idea of being driven forward or advanced beyond a limit. The term reflects the root's themes of excess, haste, or surpassing boundaries, whether intentionally or as a consequence of neglect or error. This highlights a state of being propelled forward, often with negative implications, emphasizing the importance of balance and restraint.",
  "3787": "مُفْسِدُونَ and related words stem from the root ف-س-د, with the root verb فَسَدَ meaning \"it became corrupt,\" \"it spoiled,\" or \"it deteriorated.\" مُفْسِدُونَ means \"corrupters\" or \"ones who cause corruption.\" The connection lies in the role of actively spreading disorder, directly relating to the root's emphasis on decay. This term identifies those who disrupt harmony and righteousness, serving as a caution against actions leading to moral degradation.",
  "3788": "مُفْلِحُونَ and related words stem from the root ف-ل-ح, with the root verb فَلَحَ meaning \"he cleaved\" or \"he succeeded.\" مُفْلِحُونَ means \"successful ones\" or \"prosperous persons.\" The connection highlights someone who attains success, reflecting the root's concept of achievement and prosperity. This term often describes those who are spiritually successful, having achieved salvation and divine approval.",
  "3789": "مُقامٌ and related words stem from the root ق-و-م, with the root verb قامَ meaning \"he stood\" or \"he rose.\" The root encompasses concepts of standing, residing, and remaining. مُقامٌ means \"residence,\" \"abode,\" or \"place of staying.\" It refers to the place where one resides or remains standing. The connection lies in the idea of standing or staying in a particular location, reflecting the root's emphasis on establishment and stability. It highlights the significance of one's dwelling as a place of permanence and presence.",
  "3790": "مُقامَةٌ and related words stem from the root ق-و-م, with the root verb قامَ meaning \"he stood\" or \"he rose.\" The root conveys concepts of standing, gathering, and establishing. مُقامَةٌ can mean \"assembly,\" \"session,\" or \"gathering.\" The connection lies in people standing together in an assembly or gathering for a purpose. It reflects the root's emphasis on uprightness and the establishment of communal bonds. In literature, مُقامَةٌ refers to a genre involving eloquent storytelling, where the narrator \"stands\" to deliver a tale, highlighting the art of oration and presence.",
  "3791": "مُقَدَّسٌ and related words stem from the root ق-د-س, with the root verb قَدَّسَ meaning \"he purified,\" \"he sanctified,\" or \"he consecrated.\" مُقَدَّسٌ is a passive form meaning \"sanctified,\" \"made holy,\" or \"consecrated.\" The root conveys purification, elevation, and the act of setting apart for a sacred purpose. This term emphasizes the transformation or designation of something as sacred, highlighting its separation from the ordinary. It reflects the idea of purity being bestowed upon something, elevating it to a status of reverence and sanctity.",
  "3792": "مُقَدَّسَةٌ and related words stem from the root ق-د-س, with the root verb قَدَّسَ meaning \"he purified,\" \"he sanctified,\" or \"he consecrated.\" مُقَدَّسَةٌ is a passive form meaning \"sanctified,\" \"made holy,\" or \"consecrated.\" The root emphasizes themes of purification and elevation. This term often refers to sacred lands or places, highlighting their divinely ordained purity and reverence. It highlights the concept of certain spaces being elevated above the ordinary, reflecting their unique connection to sanctity and divine purpose.",
  "3793": "مُقَرَّبُونَ and related words stem from the root ق-ر-ب, with the root verb قَرَّبَ meaning \"he brought near\" or \"he offered.\" مُقَرَّبُونَ is a passive form meaning \"ones who are brought near\" or \"favored,\" emphasizing someone granted close proximity in rank, honor, or spiritual status. Broader root meanings highlight nearness, approach, and connection, whether physical or metaphorical. The connection lies in embodying the act of bringing closer, signifying elevation or privilege bestowed upon an individual, particularly in the context of closeness to Allah (ﷻ) or positions of honor.",
  "3794": "مُقَرَّنِينَ and related words stem from the root ق-ر-ن, with the root verb قَرَنَ meaning \"he coupled\" or \"he joined.\" قَرَّنَ means \"he bound together.\" مُقَرَّنِينَ is a passive form meaning \"bound together\" or \"chained.\" The connection lies in the state of being tightly connected or confined, emphasizing restriction and mutual dependence. Broader root meanings suggest a process of binding, unifying, or forcing together, symbolizing the idea of things being inseparably connected, whether through necessity or compulsion.",
  "3795": "الْمُقَسِّمَاتُ and related words stem from the root ق-س-م, with the root verb قَسَمَ meaning \"he divided.\" قَسَّمَ means \"he distributed extensively,\" and الْمُقَسِّمَاتُ refers to \"those who divide\" or \"distributors,\" emphasizing active participation in the process of division or allocation. The connection lies in the deliberate and equitable apportionment of resources, duties, or responsibilities. In the Qur'an, it refers to angels tasked with dividing and executing Allah’s (ﷻ) commands, such as distributing provisions, managing natural phenomena like rain, or carrying out divine decrees. It highlights themes of balance and precision, reflecting the importance of orderly execution in maintaining harmony and fulfilling divine will.",
  "3796": "مُقَصِّرِينَ and related words stem from the root ق-ص-ر, with the root verb قَصَرَ meaning \"he shortened,\" \"he limited,\" or \"he confined.\" قَصَّرَ carries meanings such as \"he made short\" or \"he fell short,\" encompassing both the physical act of shortening and the metaphorical idea of negligence or incompleteness. مُقَصِّرِينَ refers to \"ones who shorten,\" often applied to those who physically shorten something, such as trimming hair, or metaphorically, to those who fall short or limit themselves in action. The root emphasizes both the act of reducing in length and the concept of restraint, highlighting themes of moderation, physical change, or moral shortcomings depending on context.",
  "3797": "مُقَنْطَرَةٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ن-ط-ر, with the root verb قَنْطَرَ meaning \"he tied, or knit, the thing and vaulted it and made it firm, or strong.\" مُقَنْطَرَةٌ means \"amassed\" or \"heaped up,\" particularly in reference to wealth or resources. The emphasis on tying and binding in the root highlights the effort and care involved in gathering and securing wealth. The term suggests not just the physical accumulation but also the deliberate organization and consolidation of resources, reflecting human aspirations toward permanence and control. This reinforces the broader theme of wealth as a symbol of stability and strength, as well as a test of one's priorities and values.",
  "3798": "مُقِيتٌ and related words stem from the root ق-و-ت, with the root verb قَاتَ meaning \"he fed, nourished, or sustained,\" specifically with provisions sufficient to maintain life. مُقِيتٌ means \"a giver of food, nourishment, or sustenance,\" reflecting the act of sustaining and supporting. ٱلْمُقِيتُ, one of Allah’s (ﷻ) perfect names, is best understood as \"The Preserver,\" emphasizing His comprehensive role in preserving creation through His provision of every form of nourishment—physical, spiritual, and emotional. This name highlights Allah’s (ﷻ) meticulous care and oversight, ensuring every creature is sustained and protected according to its needs, aligning with the root’s essence of maintaining and upholding life.",
  "3799": "مُقِيمٌ and related words stem from the root ق-و-م, with the root verb قامَ meaning \"he stood\" or \"he rose.\" Derived from أَقامَ, meaning \"he established\" or \"he caused to stand,\" مُقِيمٌ means \"one who establishes,\" \"maintains,\" \"resident,\" \"enduring,\" or \"lasting.\" It reflects the root’s emphasis on stability, continuity, and steadfastness, whether in maintaining prayer, residing, or embodying permanence. Spiritually, مُقِيمٌ often describes someone who establishes acts of worship with dedication and consistency. It also conveys enduring states, such as unchanging blessings or lasting conditions, which can be either positive, like eternal bliss, or negative, such as unending punishment.",
  "3800": "مُقْتَحِمٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ح-م, with the root verb قَحَمَ meaning \"he plunged,\" \"he rushed headlong,\" or \"he entered recklessly.\" مُقْتَحِمٌ means \"one who rushes in,\" \"one who forcefully enters,\" or \"one who plunges forward.\" The root conveys themes of boldness, forceful entry, or reckless action, often implying a lack of foresight or a sense of urgency. This term reflects the act of entering into something difficult, dangerous, or overwhelming, whether physically or metaphorically. It highlights the determination or recklessness of one who forces their way forward, highlighting the consequences of such actions when undertaken without consideration or guidance.",
  "3801": "مُقْتَدُونَ and related words stem from the root ق-د-و, with the root verb قَدَا meaning \"he followed,\" \"he emulated,\" or \"he took as an example.\" مُقْتَدُونَ refers to \"those who follow,\" \"followers,\" or \"imitators,\" emphasizing the act of actively adhering to or emulating the example of another. The root conveys themes of imitation, adherence, and walking in the footsteps of someone else, whether the guidance being followed is correct or misguided. This term highlights the significant influence of leadership and role models, as followers may adopt the path of those they emulate, whether leading to righteousness or deviation.",
  "3802": "مُقْتَدِرٌ and related words stem from the root ق-د-ر, with the root verb قَدَرَ meaning \"he measured,\" \"he determined,\" or \"he had power over.\" مُقْتَدِرٌ means \"one who is capable,\" \"powerful,\" or \"possessing great ability,\" emphasizing mastery, control, and authority. ٱلْمُقْتَدِرُ, one of Allah’s (ﷻ) perfect and beautiful names, means \"The Supreme Power\" or \"The All-Powerful,\" signifying Allah’s (ﷻ) unmatched authority and absolute control over all creation. The root conveys themes of precise determination, measurement, and ultimate power, reflecting Allah’s (ﷻ) ability to govern, direct, and sustain all matters with perfection. ",
  "3803": "مُقْتَرِفُونَ and related words stem from the root ق-ر-ف, with the root verb قَرَفَ meaning \"he peeled off\" or \"he scraped.\" مُقْتَرِفُونَ means \"those who commit\" or \"perpetrators,\" especially of sin. The connection lies in how sins metaphorically strip away moral integrity, exposing corruption. Just as peeling removes protective layers, those who commit sin erode their character with each wrong action, emphasizing the destructive impact of repeated wrongdoings and how choices shape one’s moral foundation.",
  "3804": "مُقْتَرِنِينَ and related words stem from the root ق-ر-ن, with the root verb قَرَنَ meaning \"he coupled\" or \"he joined.\" اقْتَرَنَ means \"he was associated with\" or \"he became connected.\" مُقْتَرِنِينَ means \"those who are associated\" or \"connected.\" The connection lies in the intentional association or companionship, reflecting how relationships, whether positive or negative, influence one’s life journey. The broader root meanings emphasize joining, linking, or binding, illustrating the act of bringing together, either through conscious choice or circumstance.",
  "3805": "مُقْتَسِمِينَ and related words stem from the root ق-س-م, with the root verb قَسَمَ meaning \"he divided.\" اِقْتَسَمَ means \"he divided among themselves.\" مُقْتَسِمِينَ means \"one who divides for himself\" or \"apportioner.\" The connection emphasizes self-involvement in division, sometimes with a negative connotation of selfishness or manipulation. In the Qur'an, it warns against those who divide divine revelations, accepting parts and rejecting others.",
  "3806": "مُقْتَصِدٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ص-د, with the root verb قَصَدَ meaning \"he intended.\" اِقْتَصَدَ means \"he was moderate,\" and مُقْتَصِدٌ refers to \"a moderate person\" or \"one who adopts a middle course.\" The connection lies in the conscious choice to avoid extremes and embrace balance in thought and behavior. This term emphasizes moderation as a principle of living, encouraging steadiness and a measured approach in all aspects of life, whether physical, emotional, or spiritual.",
  "3807": "مُقْتَصِدَةٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ص-د, with the root verb قَصَدَ meaning \"he intended.\" مُقْتَصِدَةٌ means \"a moderate woman\" or \"one who adopts a middle course,\" embodying the values of balance and purposeful intent. The connection lies in embracing moderation as a universal virtue, reflecting the deliberate effort to maintain equilibrium in actions, thoughts, and decisions. This term highlights the significance of steadiness and restraint, promoting righteousness and thoughtful living as essential qualities.",
  "3808": "مُقْتِرٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ت-ر, with the root verb قَتَرَ meaning \"he was stingy.\" أَقْتَرَ means \"he was or became poor,\" and مُقْتِرٌ means \"poor\" or \"needy.\" The connection to stinginess lies in the shared theme of scarcity and limitation. While poverty reflects a state of lacking due to external conditions, stinginess reflects a self-imposed withholding that mirrors poverty in its effects. مُقْتِرٌ emphasizes the constricted state, illustrating how stinginess or deprivation, whether self-inflicted or circumstantial, leads to a lack of growth and opportunity.",
  "3809": "مُقْرِنِينَ and related words stem from the root ق-ر-ن, with the root verb قَرَنَ meaning \"he coupled,\" or \"he joined.\" مُقْرِنِينَ means \"those who are capable\" or \"those who have the ability to manage or control.\" It reflects the idea of bringing together or binding something with mastery, often signifying strength and capability. In a broader sense, the root emphasizes not just joining but also the ability to manage or harness what is joined. In the Qur'an, it highlights human dependence on Allah’s (ﷻ) facilitation, highlighting that without His help, such mastery or capability would be unattainable.",
  "3810": "مُقْسِطِينَ and related words stem from the root ق-س-ط, with the root verb قَسَطَ meaning \"he was unjust,\" while أَقْسَطَ means \"he acted justly.\" مُقْسِطِينَ refers to \"those who act justly,\" emphasizing fairness and the deliberate promotion of justice. ٱلْمُقْسِطُ, one of Allah’s (ﷻ) perfect names, means \"The Just\" or \"The Equitable,\" signifying His absolute and flawless justice in all judgments. This name reflects Allah’s (ﷻ) perfect equity, ensuring every reward and punishment is dispensed with complete fairness. It serves as a reminder to embody justice and fairness in all actions, striving to reflect Allah’s (ﷻ) attribute of justice in our dealings with others.",
  "3811": "مُقْمَحُونَ and related words stem from the root ق-م-ح, with the root verb قَمَحَ meaning \"he raised his head and held it back\" or \"he was restrained from lowering it.\" مُقْمَحُونَ is a passive form meaning \"those whose heads are raised up\" or \"held back.\" The connection lies in the vivid imagery of someone whose head is forcibly raised and unable to lower, symbolizing arrogance, stubbornness, or being restrained from perceiving or progressing forward, aligning with the root's theme of restriction and limitation.",
  "3812": "مُقْنِعِي and related words stem from the root ق-ن-ع, with the root verb قَنِعَ meaning \"he was content,\" \"he was satisfied,\" or \"he accepted,\" and قَنَعَ meaning \"he raised up\" or \"he held upright.\" مُقْنِعِي means \"raised up,\" often referring to heads lifted in attentiveness, expectation, or helplessness. The connection to قَنِعَ reflects acceptance of circumstances, while قَنَعَ conveys vigilance and anticipation. This term captures the duality of striving for readiness while acknowledging dependence, symbolizing alertness and submission in situations requiring heightened awareness.",
  "3813": "مُكاءٌ and related words stem from the root م-ك-و, with the root verb مَكَا meaning \"he whistled\" or \"he made a whistling sound.\" مُكاءٌ specifically refers to \"whistling.\" The root extends to encompass the idea of producing distinctive, sharp sounds often associated with signaling, attracting attention, or creating rhythm. In classical usage, مُكاءٌ conveys the action of deliberate sound-making, reflecting a purposeful act of emitting sound to communicate, draw notice, or create a specific auditory effect. The connection highlights the root's focus on intentionality and the distinctiveness of the sound produced, emphasizing the role of whistling as a means of expression or signaling in its various contexts.",
  "3814": "مُكَذِّبُونَ and related words stem from the root ك-ذ-ب, with the root verb كَذَبَ meaning \"he lied,\" \"he spoke falsely,\" or \"he gave an untrue account.\" كَذَّبَ expands this meaning to \"he denied,\" \"he rejected,\" or \"he accused (someone) of lying.\" مُكَذِّبُونَ means \"ones who deny,\" \"ones who reject,\" or \"ones who accuse of lying,\" referring to those actively engaged in rejecting or discrediting truth. The root conveys themes of fabricating falsehood and denying authenticity, and مُكَذِّبُونَ highlights a deliberate, persistent role in opposing truth. This term highlights the active stance of rejecting reality or truth, portraying a state of willful opposition to moral or factual correctness.",
  "3815": "مُكَرَّمَةٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ر-م, with the root verbs كَـرُمَ meaning \"he or it was highly esteemed, valued, precious, or rare,\" and كَرَّمَ meaning \"he honored greatly\" or \"he ennobled.\" مُكَرَّمَةٌ is a passive form meaning \"honored\" or \"ennobled.\" It describes someone or something elevated in status or treated with profound respect and dignity. The root emphasizes recognizing intrinsic worth and granting elevated status. In the Qur'an, it appears in صُحُفٍ مُكَرَّمَةٍ, referring to scriptures of exceptional honor, revered and graced with elevated status. This term highlights the importance of valuing and honoring what is sacred, rare, or inherently worthy of respect.",
  "3816": "مُكَلِّبِينَ and related words stem from the root ك-ل-ب, with the root verbs كَلِبَ, meaning \"he was greedy\" or \"he became rabid,\" and كَلَّبَ, meaning \"he trained a dog to hunt.\" مُكَلِّبِينَ refers to \"trainers of hunting animals,\" skilled in preparing predatory creatures like dogs or falcons for hunting. The root connects to controlling and refining natural instincts, transforming an animal's voracity or predatory nature into disciplined, purposeful hunting. This term emphasizes the collaborative relationship between humans and animals, requiring effort and skill to train hunting animals to obey commands and perform tasks effectively, reflecting persistence, loyalty, and potential greed in hunting.",
  "3817": "مُكِبٌّ and related words stem from the root ك-ب-ب, with the root verb كَبَّ meaning \"he threw down\" or \"he overturned.\" مُكِبٌّ means \"turned downward\" or \"one who is lowered.\" The connection lies in the idea of being inclined downward, reflecting the root's concept of inversion or subjugation. It highlights a state of being humbled, overpowered, or subdued. In spiritual contexts, it refers to the image of someone walking with their head down, symbolizing a loss of direction, guidance, or uprightness, while also metaphorically reflecting a state of misguidance, with one's actions leading them to stumble or falter.",
  "3818": "مُكْثٌ and related words stem from the root م-ك-ث, with the root verb مَكَثَ meaning \"he remained\" or \"he lingered.\" مُكْثٌ means \"a period of waiting,\" \"delay,\" or \"duration.\" The connection lies in the extension of time spent in a state of waiting, reflecting the root's concept of lingering. It highlights the temporal aspect of patience and the passage of time.",
  "3819": "مُكْرَمِينَ and related words stem from the root ك-ر-م, with the root verbs كَـرُمَ meaning \"he or it was highly esteemed, valued, precious, or rare,\" and كَرَّمَ meaning \"he honored greatly\" or \"he ennobled.\" مُكْرَمِينَ is a passive form meaning \"honored\" or \"ones who are treated generously.\" It refers to individuals who are recipients of honor, emphasizing their elevated and esteemed status. The connection to the root lies in the recognition of their value or rarity, as they are treated with the dignity befitting something precious. In the Qur'an, مُكْرَمِينَ often describes angels or individuals elevated by Allah (ﷻ), highlighting their exceptional status and the transformative nature of divine generosity.",
  "3820": "مُكْرِمٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ر-م, with the root verbs كَـرُمَ meaning \"he or it was highly esteemed, valued, precious, or rare,\" and كَرَّمَ meaning \"he honored greatly\" or \"he ennobled.\" مُكْرِمٌ means \"one who honors\" or \"one who is generous.\" It describes a person who actively bestows honor, respect, and generosity upon others. The connection to the root lies in the idea of recognizing and elevating the inherent worth or preciousness in others, treating them with dignity and value. It represents a source of upliftment, reflecting the responsibility to grant dignity, acknowledge the rare and esteemed qualities in others, and inspire moral excellence.",
  "3821": "مُلاقٍ and related words stem from the root ل-ق-ي, with the root verb لَقِيَ meaning \"he met,\" \"he encountered,\" or \"he found.\" مُلاقٍ means \"one who meets\" or \"meeting,\" emphasizing someone actively engaging in meeting others. The term often carries a sense of inevitability or destiny in meetings, such as meeting one's fate or meeting Allah (ﷻ). The connection to the root highlights the continuous or imminent nature of encounters, focusing on the individual's role in approaching significant meetings.",
  "3822": "مُلاقُوا and related words stem from the root ل-ق-ي, with the root verb لَقِيَ meaning \"he met,\" \"he encountered,\" or \"he found.\" مُلاقُوا means \"those who meet\" or \"meeting.\" It refers to groups of individuals actively engaging in meetings or encounters. The connection lies in the collective aspect of meeting, emphasizing shared experiences or common destinies, such as communities meeting their outcomes or collectively facing consequences. This expands the root's concept by highlighting the communal dimensions of encounters.",
  "3823": "مُلَاقِيًا and related words stem from the root ل-ق-ي, with the root verb لَقِيَ meaning \"he met,\" \"he encountered,\" or \"he found.\" مُلَاقِيًا means \"one who meets\" or \"meeting,\" often used in construct form to indicate \"the one who meets\" something specific. The connection emphasizes the direct involvement of the individual in the act of meeting, particularly in relation to a specific object or event. It highlights the personal aspect of encounters, reflecting the root's focus on interactions that are significant and transformative, highlighting the importance of the individual's role in approaching meaningful engagements.",
  "3824": "مُلِئَتْ and related words stem from the root م-ل-أ, with the root verb مَلَأَ meaning \"he filled.\" مُلِئَتْ is a passive form meaning \"it was filled,\" reflecting the state of being made full by an external agent. This highlights a key aspect of the root: the emphasis on the resulting state of fullness or completion, whether in physical objects or metaphorical contexts like ideas, emotions, or knowledge. The word captures the transformation from emptiness to abundance, highlighting the root’s broader themes of fulfillment and completion.",
  "3825": "مُلِيمٌ and related words stem from the root ل-و-م, with the root verb لَامَ meaning \"he blamed,\" \"he reproached,\" or \"he censured,\" and أَلَامَ meaning \"he committed a blameworthy act\" or \"he became culpable.\" مُلِيمٌ means \"one who commits blameworthy acts,\" \"culpable,\" or \"deserving blame.\" The connection lies in performing actions that warrant censure, directly relating to the root’s concept of blame. It emphasizes personal responsibility and moral accountability, focusing on the nature of actions that lead to blame. Unlike مَلُومٌ, which centers on being the recipient of blame, مُلِيمٌ highlights the act of wrongdoing and the individual’s role in incurring blame, reflecting the active dimensions of the root.",
  "3826": "مُلْتَحَدٌ and related words stem from the root ل-ح-د, with the root verb لَحَدَ meaning \"he inclined\" or \"he turned aside.\" مُلْتَحَدٌ specifically means \"refuge\" or \"place of retreat,\" emphasizing the act of deliberately seeking shelter or a position of safety. The connection to the root lies in the idea of inclining away from danger or toward a place of security, reflecting both physical movement and the deeper sense of choosing a path of safety during distress.",
  "3827": "مُلْقِينَ and related words stem from the root ل-ق-ي, with the root verb لَقِيَ meaning \"he met,\" \"he encountered,\" or \"he found.\" مُلْقِينَ means \"those who throw\" or \"those who cast,\" emphasizing the individuals actively engaged in casting or throwing something. The root conveys themes of intentional interaction, projection, or engagement. Similarly, مُلْقُونَ refers to \"throwing,\" describing the act itself or the ongoing performance of casting. Both words emphasize deliberate and purposeful actions, reflecting impactful encounters or events.",
  "3828": "الْمُلْقِيَاتُ and related words stem from the root ل-ق-ي, with the root verb لَقِيَ meaning \"he met,\" \"he encountered,\" or \"he found.\" أَلْقَى means \"he threw,\" \"he cast,\" or \"he presented.\" الْمُلْقِيَاتُ refers to \"those who throw,\" \"those who cast,\" or \"those who bring down.\" This term is understood as describing entities, such as winds or angels, that perform the act of delivering, casting down, or presenting something. The root reflects themes of intentional interaction and projection, emphasizing purposeful actions that lead to an encounter or the presentation of something to be received.",
  "3829": "مُلْكٌ and related words stem from the root م-ل-ك, with the root verb مَلَكَ meaning \"he possessed,\" \"he ruled,\" or \"he governed.\" مُلْكٌ means \"sovereignty,\" \"dominion,\" or \"kingdom,\" signifying the authority to rule over a domain. The connection lies in the power and mastery involved in governance, whether on a worldly or divine scale. It reflects the temporary nature of human sovereignty compared to Allah’s (ﷻ) eternal dominion, encouraging believers to place trust in His ultimate authority over all matters.",
  "3830": "مُمَدَّدَةٌ and related words stem from the root م-د-د, with the root verb مَدَّ meaning \"he extended,\" \"he stretched,\" or \"he prolonged.\" مُمَدَّدَةٌ means \"extended,\" \"stretched out,\" or \"prolonged.\" The root conveys the idea of elongation or expansion, and مُمَدَّدَةٌ highlights the result of this process, emphasizing something spread extensively or made continuous. This term can signify the idea of vastness or thoroughness, illustrating how the root’s concept of stretching applies to physical or metaphorical states of being made expansive or enduring.",
  "3831": "مُمَرَّدٌ and related words stem from the root م-ر-د, with the root verb مَرَدَ meaning \"it was smooth\" or \"it was bare.\" مُمَرَّدٌ is a passive form meaning \"made smooth,\" \"polished,\" or \"leveled.\" The connection lies in the idea of being stripped of roughness or irregularities, resulting in a smooth, refined surface. This reflects the root's concept of stripping away, emphasizing transformation towards refinement and purity, as seen in the description of structures made smooth and elegant.",
  "3832": "مُمَزَّقٌ and related words stem from the root م-ز-ق, with the root verb مَزَّقَ meaning \"he tore\" or \"he tore to pieces.\" مُمَزَّقٌ means \"torn,\" \"ripped apart,\" or \"shredded.\" The root conveys dimensions of tearing into pieces, breaking apart, scattering, and dispersal, often implying a state of complete and irreparable separation. مُمَزَّقٌ describes the condition of something that has been thoroughly torn apart and dispersed, symbolizing the disintegration of what was once whole. This includes both physical tearing and metaphorical meanings, such as the scattering of unity, the collapse of cohesion, or the dissolution of order. The word highlights themes of fragmentation, dispersal, and the permanent breakdown of structure or stability, reflecting the root’s broader meanings of destruction and loss."
};
